<SLUG> BC-Kosovo's Die-Hards,0545 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defeats have not sapped spirit of Kosovo guerrillas
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo PRI102-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MALISEVO, Yugoslavia (AP) _ While an unrelenting push has put
Serb special forces within earshot of some rebel outposts, the
guerillas in dusty villages in central Kosovo shrug off their
recent defeats.
	   ``We might have lost some battles, but we will win the war,''
Agim Kuci, the lanky commander of Kosovo Liberation Army forces in
southwest Kosovo, said Friday. ``We have founded an army that will
free all of Kosovo and is prepared to die for it!''
	   A string of defeats for the ethnic Albanian militants, fighting
to wrest control of Kosovo province from Serbia, culminated last
weekend in the fall of Junik, a village near Albania and their main
organizational, logistical and weapons-distribution center.
	   With the rebels also on the defensive in the central Drenica
region, the cradle of their insurgency, the territory they control
has shrunk dramatically.
	   Plumes of smoke drifted into the sky Friday above Drenica.
Houses were burning in villages taken long ago by the Serbs,
evidence to the Kosovo fighters that their enemy wanted to destroy,
not just defeat, the province's Albanian community.
	   In Malisevo, once a main rebel center, the roads were filled
with armored vehicles of the army of Serb-dominated Yugoslavia.
	   The start of enemy-held territory begins southwest of town,
where a checkpoint is manned by ethnic Albanians with submachine
guns. Some are dressed in camouflage uniforms bearing the black
eagle emblem of their guerrilla movement.
	   Their regional headquarters is little more than a mile away in a
village they refuse to identify for security reasons.
	   There, Kuci, the KLA commander, explained why he thinks the
Serbs face ultimate defeat, despite overwhelming firepower.
	   ``They are throwing in everything they have _ planes, tanks,
artillery, heavy machine guns _ to gain just a tiny bit of
ground,'' he says. ``That's not something they will be able to
sustain. In time, we will see their forces diminishing, even as our
forces gain in strength.''
	   The numbers are indeed on the KLA's side.
	   Kosovo is in Serbia, the dominant Yugoslav republic. Ethnic
Albanians make up more than 90 percent of the province's
population, forcing the Serbs to bring in forces from the rest of
Serbia. Many are reluctant to fight.
	   But the guerrillas can recruit from a large pool of young and
enthusiastic homegrown supporters. Adem Demaci, the KLA political
spokesman, said Friday that the KLA force has grown to 30,000 in
recent weeks.
	   He said the Serb crackdown has turned an untested force into
``an experienced army which no longer knows fear and can easily
fight the Serbs'' through guerrilla tactics ``much more dangerous''
than classic warfare.
	   Many of the dozens of fighters sighted during a tour of the
region southwest of Malisevo were in their teens or early 20s.
Their weapons were old Kalashnikov submachine guns or Chinese-made
bolt-action rifles smuggled from Albania. But their enthusiasm was
high.
	   ``I left my wife in Switzerland to come back and fight,'' said
Bekhim Hajdari, 28. ``And I will die for my homeland if I need
to.''
</TEXT>
