<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-US-Diplomatic Tightrope,0662 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan distances itself from U.S. strikes _ but not too far
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By DONNA BRYSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan's precarious position was
never clearer than on the dark, rainy night when the missiles of
one ally roared across its skies to strike the territory of
another.
	   In the morning light, Pakistani officials carefully navigated a
middle course, distancing itself from the United States without
straying too close to Afghanistan.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton said the attacks on Afghanistan as
well as Sudan Thursday were aimed at rooting out extremist
violence, personified in Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden, who is
convinced America threatens Islam. Bin Laden is accused of
directing worldwide attacks from hide-outs in Afghanistan .
	   ``Irrespective of the motive of these strikes,'' Pakistani
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz told his senate Friday, ``the act of
violation of the sovereignty and territorial integrity of these
Islamic countries cannot but be a matter of grave concern to the
people of Pakistan who justifiably feel outraged.''
	   But Aziz was also quick to note his country's firm opposition
``to terrorism in all its manifestations.''
	   ``Clearly Pakistan is caught between two allies,'' said Maleeha
Lodhi, a former Pakistani ambassador to Washington. ``Whatever it
does there are costs. It's not an enviable position to be in.''
	   On terrorism, Pakistan has hinted at frustration with
Afghanistan's Taliban rulers.
	   In a recent interview with The Associated Press, Aziz said
Pakistan was trying to use its influence to persuade the Taliban to
adopt a more responsible international stance on terrorism.
	   ``People do overestimate our leverage on the Taliban,'' the
foreign minister added.
	   Some say Pakistan nurtured, if not created, the Taliban in hopes
that by influencing the course of Afghanistan, it would be a power
in central Asia. It is one of the few countries to recognize the
Taliban as the legitimate rulers of Afghanistan.
	   The United States has offered no such recognition to the
Taliban. While Washington and Islamabad differ sharply on
Afghanistan, they have been close partners in other areas, and
Washington is an important donor to this poor Islamic country.
	   In the 1980s, Pakistan and the United States supported Afghan
groups against Soviet invaders and a Moscow-installed government.
	   But when the communists were defeated, Washington began to worry
about the potential for terrorism brewing among war-hardened Arabs
who had come to the region to help the Afghans. At U.S. urging,
Pakistan expelled hundreds of the men known as Arab Afghans from
its Afghan border town of Peshawar.
	   In 1995, Pakistan extradited Ramzi Yusuf, the convicted
mastermind of the New York World Trade Center bombing and an Arab
Afghan, to the United States.
	   Two years later, Pakistan allowed U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation agents to operate on its soil, capturing Mir Aimal
Kasi and spiriting him back to the United States, where he was
convicted of murder in a 1993 shooting spree outside CIA
headquarters.
	   Each case sparked criticism _ sometimes violent _ in Pakistan.
Politicians here must answer to a vocal minority at home that often
portrays the United States as an enemy of Islam.
	   Already weakened by an economic crisis and other domestic
issues, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's government cannot afford to
appear to have abandoned an Islamic neighbor. Particularly one like
the Taliban, whose extreme form of Islam mirrors that of some of
the most prominent Islamist parties in Pakistan and could threaten
the government.
	   The specter of day after day of protests like the anti-American
demonstrations that erupted across Pakistan Friday is sobering to
anyone who wants to convince the outside world Pakistan is a safe
place to invest and visit _ and an image the government does not
want. 	   
</TEXT>
