<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAV-Indonesia-Timor Tourism,0944 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Troubled country tries to shed image as a war zone
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY303-305, AP Graphic TRV EAST TIMOR &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Goats meander through waist-high grass in
the ruins of an old Portuguese jail on East Timor's rugged, lonely
coast. Shrubs sprout from ledges of crumbling stone.
	   Yet, in this isolated place, an attendant diligently pulled out
a guest book for a couple of visitors to sign. The last scrawled
entry was six weeks old.
	   Tourists are few in East Timor, a former Portuguese colony riven
by conflict and short of facilities for travelers. Indonesia barred
most foreign visitors until 1989, 14 years after invading and
wiping out all but a few cells of armed resistance.
	   As political reform sweeps Indonesia, local officials hope
tensions will ease in East Timor, tempting foreign divers and
hikers to check out its coral reefs, white-sand beaches and rocky
hills.
	   Maybe people curious about the territory's troubled history will
come too, they say. Tens of thousands of people died in the 1970s
in fighting and ensuing famine and disease, sullying Indonesia's
image and prompting international sympathy for the East Timorese.
	   ``We can sell the war,'' says Basilio Araujo of the East Timor
Investment Coordinating Board, a local government division.
However, East Timor's fragile political situation is likely to
deter many tourists for now.
	   In recent weeks, Indonesian soldiers shot and killed two
pro-independence demonstrators and several thousand non-East
Timorese settlers fled the territory, complaining of harassment by
the indigenous population. Separatist rebels still hide out in the
mountains.
	   Despite the turbulence, momentum for dialogue is building,
fueled by Indonesia's withdrawal of some troops.
	   On Aug. 5, Portugal and Indonesia agreed to discuss granting
East Timor autonomy after two days of talks brokered by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan. The agreement calls for a solution by
the end of this year.
	   Annan described the deal as ``progress,'' but said it was not a
major breakthrough.
	   No mention was made of East Timorese demands for a referendum on
independence among the province's 800,000 people.
	   Indonesian President B.J. Habibie earlier ruled out independence
for East Timor, but offered a compromise that would entail a
measure of autonomy.
	   Jittery at times, Dili is usually a sleepy town. Palm trees,
rusting barges and a few Portuguese cannon line the waterfront.
Shops close their shutters for several hours every sweltering
afternoon and the streets empty.
	   Portuguese rose wine is cheap _ as is everything else with the
drastic devaluation of the Indonesian rupiah _ and seafood is
plentiful. The one-star Turismo and Mahkota hotels offer double
rooms for 110,500 rupiah (dlrs 8.50) a night.
	   Diners can choose a fish from a freezer at one simple restaurant
on the beach. The wait is lengthy: Many things, even the
mosquitoes, move at a leisurely pace in East Timor.
	   At the city's main marketplace, only a charred facade remains
after fire gutted the colonial-era building last year. Now colorful
tents and kiosks have sprung up amid the ruins.
	   Dili falls quiet at night. The only disco in town closed in the
tense days after soldiers fired on a crowd of pro-independence
demonstrators in 1991, killing dozens.
	   A few open-air, Spartan restaurants on the beach offer delicious
grilled fish and squid. A meal costs no more than a couple of
dollars.
	   A bottle of Portuguese-made Mateus rose wine costs 35,100 rupiah
(dlrs 2.70) in the hotel restaurants, less in the few stores that
offer it. Other wines are scarce.
	   One restaurant in Dili offering Portuguese food is Bidau Massau.
Pujasera restaurant offers dishes from the Indonesian island of
Java, and then there's the Rotterdam Steak House, which serves
steak.
	   A quarter-century ago, East Timor was a popular destination for
backpackers from neighboring Australia who stopped by on the way to
other Indonesian islands. About 1,000 foreigners with tourist visas
visited East Timor last year.
	   With Australian aid, officials now plan to renovate a handful of
Portuguese guest houses. In April, a diving company based in
Darwin, Australia, ferried eight tourists to East Timor's coral
reefs for the first time. Another trip is scheduled in November.
	   Eager for upbeat publicity, the governor's office still hands
out copies of a 1996 book extolling Indonesia's economic
development of impoverished East Timor in the wake of Portuguese
neglect. It comes complete with typographical errors.
	   ``The massage of the minister of home affairs,'' reads the title
of one introductory note.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; If You Go ...
	   GETTING THERE: There are no direct international flights to East
Timor. A roundtrip flight to the provincial capital of Dili from
the resort island of Bali on the national carrier Garuda costs
13,000 rupiah (dlrs 102). There is one flight a day. Bali is about
halfway between Jakarta, the capital of Indonesia, and Dili.
	   TOURS: Tours of East Timor can be organized through Sumaflo
Agung Tour and Travel, phone 62-390-21477 or 62-390-22477. Fax:
62-390-23066. (390 is the Dili code. If inside Indonesia, callers
should dial 0390).
	   TAXIS: Renting a taxi in Dili costs between 14,950 rupiah (dlrs
1.15) and 19,500 rupiah (dlrs 1.50) an hour. Haggling on the rate
for out-of-town trips is suggested.
	   INFORMATION: East Timor tourism officials can be reached at
62-811-384-631 (a cell phone: 62 is the country code). Fax.
62-390-21010, 62-390-23366.
</TEXT>
