<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAV-Wild Rapids-Tips,0297 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With TRAV-US-Wild Rapids
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	    &UR; If You Go ...
	   There are about two dozen whitewater rafting outfitters on the
Ocoee River in Tennessee. Prices vary depending on time of year and
day of the week. Expect to pay about dlrs 40 per person, and to pay
in advance. Many outfitters charge you a cancellation fee in case
you chicken out.
	   Here are few outfitters:
	   Ocoee Outdoors: 1-800-533-7767.
	   Southeastern Expeditions: 1-800-868-7232.
	   Quest Expeditions: 1-800-277-4537.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   There are a variety of choices for whitewater rafting in the
South, depending on what you are looking for and your expertise.
	   The Ocoee River: A fun river in Eastern Tennessee with Class III
and IV rapids that turn beginners into rafters out of necessity.
The five-mile (8-kilometer) trip takes anywhere from 1 1-2 and 2
hours as rafters drop 275 feet (84 meters). Children must be at
least 12 and since the river is dam-controlled, it runs 116 days a
year.
	   The Chattooga: This river along the Georgia-South Carolina
border became famous in the film ``Deliverance.'' It is a
challenging river that contains Class II-IV rapids.
	   Big Pigeon: Not as intense as the Chattooga or the Ocoee, it
gives adults an exciting ride on its upper part, and allows
children as young 6 to raft in the lower river.
	   The Nolichucky: Catch this deep-canyon river in Tennessee
between March and July when the river is at its highest and most
exiciting with Class III-IV rapids.
	   The Hiwassee: This is a multipurpose big river, known as much
for its trout fishing as for its leisurely rapids. It's perfect for
family outings. It's about 15 miles (24 kilometers) from the Ocoee.
</TEXT>
