<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Mass Graves </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian investigators visit more alleged mass grave sites
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALI KOTARUMALOS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEDAN, Indonesia (AP) _ After digging up eight sets of bones,
human rights workers headed Saturday to more sites in northern
Indonesia believed to contain the remains of people killed by the
military.
	   Indonesian troops are accused of committing atrocities,
including arbitrary killings and torture, during the late 1980s and
1990s in Aceh province on Sumatra island.
	   The soldiers were trying to put down separatist guerrillas who
were fighting for an Islamic state. The number of insurgents
dwindled under the crackdown, but resentment toward the Indonesian
military runs deep among many Acehnese.
	   On Friday, grieving widows and torture victims looked on as
investigators dug up bones from remote grave sites. Two skeletons
found at one spot had holes in their skulls, probably bullet
wounds, forensic doctors said.
	   Local residents said some of the victims were Muslim teachers.
	   A four-man team from Indonesia's National Human Rights
Commission and a group of volunteers with shovels were led to
several alleged mass graves by villagers.
	   The team said it was only taking samples of human remains from
several grave sites, which locals allege contain dozens of
skeletons.
	   ``We need evidence,'' the Kompas newspaper quoted chief
investigator Baharuddin Lopa as saying.
	   The bones will be subjected to forensic tests to determine
whether they were of execution victims, officials said. Mass
exhumations would be made later.
	   The investigation into the Aceh graves is the latest sign of a
new openness in Indonesia since former autocratic President Suharto
resigned after nationwide riots in May.
	   His successor, B.J. Habibie, has promised greater human rights
for Indonesia's 202 million people.
	   Indonesia's military commander, Gen. Wiranto, has also publicly
apologized for human rights violations in Aceh and ordered the
withdrawal of about 1,000 troops. However, thousands remain
deployed in Aceh, 1,750 kilometers (1,100 miles) northwest of
Jakarta.
</TEXT>
