</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Sweet Tooth </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Government orders soft-drink makers to reduce sugar
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Soft-drink manufacturers that
continue to heap extravagant amounts of sugar into their canned
drinks will be shut down, a newspaper reported Saturday.
	   Such companies have ignored the government's recently launched
``Less Sugar, Please'' nationwide campaign to reduce sugar in their
products, Health Minister Dr. Chua Jui Meng was reported as saying
by The Star daily.
	   About 600,000 people out of the country's population of 22
million suffer from diabetes, but some bottle drinks contain as
much as nine teaspoonfuls of sugar each, Chua said.
	   ``They showed no interest to voluntarily reducing the among of
sugar in soft drinks,'' he said, accusing profit-driven companies
of adding sugar to their products because they believe Malaysians
have a sweet tooth.
	   Soft-drinks manufacturers that refused to cut down on sugar will
have their licenses canceled, Chua warned.
	   Domestic sugar consumption has dropped 21 percent in the first
six months of this year, but industrial use of sugar had increased
by 15 percent in the same period.
	   Malaysians on average consume about 30 teaspoons of sugar a day
each in raw form or through processed food, double the amount
recommended by the ministry, Chua said.
</TEXT>
