<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Paraguay-No Honeymoon,0599 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Political honeymoon for Paraguay's new president lasted only days
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY108 &QL; 
 &UR; By PEDRO SERVIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) _ Talk about a short honeymoon.
	   Less than a week ago, Raul Cubas was inaugurated as Paraguay's
president. Now Cubas is facing calls for impeachment _ and even his
brothers disapprove of his fledgling administration.
	   The uproar stems from Cubas' decision to free Gen. Lino Oviedo,
a friend and former presidential candidate who was jailed last year
in the middle of the election campaign after a power struggle
within the long-ruling Colorado Party. Cubas took over the party's
nomination and won the presidency in elections in May.
	   The decision to free Oviedo has infuriated many in the party.
Congressional detractors have called for Cubas' removal from
office.
	   ``He (Cubas) freed the man that could begin a diabolical plan to
persecute everyone who he thinks is not with him,'' said lawmaker
Juan Carlos Galaverna.
	   Oviedo ran into trouble after former President Juan Carlos
Wasmosy demanded his resignation as the army's commander in 1996.
	   Oviedo refused, and not long after he won the Colorado Party's
presidential nomination in a September 1997 primary, he was brought
before a military tribunal and sentenced to 10 years in prison.
	   Cubas, who was the Colorado Party's vice presidential nominee,
became the presidential candidate after the Supreme Court upheld
Oviedo's prison term just weeks before the elections.
	   Cubas' campaign was largely seen as an extension of the vigorous
campaign run by Oviedo, who had traveled Paraguay's countryside
giving rousing speeches in the indigenous Guarani language.
	   ``Cubas is not really a leader and he doesn't have a strong
political base,'' political analyst Carlos Martini said.
	   Cubas took office Aug. 15 and gave a well-received economic
address last Monday. But the next day, Cubas signed a decree
overriding Oviedo's sentence.
	   Cubas said his decision shouldn't have come as a surprise.
Granting freedom to Oviedo was part of his campaign platform.
	   ``I've used the constitutional power given to presidents to
fulfill a campaign promise,'' he explained during a news conference
this week.
	   Hundreds of Oviedo supporters took to the streets upon hearing
of his release, shouting slogans such as ``President Lino!'' That
jubilation was not shared by other factions in the Colorado Party _
most notably Cubas' brothers.
	   ``I hope that in a moment of illumination my brother will annul
this decree,'' said Emilio Cubas, a former Colorado senator.
Another brother, Carlos Cubas, resigned as economic minister in
protest Tuesday.
	   Colorado Party members vowed to seek impeachment. But a vote to
start such proceedings would require a two-thirds majority in both
chambers of Congress to move forward.
	   Congressional members also asked the Supreme Court to rule on
the legality of Cubas' decision.
	   Many Paraguayans said political infighting would only distract
the country from solving its problems, including a protracted
economic crisis and an international image tarred by perceptions of
rampant corruption.
	   ``The people in power are always fighting and it's the people in
the streets that always have to pay,'' said Javier Benitez, a
35-year-old electrician.
	   Maribel Gomez, 17, agreed.
	   ``It's makes no difference to me whether Oviedo is in jail or
free,'' said Gomez, a student. ``I think the most important thing
the government needs to be doing is creating jobs.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Paraguay-No Honeymoon; CT:i; 
