<HEADER>
w1993 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Election     08-22 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rainsy says violence will not deter Cambodian opposition
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PHN101-102

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ After attending the funeral of a
grenade attack victim on Saturday, a defiant Sam Rainsy said
violence and threats will not weaken his resolve to expose last
month's Cambodian election as a farce.
	   ``I condemn all acts of violence,'' the opposition politician
said. ``But we should not be deterred by threats. We should
continue in our struggle.''
	   Late Thursday, several shots were fired and a grenade was thrown
at the Interior Ministry where Sam Rainsy and supporters were
protesting against alleged election irregularities.
	   Sieng Sean, a driver for Kyodo News, a Japanese news agency, was
killed. Sam Rainsy, who was several hundred meters (yards) away,
was unharmed.
	   Claiming he was the intended target of the attack, Sam Rainsy
said he would continue challenging the results of last month's
parliamentary elections.
	   On Saturday he handed out leaflets at markets, urging vendors to
attend a rally to protest election fraud at the Olympic Stadium
Sunday. Ten opposition parties will take part in the demonstration.
	   Sam Rainsy said he thought the purpose of the most recent round
of violence was to intimidate people into not attending the rally.
The attack also heightened his own security concerns, he said.
	   ``Of course one has to be always worried,'' he said as vendors
cautiously gathered around him.
	   ``Threats and blackmail are the most effective weapons of
dictators,'' he said. ``We cannot succumb to fear.''
	   After Thursday's attack, Sam Rainsy and his supporters were
questioned by police for about two hours inside the Interior
Ministry, often at gunpoint.
	   On state television Friday night, national police chief Hok
Lundy _ a close ally of Cambodian leader Hun Sen _ accused Sam
Rainsy of provoking the attack, and said he bears ultimate
responsibility for Sieng Sean's death.
	   He hinted that Sam Rainsy could be tried for Sieng Sean's death.
	   Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party won a slight majority in last
month's parliamentary elections, but not the two-thirds needed to
form a government.
	   Sam Rainsy's party and his opposition ally, Prince Norodom
Ranariddh's Funcinpec Party, together won 58 seats in the 122-seat
parliament.
	   They have been invited by Hun Sen to form a coalition government
but have so far refused, saying they will not recognize the
election results until allegations of irregularities in the voting
and counting process are investigated.
	   The National Election Committee has rejected most of the
opposition's complaints as ``baseless.'' The opposition has
appealed the findings to the Constitutional Council.
	   The opposition's persistence in challenging election results has
raised new concerns about political stability in Cambodia.
	   The London-based human rights group Amnesty International called
for restraint and calm among opposing political factions.
	   ``More violence is not going to solve Cambodia's current
political problems,'' Amnesty International said Saturday.
``Everyone involved in the political process has a responsibility
to prevent an escalation in tension.
	   ``It is in everyone's interest to ensure that the political
process _ already severely tainted _ does not descend even further
into violence,'' the rights group said. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Cambodia-Election; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
