APTV's comprehensive coverage of the aftermath of the U-S air
strikes against Afghanistan and Sudan includes the following items:
----
UN: BOMB REAX 2 - This APTV package includes comment from Sudan's
ambassador to the UN regarding his country's request to the Security
Council to sanction a fact-finding mission to investigate the U-S
missile attacks on Sudan and Afghanistan. (FIRST RUN EUROPE EARLY
0300GMT)
----
SUDAN: UPDATE - APTV has a wrap including daylight shots of the
attack site in Sudan and comment from the Sudanese President after a
Cabinet meeting.  (North America Update 1830 GMT)
----
PAKISTAN: REAX 4 - There's been an angry reaction in Islamabad to
the strikes. APTV has Pakistan's first official comment about the
strikes, plus anti-American demonstrations after Friday prayers.
Package includes latest pictures from Pakistan and comment from its
ambassador to the U-N. (North America Update 1830GMT)
---
US: DEFENSE - APTV package on the defense implications of the
bombing. Package  includes defence and terrorist analysts, voxpops
of concerned U-S citizens and pictures of security being stepped up
in Washington. (North America Late 1930GMT)
---
US: REAX - APTV has pictures of Friday prayers from a mosque in
Washington as well as comment from the Afghan Foundation, the
Islamic Institute, condemnation fro the Sudanese embassy and an
expert on the Taliban movement. (North America Late 1930GMT)
----
US: UN - Reaction from China which says it wishes the U-S had used
the proper U-N procedures before launching attacks on the Sudan and
Afghanistan. (North America Update 1830GMT)
----
US: WHITE HOUSE - APTV has a wrap of Sandy Berger, National Security
Council Adviser, and shots and comment from Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. (FIRST RUN NORTH AMERICA UPDATE 1830GMT)
---
US: CLINTON - President Bill Clinton leaves the Whitehouse for Martha's
Vineyard. He makes no comment. (First Run Latin America Update
2130GMT)
----
UN: BOMB REAX - APTV has comment from India's and China's
ambassadors to the United Nations concerning the missile strikes on
Sudan and Afghanistan. (First Run Australia/NZ 0000GMT)
----
LEADERS: REAX - APTV has a wrap of world leaders' reaction to the
bombing including Boris Yeltsin, Benjamin Netanyahu, Tony Blair and
Lionel Jospin. (North America Update 1830GMT)
---
KENYA: FREEH - APTV has coverage of the news conference held by FBI
Director Louis Freeh in Nairobi.  He told reporters that there was
not necessarily a direct linkage between the Embassy blasts and the
subsequent US air strikes.  (Freeh F-L-A-S-H 1650GMT)
----
EMBASSY: WRAP 2 - APTV has a wrap of scenes from U-S embassies
around the world in the wake of the U-S air strikes including
heightened security, tourists and vox pops. (FIRST RUN EUROVISION
1440GMT)
----
POSH SPICE: FILE British pop star ``Posh Spice'' Victoria Adams is
three months pregnant, according to press reports,  but is not
planning to leave the chart-topping Spice Girls. APTV has a file
package. (Asia Pacific Early 1945GMT )
----
PERU: CABINET -  President Alberto Fujimori named a new prime
minister and defense minister Friday as part of a shakeup of Peru's
political and military leaders that has also toppled its top
general. APTV will have shots of new minsters and reactions from the
street. (FIRST RUN EUROPE EARLY 0300GMT)
----
DOM REP: CARICOM -  Attending a 15-nation Caribbean summit starting
Friday, Cuban President Fidel Castro prepares to join the struggle
of small island states fighting for economic survival in an era of
increasingly global free trade. (Latin America Update 2130GMT)
----
MEXICO: PESO- APTV package on the Peso which has reached its lowest
level since devaluation in 1994. The package includes an interview
with an analyst and pictures of the Mexican stock exchange. (Latin
America Update 2130GMT)
----
COLOMBIA: ARREST-  One of South America's most wanted drug smugglers
has been captured by Colombian secret police in Bogota. Colombian
National Police held a press conference to confirm that Fernando
Florez was a leader of the Cali drug cartel. (Latin America 1900GMT)
----
MEXICO: DRIVING - A special driving school in Mexico is teaching
drivers 'James Bond' dare-devil skills to avoid possible kidnapping
and robbery. APTV reports. (Latin America 1900GMT)
