<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-US Bombings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysian press, officials condemn U.S. missile attacks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Calling the United States a
power-obsessed ``war maker,'' a widely-read Malaysian newspaper on
Saturday condemned America's missile attacks on Sudan and
Afghanistan.
	   ``Its action is nothing more than an international bully who
muscles its will on the whole world,'' said an editorial published
in the government-linked New Straits Times daily.
	   ``The mere suspicion that the groups were responsible for the
recent embassy attacks in Kenya and Tanzania does not warrant it to
take justice into its own hands,'' said the paper.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton's Thursday decision to strike a
purported chemical weapons plant in Sudan and suspected terrorist
targets in Afghanistan has drawn the ire of many officials in
Muslim-dominated Malaysia.
	   ``How are we to know it was done in self-defense when there is
no one to determine that?'' Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad told
reporters late Friday.
	   ``If I can decide where I want to attack, the world will be in
chaos,'' said Mahathir.
	   Mahathir has been waging a verbal war against foreign currency
traders, blaming them for destroying Asia's economic boom and
devaluing his nation's currency by more than 40 percent.
	   Malaysian activists also voiced their opposition.
	   ``It is hypocritical for the U.S. to accuse Sudan and
Afghanistan of supporting terrorism,'' said Mohamed Idris, chairman
of the Malaysian-based Third World Network.
	   Echoing remarks made by many Malaysian officials, Mohamed said
the United States had no right to impose its military might on
another nation. 	   
</TEXT>
