w2003 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Floods     08-22 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Floods </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Flooding displaces more than 1 million in northeast China
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOHN LEICESTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARBIN, China (AP) _ Days of surging river waters undermined a
dike protecting a provincial capital Saturday, forcing residents to
flee and adding to the swelling numbers of homeless from floods
devastating China.
	   Fearful for the safety of Harbin city's 9 million people,
military commanders sent frogmen into the raging Songhua River
Friday to plug the leaking levee. But foundations under a riverside
pumping station and apartment complex gave way overnight, state
television reported.
	   Nearby residents had to be evacuated, although the TV report
gave no figures. Video footage showed a crack running down the
two-story pumping station building, part of which sank 30
centimeters (a foot) into the soggy ground.
	   More than a million people in northeast China have been
displaced, their homes submerged by the Songhua and Nen rivers, the
official China Youth Daily reported.
	   Those refugees form a new batch of homeless left by China's
worst flooding in 44 years. Officials have said more than 2,000
people have died nationwide and millions left homeless. But those
numbers are two weeks old, before rains lashed the northeast.
	   Damage has been more widespread in central China. The Yangtze
River, China's longest, has stood above the emergency stage for
more than a month, weakening embankments. Rains along the Yangtze's
upper reaches have formed a new surge of high waters that is
expected to roar down the river over the next week.
	   Soldiers in Jiujiang city repaired a dike that burst two weeks
ago just before the last flood crest entered the area Thursday
night, the China Daily reported. The newspaper described the breach
as the worst accident of the flood season. Officials insisted there
were no casualties.
	   With local clinics and hospitals in many parts of the country
under water, health officials face a shortage of medicines and
equipment to check the outbreaks of diseases.
	   Health Minister Zhang Wenkang warned Friday that colds, stomach
illnesses, dysentery, hepatitis and diseases carried by waterborne
parasites are on the rise and the trend is likely to worsen over
the next three months, state media reported.
	   Relief officials are worried many flood victims in the
northeast, known in the West as Manchuria, may not be able to move
back into their homes before the onset of winter in mid-October,
the China Youth Daily said.
	   More than 230,000 soldiers and paramilitary police were now in
the northeast fighting the floods, the official Xinhua News Agency
reported.
	   Trucks brought more soldiers into Harbin, Heilongjiang's
provincial capital, on Saturday morning to reinforce the levee as
the Songhua River swelled to ever higher record levels.
	   ``As long as the dikes are all right, we are all right and our
homes are safe,'' read one banner in the city.
	   The rising Nen River, 150 kilometers (100 miles) to the
northwest, on Thursday night began spilling over a dike that formed
the last line of defense for the Daqing oil field and its nearby
city, newspapers said.
	   Flooding surrounded the oil field, China's largest, on three
sides, washed away a highway and inundated nearly half the area's
farmland.
	   With 1,443 oil wells swamped and 282 of them shut down, oil
workers struggled to maintain production, the Xinhua News Agency
said.
	   More threatening to the oil field was a brimming reservoir on
its eastern edge.
	   ``If the weather gods don't smile and we get another torrential
soaking, it might unleash flooding,'' the Liberation Daily said.
</TEXT>
