w2013 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Myanmar     08-22 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Myanmar </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Suu Kyi's health improving as standoff continues
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ Opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi's
health was improving as she entered the 11th day Saturday of her
standoff with Myanmar's military government over her right to
travel freely, her colleagues said.
	   Myanmar, also knowns as Burma, remained quiet following an
announcement Friday by Suu Kyi's party, the National League for
Democracy, that it would convene the parliament elected in 1990 in
the near future.
	   Analysts in Yangon expect the military government will respond
with arrests of elected lawmakers before the NLD can hold a
parliament session.
	   So far, the military has not responded publicly to the NLD's
call. However, past attempts by the NLD to bring its party's
lawmakers together for a meeting were met with mass arrests.
	   The NLD won 82 percent of the seats in the assembly in the 1990
vote. The military refused to honor the election result, despite
repeated United Nations resolutions calling for it to do so.
	   Suu Kyi's party, stepping up its campaign to bring democracy to
Myanmar through nonviolent means, had set Aug. 21 as the deadline
for the military to allow parliament to meet.
	   The military, which has ruled Myanmar since 1962, has refused.
	   It has also refused to let Suu Kyi travel to the provinces and
meet her party's lawmakers and other supporters. She was stopped
last Wednesday for the fourth time in two months at a checkpoint 32
kilometers (19 miles) west of Yangon by the authorities.
	   She and three colleagues are encamped in a van stocked with food
and water. Her party said, however, the provisions are nearly
exhausted.
	   The military has forced the van on to a small wooden bridge over
a stream. It has attempted to ridicule the 1991 Nobel Peace Prize
winner's protest by setting up a table, chairs and umbrella just
outside the vehicle.
	   The government ended the last standoff by force, seizing Suu
Kyi's car, restraining her and driving her back to Yangon against
her will.
	   Earlier this week, Suu Kyi's doctors, who have visited her daily
in her van at the site of the impasse, said her health was failing.
She was suffering from low blood pressure and her eyes had turned
yellow, causing them to suspect she may have contracted jaundice or
another disease, they said.
	   ``Her blood pressure is back to normal, although blood tests
showed that her kidneys have been slightly affected,'' the NLD said
in a statement Saturday, adding that Suu Kyi's spirits are high.
	   Meanwhile, the All Burma Students Democratic Front, an exiled
students group, called on Suu Kyi to end her protest so she can
conserve her health for the struggle for democracy.
	   About 30 exiled Myanmar students began a hunger strike Saturday
outside the Myanmar Embassy in Bangkok. Along with about 70 of
their colleagues, they have been protesting there for more than a
week, demanding the military allow parliament to convene.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
