<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Japan Tournament </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yokohama team wins Japanese National Baseball Tournament
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KOZO MIZOGUCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NISHINOMIYA, Japan (AP) _ Yokohama High won Japan's annual high
school baseball tournament Saturday, powered by Daisuke Matsuzaka's
no-hitter to shut out Kyoto Seisho 3-0.
	   Yokohama also won this year's spring tournament in March and
became only the fifth school to triumph in both highly publicized
baseball tournaments in the same year.
	   In Saturday's game, Matsuzaka struck out 11 in 9 innings. He was
the 22nd pitcher to throw a no-hitter shut-out in tournament play
history, but the only second hurler to do it in the final game
since 1939.
	   ``This is my happiest day ever,'' Matsuzaka told Japan's
national television network, NHK, after the game.
	   The tournaments are summer favorites in Japan. TVs in bars and
restaurants all over the nation are constantly tuned to the games,
which are seen not as youthful fun but as dead serious competitions
and displays of determination and sacrifice.
	   Before a near-capacity crowd of 55,000 at Koshien Stadium in
western Japan, Tsutomu Matsumoto hit a solo homer in the fourth,
and Yokohama High School also added a second run in the fifth and
another in the eighth.
	   A record 4,102 high school teams competed in the summer
tournament, with 55 of them playing in the finals of the 80th
National High School Baseball Championships.
	   After the tournament ended Saturday, the Japan High School
Baseball Association said a Japanese high school all-star team led
by Yokohama High School players will participate in an eight-nation
tournament in Osaka, western Japan, Sept. 4-13, playing with their
counterparts from South Korea, the Philippines, Mongolia,
Indonesia, Taiwan, China and Australia.
	   It will be the third such baseball tournament by players, aged
16-18, and held every two years from Asia and Oceania area. The
eight-nation tournament last was held in Manila in 1996.
 &UR; (km-jc)
</TEXT>
