<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Landslides,0378 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fresh landslides hamper rescue work in Himalayan village
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JAIDEEP MAZUMDAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUCKNOW, India (AP) _ Rescue workers ran for cover from boulders
hurtling down a remote Himalayan village Saturday, where 202 people
were already feared killed in an earlier landslide.
	   Hopes faded of finding more survivors in the mountain village of
Malpa, buried under mounds of rocks and mud.
	   No one was reported injured Saturday from the latest of nearly a
dozen landslides that have rumbled down the mountains of northern
India this season, lashed by heavy monsoon rains for three weeks.
The total number of dead reached 239.
	   The rain stopped Friday, but dense fog blocked a helicopter
rescue of 18 survivors from Malpa, 300 kilometers (185 miles) east
of New Delhi, said Ashok Kumar, the Uttar Pradesh state relief
commissioner.
	   Rescuers have found 32 bodies so far. The survivors, most of
them injured by falling rocks and mud, are being treated by two
doctors attached to paramilitary forces in the village.
	   On Saturday, Indian air force helicopters flew food and
medicines to Pithoragarh, a nearby town, from where they will be
carried on packs 60 kilometers (40 miles) to the devastated
village, Press Trust of India news agency said.
	   After waiting for two days, anxious relatives of those feared
killed traveled by bus to Pithoragarh. They will be taken to the
devastated village as soon as the weather clears, Kumar said.
	   Among those feared killed were 60 Hindu pilgrims headed to a
sacred lake across the Chinese border in Tibet. Porters and local
villagers were also missing.
	   Nearly 200 rescue workers have been looking for victims in the
sludge and along the banks of the Kali River. But fresh landslides
Friday evening forced them to suspend their efforts.
	   Authorities have evacuated more than 30,000 people to higher
ground from 30 nearby towns and villages facing a flood threat
after a blockage in the Mandakini River.
	   Army and civil engineers have decided not to dynamite the
blockage caused by falling boulders and mudslides. Removing the
blockage would have made the water level shoot up by as much as 26
feet (8 meters) downstream, engulfing 30 town and villages. 	   
</TEXT>
