<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Indonesia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese newspaper: Indonesian riot probe a credibility test
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China urged Indonesia's police chief Saturday to
stop threatening activists looking into rapes, beatings and other
brutality against Indonesian Chinese in May riots.
	   The national police chief Lt. Gen. Roesmanhadi should be out
digging up evidence instead of hurling accusations, the official
China Daily newspaper said in an editorial.
	   Women's groups allege 168 women and girls were raped during the
riots that ultimately ended the long reign of President Suharto.
Many of the victims were ethnic Chinese, resented for their
affluence and influence over Indonesia's now crippled economy.
	   Roesmanhadi earlier this month warned groups investigating the
violence that they may be charged with ``spreading false reports''
if they did not substantiate their claims. Indonesian newspapers
have reported that some victims have received threats by police.
	   The China Daily called the Indonesian police's conduct
``improper'' and a hindrance to a government investigation. The
newspaper called the probe a test of the credibility of Suharto's
successor, B.J. Habibie.
	   China has demanded the Indonesian government punish those
responsible and protect Indonesians of Chinese descent.
	   Pictures of purported rape victims circulating on the Internet
and reprinted in Chinese newspapers stirred public opinion,
provoking calls for stronger action by Jakarta.
	   More than 100 Beijing students protested outside the Indonesian
Embassy on Monday. A group of 40 women writers also demanded a U.N.
investigation and suggested the Chinese government had reacted
faintheartedly to the tragedy.
	   Indonesian police have been ``turning a blind eye to the gory
pictures of the rapes and the testimonies of victims lodged on the
Internet,'' China Daily said.
	   ``The threat can only bring fear to the victims and prevent them
from giving testimonies,'' it added.
</TEXT>
