<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Caterpillar-Mitsubishi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kido surges ahead in New Caterpillar-Mitsubishi Ladies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HAKONE, Japan (AP) _ Fuki Kido carded a 3-under-par 70 Saturday
and took a one-stroke lead over Chikayo Yamazaki going into the
final round of the New Caterpillar-Mitsubishi Ladies.
	   Kido, winner of the Mizuno Ladies two weeks ago, fired a round
of four birdies and a bogey en route to a 5-under 141 total.
	   Yamazaki, a one-shot leader overnight, shot a level-par 73 for
142. She had three birdies and three bogeys in negotiating the
windswept, hilly 6,662-yard (6,062-meter), par-73 Shizuoka Country
Hamaoka Course.
	   ``I wasn't putting very well, especially on the front nine,''
said Yamazaki, in contention for her first title of the season and
eighth overall. ``I hope I'll have a better round tomorrow, but I'm
not thinking about the result. I'll just let it happen.''
	   Kido, seeking her fifth career victory, said she's driving it
straighter, keeping the ball in the fairway off the tee on all but
two holes. ``But my iron shots were somewhat erratic, and I reached
the greens in regulation on about half of the holes,'' she said.
	   Kyoko Ono shot a 70 and was alone in third place at 144. Another
stroke back at 145 was Aki Takamura, who fired a 75. Defending
champion Takayo Bando struggled to a 78 for a share of 36th at 151.
	   Akiko Fukushima, the Japan tour's top player in the last two
years, has skipped the tournament to take part in the U.S. LPGA
Tour's qualifying tournament.
	   Of a total of 95, 61 players made the cut at 7-over 153.
	   The 60 million yen (dlrs 420,000) event pays the winner 10.8
million yen (dlrs 75,500).
 &UR; (kph)
</TEXT>
