w2066 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Pakistan-US-Bombings     08-22 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-US-Bombings,0676 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Witnesses see fire in the sky, then feel strike of U.S. missiles
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MOHAMMED RIAZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MIANSHAH, Pakistan (AP) _ A Pakistani who was in Afghanistan on
the night of a U.S. attack said he saw fire in the sky, then felt
the missiles strike what Washington says was a training camp for
Islamic militants from around the world.
	   ``There was panic and screaming, and people running everywhere.
I remember nothing after that, because I passed out,'' Muhammed
Furqan told The Associated Press Saturday from his hospital bed in
Mianshah, a Pakistani town near the targeted base. He had wounds on
his legs, chest and head he said were received in the attack.
	   Furqan said he had arrived just a week ago at the camp near
Khost, 150 kilometers (90 miles) southeast of the Afghan capital of
Kabul and just across the border from Pakistan. He said he was
engaged in ``religious studies'' there.
	   The commander of the base, Badshah Gul, said that when he heard
explosions he thought the men were engaged in their usual Friday
night drill of hurling explosives at targets.
	   ``But the explosions were so big that they lit the sky for a
while, and I began to realize what actually happened,'' Gul told
the Pakistan national newspaper The News.
	   Rehmat Ali, a 20-year-old who was injured in the attack, said he
heard fighter planes before the bombs.
	   ``As the fighter aircraft flew past our camp, the whole area got
lit up, and almost simultaneously the place got bombed,'' Ali told
The News from his hospital bed in the Afghan border town of
Peshawar.
	   U.S. officials said the missiles, which sound like jets, were
fired from ships in the Arabian sea. Pakistani officials have said
no U.S. planes crossed their airspace for the attack.
	   Six people injured in the attack died in hospitals in Pakistan
Friday. Earlier, Taliban officials had put the toll at 21, for a
total of 27.
	   There was a near-simultaneous U.S. attack on a target in Sudan,
which Washington accuses of sponsoring terrorism. U.S. officials
said they were unsure how much damage had been caused by the
strikes, which were meant to disrupt Saudi dissident Osama bin
Laden's alleged terrorist activities against the United States.
	   Pakistani government sources said bin Laden would have been
having coffee at the targeted Afghan base at the time of the attack
if he hadn't changed his plans for security reasons.
	   Taliban officials have said bin Laden was unharmed, and he has
reportedly issued new threats against the United States. He had
reportedly been taking special precautions after Washington named
him as the primary suspect in the Aug. 7, U.S. Embassy bombings in
Kenya and Tanzania.
	   Information pieced together from witnesses, Pakistani government
sources and newspaper reports, suggests that bin Laden dropped
plans to meet with key commanders from Pakistan and elsewhere late
Thursday on the advice of his security men.
	   Pakistan reportedly had intimate knowledge of bin Laden's
movements, and knew he was due to speak at the Khost camp, known as
the Zhawar Kili Al-Badr base, on Thursday.
	   Kuwait's Al-Watan newspaper, quoting unidentified sources in
London Saturday, reported Pakistan leaked to bin Laden news about
an impending U.S. strike. The sources said the leak was aimed at
limiting casualties, so that bin Laden would have less
justification for a counterattack.
	   A Pakistani government source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that Gen. Anthony Zinni, commander of the U.S.
Central Command, was in Peshawar the day before the attack to meet
with Pakistani officials.
	   Other Pakistani sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Zinni came with a team of U.S. intelligence experts whose task
was to pinpoint the camps and determine bin Laden's exact
whereabouts.
	   By all accounts, had things gone normally that night bin Laden
would have had dinner with commanders, then sit down to sip coffee
in the open, a habit among many Arabs. 	   
</TEXT>
