<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parliamentary leader sides with Yeltsin, Kiriyenko
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The head of the upper house of Russia's parliament
stood up for President Boris Yeltsin and his government Saturday,
saying he opposed efforts in the lower chamber to dismiss them, a
news agency reported.
	   ``I think it would be premature to dismiss the government,''
Yegor Stroyev said, according to Interfax. ``The difficulties and
mistakes we are now suffering from are the result of long
irresponsible work by the previous government, and errors regarding
the (bond) market.''
	   The State Duma, the lower and more left-leaning house of
parliament, passed a resolution Friday calling on Yeltsin to
resign, and all factions in the Duma called for Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko to resign.
	   The government usually receives more support from the upper
house of parliament, which is drawn from the ranks of regional
leaders who are more likely to be in Yeltsin's camp.
	   Former Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev praised the Duma for
seeking Yeltsin's resignation.
	   ``The president should now think about his country, his own
future and his legacy,'' Gorbachev told Interfax. Gorbachev rarely
misses an opportunity to attack his old rival, but his opinion
carries little weight in Russia these days.
	   Gorbachev said he had no plans to run for president in 2000,
when the next elections are scheduled.
	   (ml)
</TEXT>
