<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Koreas-Defectors </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: South Korean man defects to North Korea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ A South Korean man has defected to
North Korea by crossing the heavily armed buffer zone separating
the two countries, the North's media reported Saturday.
	   The official Korea Central News Agency said Pak Song-hun, 29,
crossed the mine-infested Demilitarized Zone near the east coast on
Friday.
	   Pak was from Wando County in South Korea's southwestern tip and
had worked as a construction worker in Seoul, KCNA said.
	   KCNA said the defector lost his job recently and was
dissatisfied with South Korean society.
	   There was no immediate confirmation of the report by South
Korean authorities.
	   The Koreas have been bitter enemies since the division of their
peninsula into the communist North and the capitalist South in
1945. Their border is the world's most heavily armed.
	   It's rare for a South Korean to defect to North Korea. About 200
North Koreans have escaped to South Korea in the past three years,
reporting widespread hunger.
</TEXT>
