<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Congolese rebels say they shot down two Zimbabwean warplanes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES urgent series; UPDATES with comment from rebel
leaders, from information minister in Kinshasa; ADDS byline.
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GOMA, Congo (AP) _ Congolese rebels fighting to oust President
Laurent Kabila said Saturday they had shot down two Zimbabwean jet
fighters southwest of the capital, Kinshasa.
	   ``Just this morning, we have shot down two of their jet
fighters,'' Bizima Karaha, Kabila's former foreign minister who
defected to the rebels, said. ``And this is just a warning.''
	   ``It should be understood that the people of Congo are ready to
resist any foreign aggression.''
	   Karaha did not specify where the planes were shot down or what
happened to the pilots. No independent confirmation was possible.
	   He accused Zimbabwe of sending 900 troops to help Kabila's
embattled government ward off rebels advances and said 500 of them
had been sent to the frontlines in western Congo.
	   ``We shall continue to resist,'' he said.
	   Karaha said until Kabila agreed to a cease-fire and to a
negotiated political solution which the rebel coalition had
proposed on Wednesday, the rebels would continue to march on
several fronts.
	   ``We're marching on Kinshasa. We're marching on Kisangani. We're
marching on Katanga,'' he said. Kisangani, in north central Congo,
is the nation's third-largest city. Katanga region in the southeast
is home to Kabila, and he is believed to be directing war efforts
from there.
	   ``We're ready for negotiations with Kabila, but instead he is
sending jet fighters on us,'' Karaha said.
	   Karaha said he expected the peace summit in Pretoria, organized
by South African President Nelson Mandela in a bid to avert a
deepening crisis in sub-Saharan Africa, to persuade Kabila to
negotiate with the rebels and prevent foreign intervention.
	   ``We hope that the summit can pursuade Zimbabwe to withdraw
their troops,'' Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, the leader of the rebel
Congolese Democratic Coalition said. ``We also hope that the summit
will arrive at achieving a formula that will permit the finding of
a peaceful solution to the problem.''
	   But in Kinshasa, Information Minister Didier Mumegi told
reporters that Kabila may ask for a postponement, and if the
meeting is not postponed, it would have to go on without him.
	   The rebels _ a coalition of ethnic Tutsis fighters and
disenchanted members of the Congolese army _ accuse Kabila of
power-grabbing, tribalism and mismanagement of the vast African
nation.
	   Kabila, in turn, accuses Rwanda and Uganda of sponsoring the
revolt and appealed for help from Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola.
Both Rwanda and Uganda denied the charge.
	   Karaha said he hoped Angola would not get involved.
	   ``We are natural allies. We don't have problems with Angola,''
he said.
	   Karaha also accused Kabila of ordering the execution of 20,000
ethnic Tutsis in Moba in southeastern Congo, a move which he said
promoted the rebels to move on to the Lake Tanganyika port of
Kalemie to prevent the killing.
	   ``We have to intervene to prevent Kabila from killing people,''
Karaha said.
	   (hh/sl)	   
</TEXT>
