<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Congo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mugabe to boycott Congolese peace summit in South Africa
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ President Robert Mugabe, whose nation
has sent troops to support embattled Congolese leader Laurent
Kabila, will not attend a peace summit called by South Africa, his
office said Saturday.
	   There was no immediate reaction from Zimbabwean officials to a
Congolese rebel claim that they shot down two Zimbabwean jet
fighters on Saturday.
	   State airline officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said an airline jet was commandeered by the Zimbabwean military to
fly about 250 soldiers to Kinshasa. Diplomats said up to 600 troops
were believed to have left Harare since Thursday.
	   Mugabe spokesman George Charamba refused to say how many
Zimbabwean troops were being sent to Congo.
	   The Herald newspaper quoted unidentified witnesses saying a
Russian built cargo plane was loaded with ``a variety of war
equipment'' at an air force base outside Harare and was headed for
the Congolese capital.
	   It said Zimbabwe's intervention aimed to make the war
``unwinnable for the rebels'' and force negotiations to end the
conflict.
	   Mugabe felt the peace talks scheduled to begin Saturday in
Pretoria, South Africa's capital, was ``too limited'' and did not
include countries which _ like Zimbabwe _ support military
intervention in Congo, Charamba said.
	   Mugabe made his view known to South African Vice President Thabo
Mbeki in a telephone conversation late Friday, the spokesman said.
	   South Africa invited the presidents of Congo, Uganda, Rwanda and
Zimbabwe for talks in hopes of averting the spread of the Congo
war.
	   The war in the central African country to topple Kabila has sent
shock waves far beyond its borders.
	   Kabila accuses Rwanda and Uganda of supporting Congo rebels with
troops and weapons.
	   (as-aos)
</TEXT>
