<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Congo, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mugabe to boycott Congolese peace summit in South Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comment on report jets shot down &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ President Robert Mugabe, whose nation
has sent troops to support embattled Congolese leader Laurent
Kabila, is snubbing a peace summit called by South Africa, his
office said Saturday.
	   There was no immediate official reaction from Zimbabwean
officials to a Congolese rebel claim that they shot down two
Zimbabwean jet fighters on Saturday.
	   But a duty officer at the Zimbabwe Air Force operations center
said: ``I don't think it can be right. We don't have any fighters
up there.''
	   The officer refused to give his name, saying he wasn't
authorized to give out information.
	   Zimbabwe is believed to have squadron of Chinese-made MiG-21
interceptors with limited range and Spanish-made Casa transport
planes suitable for dropping paratroopers. Although Zimbabwe has
sent soldiers to Congo, there have been no reports it has sent
warplanes.
