<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Prison Raid </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: gunmen raid jail, free prisoners, seize weapons
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ A band of men in military uniforms raided
a government prison in an eastern town, freeing 110 prisoners and
seizing guns and ammunition, a government-owned newspaper reported
Saturday.
	   Wardens from the prison near Mbale, 250 kilometers (150 miles)
east of Kampala, were quoted by the New Vision newspaper as saying
the attackers described themselves as rebels fighting the
government of President Yoweri Museveni.
	   It did not say what faction the attackers claimed to represent,
but the Ugandan military is already fighting several well-armed
guerrilla bands in the northern and eastern parts of the country.
	   Government offices were closed Saturday and no officials could
be reached for comment on the report.
	   The attackers staged their raid just as prisoners were about to
be taken out for a day of manual labor in surrounding villages, the
newspaper said.
	   When wardens opened the front gate, they found themselves
confronting an armed band, according to the account. It did not
report any exchange of fire, or provide details about the arms
seized by the attackers.
	   Mathias Akabwai, the Mbale district commissioner, was quoted by
the newspaper as saying the raiders belonged to the same group that
struck a police station near the town last weekend, killing one
policeman and injuring another.
 &UR; (stgr-lk)
</TEXT>
