<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-US Bombings-Death </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian military officer dies of wounds in Kabul attack
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ An Italian soldier wounded by unidentified gunmen in
the Afghan capital of Kabul died Saturday, the Italian defense
ministry said.
	   The United Nations said Friday that the Italian and a French man
were shot as they drove in Kabul.
	   The shooting occurred a day after a U.S. cruise missile attack
on a suspected terrorist base in Afghanistan that reportedly killed
24 people.
	   It was not clear if the attack was related to Thursday's U.S.
missile strikes.
	   The Italian defense ministry had said Friday that Lt. Col.
Carmine Calo, posted in Kabul since July as part of the U.N.
observer force, was hit by a ricocheting bullet as he was traveling
in a U.N. vehicle to his post. Calo died in a Kabul civilian
hospital of complications from his wounds, the ministery said.
	   The French foreign mnistry on Friday said the Frenchman, Eric
Lavertu, a civilian U.N. worker, was wounded in the hand.
	   Foreigners had been advised Wednesday to leave Afghanistan.
Those still in Kabul stayed out of sight Friday while the United
Nations and other agencies arranged evacuations.
	   U.S. officials said Thursday's missile attacks were meant to
disrupt the infrastructure of a guerrilla organization run by Osama
bin Laden, an anti-American Islamic militant whom U.S. officials
suspect of involvement in the bombings of the U.S. embassies in
Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
	   (int-fd)
</TEXT>
