<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Gang Shooting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cyprus cabaret owner wounded in gang shooting
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LIMASSOL, Cyprus (AP) - A cabaret owner was shot and wounded
before dawn Saturday in the fourth gang attack in about a month.
	   Vangelis Christodoulou, 35, was shot and seriously wounded by a
man with a shotgun as he was leaving his cabaret, a police
statement said. A man was later detained in connection with the
shooting, the statement added. Police said the shooting was related
to recent gang violence.
	   Christodoulou's shooting followed the Monday attack against pub
owner Lemis Neoptolemou. He was injured when a remote-controlled
bomb exploded as he was leaving his pub in Limassol's nightclub
district, only a short distance from Christodoulou's cabaret.
	   Neoptolemou had been a prosecution witness in the trial of three
brothers of the Aeroporos family, Limassol's most notorious
underworld clan. They were tried for the attempted murder in May
last year of Andonis Fanieros, the reputed underworld leader of
Larnaca, a town 40 kilometers (25 miles) east of Limassol.
	   The Aeroporos brothers were acquitted in the Fanieros case in
June. In late July, one of the brothers, Andros, 32, was shot and
killed as he was leaving a Limassol nightclub.
	   On Aug. 9, Andonis Fanieros' son, Loucas, 31, escaped unhurt
when his car was sprayed with bullets outside a Larnaca nightclub.
	   Justice and Police Minister Nicos Koshis ordered greatly
increased police patrols and surveillance in Limassol after the
Aeroporos murder, fearing a fresh outbreak of gang warfare.
 &UR; ae-lm 	   
</TEXT>
