r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Romania-JournalistImp     08-22 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Journalist Imprisoned </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Journalist begins 20-month prison sentence for libel
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ A journalist in northwest Romania has
started a ten-month prison term after being convicted in April on a
libel charge for criticizing a local judge, Romanian media reported
Saturday.
	   Cornel Sabou, editor in chief of Trans Pres, a small private
news agency in the northwest city of Baia Mare, was arrested and
taken to jail Friday to start his sentence, the news agency
Mediafax reported.
	   He was convicted and sentenced by a court in April. Sabou was
also fined 500,000 lei (dlrs 57) and ordered to pay 300 million lei
(dlrs 34,000) in damages. A colleague was also fined 500,000 in
connection with the case.
	   In post-Communist Romania, officials are unaccustomed to
criticism in the free-wheeling press. Justice officials are often
suspected to be corrupt. They are accused of delaying some cases
for years while rushing through others in which they have a vested
interest.
	   Last year, Sabou, 26, wrote a series of articles accusing judge
Mariana Iancu of forgery and of allegedly using her position to
exert influence on a local level, the daily National reported.
	   The judge was demoted after the articles appeared, but continued
to work in the city in a lower position.
	   It was second case in recent weeks in which a journalist were
convicted for allegedly libeling a justice official.
	   Two journalists were sentenced to a prison term, deprived of
civil rights for one year and ordered to pay damages equal to dlrs
170,000 after a judge sued them for allegedly libeling her husband.
They are free pending an appeal.
	   (am/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
