w2179 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Morocco-BoatPeople     08-22 0238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Morocco-Boat People </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three smugglers sentenced, army troops accused for first time
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TANGIERS, Morocco (AP) _ A court has convicted three
emigrant-smugglers and for the first time fingered Moroccan army
officers for allegedly aiding a clandestine boat people operation
across the Mediterranean.
	   North Africans, mainly from Morocco, have long sought to get to
Europe by paying smugglers to take them across the Mediterranean to
Spain in often unseaworthy boats. Dozens have drowned in recent
sinkings.
	   The court on Friday convicted the three men of complicity and
sentenced them to prison terms of one to two years, while the
ringleader and other accomplices remained at large.
	   It acquitted seven members of the army, also accused of
complicity. But it was the first time the army was linked to
illegal emigration since Moroccan troops were deployed on the
Mediterranean coast in the early 1990s in an effort to stem the
tide.
	   Three of them _ two sergeants and a corporal _ were accused of
actively participating the week before in the nighttime sailing of
a boatload of 20 emigrants from a beach near Tangiers.
	   The emigrants were arrested Aug. 14 as they made their way
toward Spain after paying the smugglers between 4,000 and 8,000
dirham (dlrs 400-800). The emigrants were given a suspended
one-month sentence and fined 500 dirhams (dlrs 50).
	   (cb-parf)
</TEXT>
