<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-US Bombings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore stops short of condoning U.S. bombings
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The Singapore government condemned acts of
terrorism on Saturday but stopped short of condoning the U.S.
decision to bomb targets in Afghanistan and Sudan.
	   ``Singapore believes that the only effective response to such
acts of terrorism is for the international community to work
together to take firm action against terrorism,'' said a statement
from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
	   It did not elaborate on whether the Singapore government
actually opposed the surprise air strikes, which were launched on
Thursday against targets identified by Washington as sites of
terrorist activity.
	   The U.S. retaliation for the terrorist bombings in Kenya and
Tanzania has drawn a mixed global response, from angry protests in
a number of Arab countries to open support from a number of allies.
	   In its statement commenting on both the terrorist actions and
the U.S. retaliation, Singapore said that it ``regrets the loss of
lives,'' and has ``consistently supported international cooperation
in the fight against terrorism.''
	   The ministry went on to strongly condemn terrorism, which
``undermines the principles of international law and the
maintenance of the international order,'' provoking ``a cycle of
violence that only harms the innocent.''
	   The Southeast Asian nation is an ally with the United States,
which maintains naval logistics operations in the country.
</TEXT>
