w2202 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-OneNation     08-22 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-One Nation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hanson supporter says Asian nations poor on race relations
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ Asian countries have an ``appalling
record on race relations'' and have no right to accuse right-wing
Australian politician Pauline Hanson of racism, a spokesman for her
party said Saturday.
	   One Nation spokesman David Oldfield said the idea that people in
Asia could be worried that the anti-immigration Hanson is a racist
is ``laughable for two reasons.''
	   ``The first is that Pauline Hanson is not a racist,'' said
Oldfield. ``The second is that Asia itself has an appalling record
in race relations and does not have a credible position to comment
on any other nation.''
	   Oldfield was responding to Queensland premier Peter Beattie, who
said Saturday that Hanson had generated far greater racist fears in
Asia than most Australians were aware.
	   ``The damage was more significant than I thought,'' Beattie said
after returning from a five-day visit to Hong Kong and Japan. ``The
visit hopefully put a lot of minds at rest in Asia and repaired a
large part of the damage caused by One Nation.''
	   Hanson's One Nation party made its election debut at the June 13
poll which brought Beattie's Labor Party to power. One Nation, a
populist party which critics say is anti-Asian and anti-Aboriginal,
captured 11 seats and 23 percent of the vote.
	   Hanson was elected to the federal Parliament as an independent
in 1996, and later formed One Nation. She claims Australia is in
danger of becoming ``Asianized,'' wants to drastically cut
immigration levels, opposes special welfare payments to Aborigines
and advocates economic protectionism.
	   But Oldfield said impressions abroad that Hanson is racist are
misguided.
	   ``Those who have opposed her have used racism as a dishonest
form of weapon against her,'' he said. ``She is not responsible for
the perceptions they have created inside or outside of Australia.''
</TEXT>
