<SLUG> BC-Sudan-US, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With protests, marches, Sudan seeks to rally weary people
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details from rally, one of the wounded dying of
injuries &QL; 
 &UR; By ANTHONY SHADID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Chanting ``God is greater than America,''
thousands of Sudanese gathered outside the presidential palace
Saturday to protest the U.S. attack against a factory in Khartoum.
	   In the midst of the crowd hung a yellow banner reading ``Forward
ever, backward never. Yesterday Nairobi, tomorrow the White House''
_ a reference to the Aug. 7 bombing of the U.S. embassy in Nairobi,
Kenya.
	   President Clinton ordered a missile attack Thursday against a
factory in Sudan in retaliation for the bombing in Nairobi and one
the same day in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania. U.S. missiles also struck
suspected camps of Muslim militant Osama bin Laden in Afghanistan.
	   One of the 10 people wounded in the Sudan strike has died,
state-run Sudan Television said.
	   Sudan's beleaguered government has sought to rally a people
weary of war and economic hardship against the attack.
	   Saturday's crowd denounced America and Sudanese opposition
figures that the government considers traitors.
	   One soldier in green camouflage and a red head band that read
``No, no to America'' collected donations for the government's war
against southern rebels.
	   A 15-year-old boy in camouflage, who would only identify himself
as Holy Warrior Mustafa, said ``God willing, we will carry weapons
and defend our country.''
	   One banner hit on a theme sounded time and again by Sudanese:
U.S. President Clinton launched the attack to draw attention from
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, a White House intern.
	   It said: ``No war for Monica.''
	   Schools let students out early to attend the rally outside the
office of President Omar el-Bashir. Government ministries asked
employees to attend the protest, which lasted about three hours.
	   While Khartoum residents expressed surprise at the missile
strike, many said they thought there was little their government
could do.
	   ``We are not strong enough to face the west,'' Mamoun Rahama,
said a 29-year-old who works at a textile factory near the
destroyed plant. ``We cannot face a greater force.''
	   El-Bashir told a Friday rally that Sudan could ``prove that the
factory is specifically for pharmaceutical production'' and not
chemical weapons as described by U.S. officials.
	   Sudan planned to lodge complaints with the Arab League and the
Organization of African Unity, and its diplomats asked the Security
Council Friday to convene an urgent meeting to consider a U.N.
investigation into the attack.
	   The Islamic leaders in Sudan, where as many as nine out of 10 of
the country's 28 million people live in poverty, oversee a network
of well-organized cadres which can bring thousands into the
streets. Their security network is pervasive, keeping a close eye
on dissent.
	   The factory that was struck _ El-Shifa Pharmaceutical Industries
Co. _ was hit by six Tomahawk cruise missiles.
	   It was virtually destroyed. Brown glass jars sat in piles amid
crushed red bricks and twisted sheet metal. Civil defense workers
said fires at the site burned until Friday night and their pungent
fumes hung over the site like a cloud.
	   The U.S. government said the factory produced precursors for
chemical weapons. State-run Sudan Television said that the factory,
which opened in 1996, produced about half of the medicine in Sudan,
Africa's largest country and one of its poorest. It described its
main products as antibiotics and drugs to treat malaria and
tuberculosis.
	   In Cairo, a Sudanese opposition group accused the government of
backing what it described as terrorism and said it had provided
refuge to followers of bin Laden, who lived in Sudan for five years
before he was forced to move to Afghanistan.
 &UR; as-lm 	   
</TEXT>
