<SLUG> BC-Congo-Peace Talks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Congo peace talks being held in South Africa
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) _ The presidents of Rwanda and
Uganda, accused by Congo President Laurent Kabila of supporting
rebels in his country, arrived here on Saturday for peace talks
with Kabila's envoy.
	   Congolese Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo was to represent
Kabila at Saturday's talks, said President Nelson Mandela's
spokesman, Parks Mankahlana.
	   Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni, Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu and Kongolo were to open the talks Saturday afternoon
after having lunch at Mandela's residence, Mankahlana said.
	   Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who has sent troops to Congo
to back Kabila, was invited to the meeting but boycotted it because
it didn't include countries _ like Zimbabwe _ which support
military intervention in Congo, Mugabe's office said.
	   The meeting was to be followed Sunday by a full meeting of
Southern African Development Community on the crisis in Central
Africa, Mankahlana said.
	   The 14-member SADC summit is aimed at resolving a split within
the group on how best to deal with the crisis. Mandela has ruled
out military intervention in the Congo war.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
