<SLUG> BC-Congo-Peace Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Congo peace talks being held in South Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Mandela meeting with presidents of Uganda and
Rwanda; Kabila envoy not having arrived &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa's plans to hold a
summit to end the Congo crisis hit a snag Saturday when two key
figures failed to appear.
	   Only two heads of state of the four invited showed up: the
presidents of Rwanda and Uganda. Congo accuses Rwanda and Uganda of
supporting rebels in the country.
	   Congo President Laurent Kabila declined to come and was instead
reportedly sending his justice minister, Mwenze Kongolo. But by
late Saturday afternoon _ well beyond the time when the peace talks
were to have begun _ Kongolo hadn't arrived.
	   Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe _ who is backing Kabila with
troops _ boycotted the meeting because it didn't include other
countries which support military intervention in Congo.
	   South African President Nelson Mandela was having ``an exhange
of views'' with Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan
President Pasteur Bizimungu, according to Mandela's spokesman,
Parks Mankahlana.
	   But without the participation of the opposing sides, little
stood to be achieved.
	   Reporters were kept away from the meeting site, a residence for
visiting VIPs in Pretoria, the capital.
	   On Sunday, the Southern African Development Community planned to
hold a meeting in Pretoria to resolve a split within the 14-nation
group on how best to deal with the Congo crisis.
	   While Zimbabwe and reportedly Angola and sending troops to back
Kabila, South Africa has ruled out military intervention and wants
other countries to take the same stance.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
