<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Some 500 Muslims return to their pre-war homes in southern town
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPLJINA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ Some 500 Muslims returned to
their pre-war homes in this tense, Croat-held southern town
Saturday, local officials reported.
	   They stressed that there were no incidents during the return _ a
significant development, because several Muslim houses were
destroyed and many Muslim returnees harassed in the town over the
past three years.
	   Most of the Muslim families fled Capljina, where Bosnian Croats
took control during the war in 1993, and found refuge in towns and
villages to the north.
	   The return to Capljina was part of a local project for the
return of Bosnian Serbs, Croats and Muslims to their homes in
southern Bosnia.
	   Several thousand refugees have returned to this region over the
past weeks. According to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees,
this is a part of the overall figure of some 500,000 Bosnian Serbs,
Croats and Muslims who have returned to their pre-war homes since
the end of the war in 1995.
	   Still, more than one million people remain displaced within
Bosnia and across Europe, and international officials and aid
agencies are trying to speed up their return.
	   (str/sl/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
