<SLUG> BC-Sudan-US, 2nd Ld,0449 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudanese rally against U.S. strikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Sudanese stoning British Embassy, tearing apart
Union Jack, quotes from Sudanese president &QL; 
 &UR; By ANTHONY SHADID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Chanting ``God is greater than America,''
thousands of Sudanese gathered outside the presidential palace
Saturday to protest the U.S. attack against a factory in Khartoum.
	   In the midst of the crowd hung a yellow banner reading ``Forward
ever, backward never. Yesterday Nairobi, tomorrow the White House''
_ a reference to the Aug. 7 bombing of the U.S. embassy in Nairobi,
Kenya.
	   President Bill Clinton ordered a missile attack Thursday against
a factory in Sudan in retaliation for the bombing in Nairobi and
one the same day in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania. U.S. missiles also
struck suspected camps of Muslim militant Osama bin Laden in
Afghanistan.
	   Protesters hurled stones at the British Embassy _ Britain has
expressed strong support for the strikes _ and one young man
climbed up the embassy flagpole and cut down the Union Jack.
	   After the flag fell to the ground, angry demonstrators tore it
apart.
	   Sudan's beleaguered government has sought to use the strikes,
which left one dead and nine wounded, to rally a people weary of
war and economic hardship.
	   Saturday's crowd denounced America and Sudanese opposition
figures that the government considers traitors.
	   One soldier in green camouflage and a red head band that read
``No, no to America'' collected donations for the government's war
against southern rebels.
	   A 15-year-old boy in camouflage, who would only identify himself
as Holy Warrior Mustafa, said ``God willing, we will carry weapons
and defend our country.''
	   One banner hit on a theme sounded time and again by Sudanese:
Clinton launched the attack to draw attention from his affair with
Monica Lewinsky, a White House intern. It said: ``No war for
Monica.''
	   ``This is a wicked president,'' said President Omar el-Bashir,
jabbing a black staff into the air. ``This president lied to the
whole world and to his people, and he is still lying.''
	   El-Bashir struck a militant chord, calling Sudan's defiance of
the United States a war for the sake of Islam. His adviser sounded
a similar theme.
	   ``We reserve for ourselves the right to respond against American
interests anywhere in the world,'' said Brig. Bakri Hassan Saleh,
minister for presidential affairs.
	   Schools let students out early to attend the rally outside of
el-Bashir's office. Government ministries asked employees to attend
the protest, which lasted about three hours.
 &UR; While Khartoum, 12th graf pvs 	   
