<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Congo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zimbabwe denies its MiG warplanes shot down in Congo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with official statement; TRIMS material about peace
meeting in South Africa, which contained in BC-Congo-Peace Talks;
ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By ANGUS SHAW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ President Robert Mugabe's spokesman on
Saturday rejected Congolese rebel claims that they shot down two
Zimbabwean jet fighters.
	   Spokesman George Charamba said Zimbabwe had not deployed its
Chinese-made MiG-21 interceptors along with ground troops to
support embattled Congolese leader Laurent Kabila, the official
Zimbabwe news agency reported.
	   ``We have no MiG fighters in DRC (the Democratic Republic of
Congo) ... our deployment in the DRC did not have that dimension,''
Charamba was quoted as saying.
	   In his statement to the state-run media, Charamba did not
mention the British Hawk ground attack jets or the Spanish Casa
transport planes _ suitable for dropping paratroopers _ which
Zimbabwe also possesses. He did not return repeated phone calls
seeking clarification.
	   A duty officer at the Zimbabwe Air Force operations center said
of the rebels' claim: ``I don't think it can be right. We don't
have any fighters up there.''
	   The officer refused to give his name, saying he wasn't
authorized to give information.
	   Although Zimbabwe has sent soldiers to Congo, there have been no
reports it has sent warplanes.
	   The Herald newspaper, meanwhile, quoted unidentified witnesses
as saying a Russian built cargo plane was loaded with ``a variety
of war equipment'' at an air force base outside Harare and was
headed for the Congolese capital.
	   It said Zimbabwe's intervention aimed to make the war
``unwinnable for the rebels'' and force negotiations to end the
conflict.
	   Charamba refused to say how many Zimbabwean troops were being
sent to Congo.
	   (as-aos)
</TEXT>
