w2362 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Pakistan-US-Bombings 2ndLd   08-22 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-US-Bombings, 2nd Ld,0541 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Witnesses describe U.S. missile strike on Afghanistan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 13th graf pvs with Pakistan firing
intelligence chief. PICKUP 14th graf pvs. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo ISL101 &QL; 
 &UR; By MOHAMMED RIAZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MIANSHAH, Pakistan (AP) _ A militant Islamic group in Pakistan
denied on Saturday that the Afghan bases bombed by the United
States were used to train terrorists, and vowed to avenge the
deaths of those killed in the attack.
	   Meanwhile, a Pakistani who was in Afghanistan on the night of
the U.S. strike said he saw fire in the sky, then felt the missiles
hit what Washington says was a training camp for Islamic militants.
	   ``There was panic and screaming, and people running everywhere.
I remember nothing after that because I passed out,'' Muhammed
Furqan told The Associated Press on Saturday from his hospital bed
in Mianshah, a Pakistani town near the camp.
	   He had wounds on his legs, chest and head that he said were
received in Thursday's attack.
	   A total of 27 people were killed in the strike. Taliban
officials initially put the toll at 21, but six people injured in
the attack died in hospitals in Pakistan on Friday, doctors said.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton said the U.S. strikes on Afghanistan
and Sudan on Thursday were aimed at rooting out extremist violence
in general and at Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden, whom the United
States accuses of directing worldwide attacks from hide-outs in
Afghanistan. Washington named him as the No. 1 suspect in the Aug.
7 bomb attacks on U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
	   Furqan said he had arrived just a week ago at the camp near
Khost, 90 miles (145 kilometers) southeast of the Afghan capital of
Kabul and just across the border from Pakistan.
	   He said he was engaged in ``religious studies'' there, reluctant
to admit to training in a militant camp.
	   Badshah Gul, the base commander, said that when he heard
explosions, he thought the men were engaged in their usual Friday
night drill of hurling explosives at targets.
	   ``But the explosions were so big that they lit the sky for a
while, and I began to realize what actually happened,'' Gul told
the national Pakistani newspaper The News.
	   The newspaper quoted several witnesses as saying that they heard
fighter planes before the missiles.
	   U.S. officials said the missiles were fired from ships in the
Arabian Sea. Pakistani officials have said that no U.S. planes
crossed their airspace for the attack.
	   There have been public protests in Pakistan since the attack,
which has been condemned by Islamabad. On Saturday, about 300 women
descended on a park in the northeastern city of Lahore, carrying
placards denouncing the United States.
	   The Pakistani government fired its intelligence chief, Manzoor
Ahmed, on Saturday for his handling of information about the U.S.
attacks.
	   The Pakistanis said Friday that one U.S. missile landed in
Pakistan, killing at least five people. Hours later, the ministry
said that information was inaccurate, and that all missile hits and
casualties were inside Afghanistan.
	    &UR; In Islamabad ... PICKUP 14th graf pvs.
</TEXT>
