<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland-Spain </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bereaved parents of Spanish victims of bombings at London service
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Northern Ireland &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The parents of two Spanish victims on Saturday led
mourners at a memorial service for people killed in the Northern
Ireland bombing a week ago.
	   The service was held at St. Martin's-in-the-Field, a historic
church on Traflagar Square, while in Omagh, where 28 people were
slain, and across Ireland, north and south, hundreds of thousands
of people fell silent in memory of the victims.
	   At the Service of Solidarity in London, the parents of
12-year-old Fernando Blasco Baselga and teacher Rocio Abad Ramos,
23, listened to poems, prayers and readings by Roman Catholics and
Protestants.
	   The pair were among a party of Spanish children and supervisors
on a day-trip to Omagh during an exchange visit to Ireland to
improve their English.
	   Twelve Spaniards were among the 330 were injured in the bombing,
the worst atrocity in three decades of sectarian conflict in
British-run Northern Ireland.
	   Mourners sang ``Make Me A Channel of Your Peace,'' and listened
to a reading from Luke 13 _ Jesus Weeps Over Jerusalem _ requested
by the Spanish families.
	   ``So many lives have been shattered, now is not the time to
interpret what it all means. It is time for us to live with the
pain,'' the Rev. David Monteith told the congregation.
	   ``We must remember the young people from Spain who came to
Ireland to enjoy the beauty and richness of the country,'' he
added.
	   People at the service welcomed the news Saturday that another
dissident group opposed to a peace settlement in Northern Ireland,
the Irish National Liberation Army, had declared a cease-fire.
	   The Omagh bombing was admitted was a group dubbed the Real IRA
because it, too, opposes the Irish Republican Army's acceptance of
the peace deal.
	   ``I'm extremely glad _ but I don't know how it will help the
parents,'' Spain's deputy ambassador to Britain, Agustin Jervas,
said.
	   Jervas said the parents of the slain boy and teacher were
overwhelmed by the warm welcome and support they had received.
	   ``We have spent the last three days in (Northern Ireland
capital) Belfast and we have been superhumanly well-treated, from
every day people, diplomats and agencies,'' he said.
	   He said the parents, Manuel Blasco and his wife Lucreva Baselga,
whose son was killed, and Jose Abad and his wife Ana Maria Ramos,
were coping remarkably well.
	   Carol Cavey, on holiday from Limerick in the Irish Republic,
said of the INLA cease-fire, ``This is great news and gives hope to
the families and all those who share in their grief.''
	   ``Perhaps some of our prayers have been answered already,'' she
added. ``I felt I had to come today, and I'm so glad I did.''
	   The organizer of the service, Dublin-born Eoin O'Neachtain,
said, ``I think the people of these islands have given the signal
they won't tolerate violence of any kind.''
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
