<DATE_TIME> 08/22/1998 11:40:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2398 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Floods 1stLd-Writethru   08-22 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Floods, 1st Ld-Writethru,0628 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede HARBIN, China
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; High waters surge anew on Yangtze; soldiers try to plug dikes &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with higher waters on the
Yangtze, cracks in dikes downstream, soldiers trying to plug dike
near oil field; no pickup; CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES HUTZLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Weeks of high waters cracked soggy dikes
protecting cities along the Yangtze River on Saturday, and soldiers
in the northeast fought to stop a breached levee hard by China's
largest oil field.
	   The state disaster relief agency warned that high waters surged
anew on the upper Yangtze, threatening another round of flooding
downstream. Governor Wang Maolin said dikes in central Hunan
province were already soggy and seriously damaged.
	   While the latest Yangtze flood crest receded Saturday around
Hunan's Dongting Lake, its retreat exposed fractures in protective
embankments. Some 830,000 soldiers and civilians worked to shore up
dikes and patch cracks, one of them 70 meters (230 feet) long,
around Yueyang city, state media reported.
	   The Yangtze River basin has taken the brunt of China's worst
flood season in 44 years. At least 2,000 people have died
nationwide and millions more have been left homeless, but the
government, often reluctant to divulge bad news, has not revised
those tallies in two weeks.
	   Since then floodwaters have smothered villages and threatened
some of the most important industrial centers of the northeast. The
Xinhua News Agency reported that 1.5 million people have been
flooded out in Heilongjiang, China's northeasternmost province.
	   With clinics and hospitals in many parts of the country under
water, health officials face a shortage of medicine and equipment
to check the outbreaks of disease.
	   Health Minister Zhang Wenkang warned on Friday that colds,
stomach illnesses, dysentery, hepatitis and diseases carried by
waterborne parasites are on the rise and the trend is likely to
worsen over the next three months, state media reported.
	   Soldiers rushed to close a breach that opened in the third and
last line of levees keeping the Nen River out of the Daqing oil
field and city, state radio reported.
	   Since overwhelming the dike Thursday night, the Nen has washed
away a highway and inundated nearly half the area's farmland, the
Liberation Daily reported. More threatening to the oil field was a
brimming reservoir on its eastern edge.
	   ``If the weather gods don't smile and we get another torrential
soaking, it might unleash flooding,'' the newspaper said.
	   Xinhua said that oil production was being maintained despite the
inundation of 1,443 oil wells and the complete shutdown of 282.
	   In Harbin, Heilongjiang's capital 150 kilometers (100 miles) to
the southeast, the Songhua River continued to swell to ever higher
record levels and began undermining the 26-kilometer (15-mile)
levee by the city's industrial heart.
	   Foundations under a riverside pumping station and apartment
complex gave way overnight and residents were evacuated, state
television reported. Video footage showed a crack running down the
two-story pumping station building, part of which sank 30
centimeters (a foot) into the saturated ground.
	   Trucks brought more soldiers into Harbin on Saturday morning to
reinforce the levee.
	   ``As long as the dikes are all right, we are all right and our
homes are safe,'' read one banner in the city.
	   Relief officials are worried that many flood victims in the
northeast, known in the West as Manchuria, may not be able to move
back into their homes before the onset of winter in mid-October,
the China Youth Daily said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-China-Floods, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
