<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-US Bombings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serbia decries U.S. bombings, but draws parallel with Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
crisis &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serbia has decried the U.S. bombings
of suspected terrorist targets in Sudan and Afghanistan as an act
of aggression against two sovereign states.
	   But at the same time, a late Friday commentary on state-run
Serbian television appeared to derive from the air raids a
justification to crack down on separatist rebels in Kosovo whom
Serbia calls ``terrorists.''
	   Serbia, the dominant republic of rump Yugoslavia, has been
confronted with a possible military intervention by NATO for its
offensives against armed ethnic Albanians militants, including many
civilians, in its southern province.
	   Speaking of ``an aggression against two sovereign states,'' the
commentary asked rhetorically whether the U.S. move was ``in
accordance with international rules of conduct,'' making clear it
was not.
	   State-run television is the chief mouthpiece of the authorities
dominated by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
	   The commentary spoke of ``a precedent ... to fight against
terrorism in territories of other states, in violation of their
integrity and sovereignty.''
	   However, the U.S. action ``can be seen as a broad authorization
for every country to respond to terrorism,'' said the commentary,
also published Sunday in pro-government papers in Belgrade.
	   ``Our country, too, is faced with terrorism and separatism,'' it
said, referring to the Kosovo rebels fighting for independence.
``Muslim fundamentalism, its aggressiveness and intolerance ...
generates many conflicts and terrorist acts in the world.''
	   A majority of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, who account for 90
percent of the two million population, are Muslims.
	   (ms/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
