<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-US Bombings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peace singers protest at U.S. Embassy in London
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Some 100 demonstrators chanted and sang peace
songs outside the U.S. Embassy on Saturday morning in protest at
American strikes in Sudan and Afghanistan.
	   In another move, a small group of governing Labor Party
lawmakers and antinuclear campaigners denounced Prime Minister Tony
Blair's backing of the strikes against what the U.S. said were
terror bases and nerve gas plant.
	   ``State terrorism by the United States is no better than the
dreadful happenings in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam,'' said Tam
Dalyell, a lawmaker who signed the protest.
	   ``It reinforces the negative image of the United States and
Britain in the Arab, African and Asian world and pushes moderate
people into support for extremism,'' Dalyell.
	   The U.S. strikes followed bombings of the American embassies in
the Kenyan capital, Nairobi, and the Tanzanian capital, Dar es
Salaam.
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
