<HEADER>
w2412 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Congo-Rebels 7thLd-Writethru   08-22 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Rebels, 7th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Congo rebels say they downed two Zimbabwean warplanes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs, RECASTS to raise rebel advances on the capital. UPDATES
to incorporate BC-Congo-Diplomats; ADDS comments from Mumengi and
Ugandan president, Congo's denial of Angolan troop support. Edits
to conform. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; With Zimbabwe-Congo, Congo-Diplomats &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GOMA, Congo (AP) _ Rebels pushing within 30 kilometers (18
miles) of Congo's capital said on Saturday they downed two
warplanes allied with embattled President Laurent Kabila's loyalist
forces.
	   ``Just this morning, we have shot down two of their jet
fighters,'' said Bizima Karaha, Kabila's former foreign minister
who defected to the rebels.
	   Karaha said the planes were shot down over rebel territory in
Congo's southwest. The report could not be independently confirmed.
	   Amid mounting threats and acts of war, South Africa scrambled to
salvage a crumbling regional peace summit it was hosting in
Pretoria in a bid to forestall an escalation in Congo's rebellion
around sub-Saharan Africa.
	   The talks were being snubbed by two key players _ Zimbabwe's
President Robert Mugabe and Kabila, who deployed reinforcements to
defend the Congolese capital.
	   Mugabe is backing Kabila with troops and military equipment.
There were conflicting reports he had also sent fighter jets.
	   In Kinshasa, the government moved to expel two French diplomats
accused of inappropriate conduct.
	   State-controlled National Radio-Television said the embassy's
First Secretary Philippe Parise and his assistant Daniel Guilbert
had 24 hours to leave the country.
	   The move follows reports that Congolese armed forces fired on
French helicopters that overflew the capital Friday night as part
of an evacuation of French civilians in Kinshasa.
	   The government in recent days has accused France and the West of
complicity in the rebellion launched three weeks ago.
	   The rebels say they have marched to within 30 kilometers (18
miles) south of Kinshasa, but did not specify where they had shot
down the two jet fighters.
	   There was no immediate comment on the downed aircraft from
Kinshasa, but a former military intelligence officer with close
government ties said Kabila's army had recently acquired fighters
being flown by either Cuban or Angolan pilots.
	   ``We know that the government does have air support
capabilities,'' the officer said on condition of anonymity.
	   Speaking from the rebel stronghold of Goma, Karaha said the
planes were from Zimbabwe.
	   But a duty officer at the Zimbabwe Air Force operations center
said the downed planes were unlikely Zimbabwean: ``I don't think we
have any fighters up there,'' the officer said, refusing to give
his name.
	   Although the rebels earlier this week offered to negotiate a
cease-fire, Kahara said the attacks Saturday demonstrated the
rebels' resolve to continue fighting as long as outside forces were
involved.
	   ``It should be understood that the people of Congo are ready to
resist any foreign aggression,'' he said of the reported arrival of
more than 600 troop reinforcements from Zimbabwe and a contingent
from Angola in support of Kabila.
	   Angola has declined to comment, but eyewitnesses in Angola's
enclave of Cabinda bordering southwestern Congo said Angolan troops
and military equipment were moving toward the border. Cabinda
governor Amaru Tati reportedly said that defensive border measures
were being taken, but did not elaborate.
	   Information Minister Didier Mumengi denied that Angolan troops
had arrived, and said when they do it will be publicly announced.
	   ``When Angola sends its troops that will be a big day, as was
the case with Zimbabwe,'' Mumengi said on state-controlled
television.
	   The rebels themselves are said to have the backing of
neighboring Rwanda and Uganda.
	   The peace negotiations in South Africa appeared doomed as
Zimbabwe said its president was boycotting the talks because it did
not include other countries favoring military support to Kabila.
	   Congo's president asked for a delay in the talks, but the
government instead sent Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo and
Transport Minister Henri Mova Sakani on his behalf.
	   Although the leaders of Rwanda and Uganda were believed
attending, Uganda's President Yoweri Museveni threatened to join
the rebel side if other foreign forces do not withdraw.
	   ``Uganda may be forced after due consultations, to take its own
independent action in the protection of its own security,''
Museveni said in the statement released in his capital.
	   In Kinshasa, hundreds of angry protesters marched down the
city's main June 30th Boulevard. Denouncing Rwanda and the West,
the demonstrators vowed to back Kabila.
	   The rebels accuse Kabila of power-grabbing, tribalism and
mismanagement of his vast African nation.
	   Karaha accused Kabila of ordering the execution of 20,000 ethnic
Tutsis in Moba in southeastern Congo, a move which he said prompted
the rebels to advance to the Lake Tanganyika port of Kalemie.
 &UR; (buros/ids/gam)
</TEXT>
