<HEADER>
w2413 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TropicalWeather 3rdLd-Writethru   08-22 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tropical Weather, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0832 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bonnie becomes hurricane; Bahamians in southeast batten down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with Bonnie getting stronger while
Charley warnings called off; Howard strengthening but expected to
dissipate over open sea; new coordinates. EDITS. At 11 a.m. (1500
GMT) Bonnie was centered near 22.7 north latitude, 70.6 west
longitude. Charley's center was near 28.4 north, 97.9 west.
Howard's center near 13.8 north, 106.2 west. &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Graphic &QL; 
 &UR; By JESSICA ROBERTSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) _ Bonnie strengthened into the Atlantic
season's first hurricane Saturday and headed toward sparsely
populated Bahamian islands, on a route that could threaten the
southeastern United States.
	   Another storm was gaining strength in the Pacific Ocean.
	   ``It's definitely going to happen. The southeastern portion (of
the Bahamas) is going to be hit today,'' meteorologist Dave Chorney
said from the U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami.
	   On Crooked Island, fuel distributor Daisy Scavella said the sun
was shining as residents battened down windows.
	   ``I guess we're going to have a good blow,'' she said. People on
the low-lying islands were most concerned about flooding.
	   Bahamian radio warned the islands' fishing fleet and yachters to
make for safe port. The islands' meteorological department said
Bonnie would hit landfall in the southeast later Saturday and pass
by Long Island, Eleuthera and the Abacos over the next 48 to 72
hours.
	   ``People along the southeastern U.S. should pay attention to its
progress,'' said Jerry Jarrell, director of National Hurricane
Center.
	   He said winds could reach 100 mph (160 kph) by Monday. Chorney
said the worst thunderstorms were on the northern side of Bonnie,
in the open Atlantic.
	   Bonnie was about 95 miles (150 kilometers) north-northwest of
Turk Island at 11 a.m. (15:00 GMT) with sustained winds of 85 mph
(140 kph) and higher gusts. It was moving west-northwest near 15
mph (24 kph) with a motion expected to continue through most of
Sunday.
	   The National Hurricane Center said Bonnie could eventually
become a Category 3 storm with winds of more than 111 mph (178 kph)
capable of causing extensive damage.
	   The Bahamian government Saturday posted a hurricane watch for
the northwest islands and hurricane warnings covered the British
Turks and Caicos islands and the southeastern and central Bahamas.
	   ``Preparations to protect life and property should be rushed to
completion,'' the hurricane center urged.
	   North Florida is more likely than any other region to be hit if
the storm reaches the mainland. Still, the storm could veer out to
sea and miss the U.S. coast entirely, Jarrell said.
	   Meanwhile, another weather system that threatened parts of Texas
lost power Saturday.
	   All warnings were discontinued when Tropical Storm Charley
weakened to a depression, though the hurricane center warned small
vessels to remain in port along the northwestern Gulf of Mexico
until winds and waves that reached 10 feet (3 meters) subside.
	   The threat of heavy rains and a storm surge hustled the
evacuation of thousands of people from oil rigs in the Gulf of
Mexico.
	   Shrimp boats hustled back to shore Friday night, crews sighting
waves up to 15 feet (4.5 meters).
	   As it moved into Texas, Matagorda Island to the south was hit
the hardest with 9 inches (23 centimeters) of rain and 70 mph (110
kmh) wind gusts around 2:30 a.m. (0730 GMT). The depression was
centered near latitude 28.4 north, longitude 97.5 west at 11 a.m.
(15:00 GMT).
	   Also Friday, a storm in the Pacific Ocean reached hurricane
strength but remained far off the Mexican coast. Hurricane Howard
intensified Saturday, packing winds of 110 mph (176 kph) with
higher gusts. The hurricane center said it was expected to get even
stronger but anticipated that it would dissipate out in the Pacific
later Sunday.
	   Authorities closed the Acapulco port and warned ships to be
cautious of high waves along the southwestern Mexican coast.
	   Howard was centered about 400 miles (645 kilometers) southwest
of Acapulco at 11 a.m. (15:00 GMT), at latitude 13.8 north,
longitude 106.2 west moving slowly northwest at about 12 mph (19
kph).
	   The Atlantic Basin typically has nine tropical storms each year
with six of them becoming hurricanes, two of them intense. In 1997,
there were seven named storms, three hurricanes and one intense
hurricane. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
