<SLUG> BC-Germany-Poland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German, Polish soldiers join in historic swearing-in
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GUBIN, Poland (AP) _ German and Polish recruits held joint
swearing-in ceremonies for the first time Saturday, a new sign that
the two nations are overcoming enmity and divisions sowed by World
War II.
	   Both defense ministers walked across a pontoon bridge built by
the troops to witness the oath-taking on opposite sides of the Oder
River, which divides Poland and Germany.
	   ``All this symbolizes a new age in the relationship between our
two peoples,'' German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe said in a
speech.
	   ``Today's ceremony will contribute to the tightening of ties
between the two armies that will soon be allies,'' said his Polish
counterpart, Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
	   About 5,000 people filled the market square of Gubin as 103
young Poles took the oath. The town was bedecked in Polish and
German flags.
	   Then, 263 German recruits were sworn in at Guben just across the
river in Germany. Recruits from each country also took part in the
other side's ceremony.
	   The symbolism was especially strong because Nazi Germany's
brutal six-year occupation still resonates with many Poles.
	   Now, Germany is Poland's key partner in building bridges to the
West after decades of Cold War isolation.
	   Saturday's ceremony was ``testimony of our return to the family
of countries that we always believed we belong to,'' Onyszkiewicz
said.
	   Since signing a landmark friendship treaty in 1991, both
countries have boosted trade and defense ties and joined together
in fighting last summer's Oder floods.
	   Championed by Germany, Poland was among the first former Warsaw
Pact countries invited to join NATO and is on the short list for
early European Union entry as well.
	   Ruehe said Poland has made impressive progress toward
integrating its army into NATO. More than 1,000 Polish officers
have already been trained, mainly in Germany and the United States,
he said.
	   (tc)	   
</TEXT>
