<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Rare Plant,0443 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Discovery of rare plant at Snowbasin complicates Olympics
</HEADLINE>
preparation &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) _ Preparations for the Olympics at Snowbasin
resort in northern Utah may be complicated by the discovery of a
rare type of mustard plant on the craggy terrain where the men's
downhill race course will begin.
	   Through genetic testing, scientists determined that the
lime-green plants with yellow flowers are a unique species, likely
to be called Burke mustard (Draba burkei). Previously the plants
were thought to be part of the Maguire mustard (Draba maguirei)
species.
	   The discovery isn't expected to significantly disrupt
Snowbasin's preparations for the 2002 Winter Games. But it could
cause some delays in a number of construction projects, including
grading work on the upper slope of the men's downhill course,
construction of the start house where racers push off, excavation
of a water line for snowmaking and installation of a ridgetop
communications tower.
	   ``It does change things,'' Ruth Monahan, the Forest Service's
Ogden District ranger, said Thursday. ``Our hope is that through
the mitigation measures we develop, we can complete the projects.''
	   The Maguire mustard is found only in northern Utah, in limited
numbers, and is listed as a sensitive species by the Forest
Service. Because Snowbasin's plants are not related to the Maguire
mustards, both species' numbers are smaller than previously
estimated.
	   There are believed to be 5,000 to 6,000 of the plants at
Snowbasin, making it the largest population of the newly described
species.
	   The Forest Service has known for some time that small
populations of mustard plants existed in northern Utah and that
botanists were uncertain whether they represented one species or
two.
	   The uncertainty was eliminated when scientists affiliated with
the Utah Museum of Natural History's Garrett Herbarium confirmed
through chromosome, enzyme and DNA studies that two species exist.
	   ``The (Burke mustard) seems to be a pretty viable species,''
herbarium curator Michael Windham said. ``But the Forest Service
has estimated there are only 10,000 (plants) total. As your
population drops and becomes more fragmented, it really represents
a threat to the species. We don't want to lose many plants or we
may exceed minimum viability levels.''
	   The Forest Service and U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service have
agreed that the loss of up to 500 plants as a result of the
Olympics projects would be acceptable.
	   The Forest Service plans to remove selective plants and collect
seeds from sites where the plants will be disturbed.
</TEXT>
