<SLUG> BC-Hungary-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hungary postpones bidding for fighter aircraft
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Hungary is postponing the announcement
of a tender for the purchase of new military aircraft, Hungarian
Premier Viktor Orban said Saturday.
	   ``The performance of the Hungarian economy does not, at this
time, allow for the purchase of new fighter aircraft,'' Orban said
at a military air show in Kecskemet, 80 kilometers (50 miles)
southeast of Budapest.
	   Hungary hopes to be formally admitted to NATO next year, and it
was hoping to be able to acquire at least a few state-of-the-art
jet fighters.
	   It came as something of a surprise when Gen. Ferenc Vegh, the
Hungarian Chief of Staff, told television news Friday evening that
``Hungary is postponing announcement of the tender until 2003.''
	   Vegh said that after 2003 dlrs one billion will be earmarked for
the purchase of 30 jet fighters.
	   Hungary's defense establishment was looking at the American
McDonnell-Douglas-made F-18s, Lockheed Martin's F-16s, and Sweden's
Saab Grippen.
	   France's Mirage and Russia's MiG 29s may also be competing.
	   The technical condition of the Hungarian Air Force is rated bad,
and Hungarian pilots spend significantly fewer hours flying than
their NATO counterparts.
	   While it is common for a NATO pilot to fly an annual 150-200
hours, it is only 30 hours for military pilots in Hungary.
	   The country's air space theoretically is defended by 28 MiG 29s,
many of which are immobile due to a lack of spare parts.
	   (ab/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
