<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-British Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Charlton wins 5-0 to go top as giants tie
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Promoted Charlton charged to the top of the
Premier League after a 5-0 crushing of Southampton Saturday with
Clive Mendonca scoring three times in the last 25 minutes.
	   Alan Curbishley's team, returning for the first time since 1990
after gaining a Premier League place through last season's division
one playoffs, overwhelmed the Saints at The Valley, a refurbished
stadium which last saw top flight soccer in 1957.
	   John Robinson fired the Addicks ahead after only three minutes,
new signing Neil Redfearn added a second before Mendonca took over
in the second half.
	   The much-traveled 29-year-old striker was brought down by Saints
goalkeeper Paul Jones who was ordered off for the foul. Mendonca
struck home the 65th minute penalty, added the fourth nine minutes
from the end and then scored the fifth in the final minute to send
Southampton sliding down to last of the 20 clubs.
	   Charlton stormed to the top on a day when the big teams were
held in tied games. Defending titlist Arsenal went to Anfield and
drew 0-0, Manchester United managed only a goal-less tie at West
Ham despite the debut of 12.6 million pound (dlrs 20 million)
Dwight Yorke, while Chelsea and Newcastle tied 1-1.
	   Liverpool striker Michael Owen signed a new contract Saturday to
keep him at Anfield for five years but had few chances against a
well-organized Arsenal defense missing its captain and central
strongman, Tony Adams, who was injured.
	   Ray Parlour missed an easy close-range chance for the Gunners
while Liverpool's United States international 'keeper Brad Friedel
made two brilliant saves to thwart Nicolas Anelka.
	   Yorke had few openings against the Hammers at Upton Park in
partnership with Andy Cole as the Reds looked far short of the form
that brought four league titles in five seasons.
	   At Stamford Bridge, Nigerian international Celestine Babayaro
fired Chelsea ahead but Swedish striker Andreas Andersson leveled
for Newcastle so that both teams are still looking for their first
win the campaign.
	   Wimbledon, surprise leader after the opening day, was held 0-0
by Derby at Pride Park and slipped to third while Leicester, which
gained a 2-2 tie at Manchester United last weekend, moved into
second place after downing Everton 2-0 at Filbert Street with goals
by veteran striker Tony Cottee and Muzzy Izzet.
	   Tottenham tumbled 3-0 at home to Sheffield Wednesday and the
pressure is already on Swiss coach Christian Gross after two losses
and six goals conceded. Peter Atherton, Paolo Di Canio and Andy
Hinchcliffe netted Wednesday's goals at White Hart Lane where the
home fans were leaving in droves long before the end.
	   Steve Stone netted Nottingham Forest's winner in a 1-0 victory
over neighbor Coventry at the City Ground.
	   Saturday's results mean that no team will have maximum points
even after only two games.
	   The two teams in action Sunday, Aston Villa and Middlesbrough,
and Monday's rivals Leeds and Blackburn, were all involved in
goal-less ties last weekend.
	   After two games, Arsenal places fourth, Liverpool fifth, while
Manchester United is 10th and Chelsea is third from last after a
loss and a tie.
	   Norwich powered to the top of division two after a 4-2 beating
of Queens Park Rangers. Birmingham, promoted Watford and Birmingham
also have 100 percent records from three games.
	   Birmingham won 2-0 at Sheffield United, Graham Taylor's Watford
triumphed 4-1 at Bristol City and Wolves scored a 1-0 victory over
Swindon.
	   In Scotland, Hearts replaced Aberdeen atop the Premier League by
beating the north-east team 2-0 at Tynecastle. Champion Celtic hit
back from a goal down to beat Dundee United 2-1 and Rangers gained
a 3-1 win at Kilmarnock.
