w2482 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-USBombings 2ndLdWritethru   08-22 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-US Bombings, 2nd Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serbia decries U.S. bombings, but draws parallel with Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
crisis &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to UPDATE with Yugoslav Foreign Ministry statement;
TIGHTENS. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslavia officially condemned
Saturday U.S. bombings of suspected terrorist targets in Sudan and
Afghanistan, suggesting it was inadmissible to support at the same
time ``terrorists'' in Kosovo.
	   Yugoslav media and officials have always referred to the Kosovo
Liberation Army fighting for independence of the Serbian province
as ``terrorists.''
	   Yugoslavia ``condemns all forms of terrorism ... but
internatioal terrorism can be successfully uprooted only by
respecting basic principles of international law,'' said the
statement carried by the official Tanjug news agency.
	   It denounced unilateral actions ``to protect terrorists and
include them in talks in one case,'' a reference to Kosovo, while
``using most destructive weapons against terrorist targets in
foreign, sovereign countries.''
	   The statement cited ``a conflict of principles in international
relations, (which) are counterproductive and unacceptable.''
	   ``Attempts to divide terrorists into `good' and `bad' ones are
not based on principles, but on ...unilateral asessments of one's
own interests,'' the statement said, referring to the U.S. action.
	   A commentary late Friday on state-run Serbian television, which
was also published Saturday, appeared to derive from the U.S. air
raids a justification to crack down on separatist rebels in Kosovo.
	   Serbia, the dominant republic of rump Yugoslavia, has been
confronted with a possible military intervention by NATO for its
offensives against armed ethnic Albanians militants, including many
civilians, in its southern province.
	   Speaking of ``an aggression against two sovereign states,'' the
commentary asked rhetorically whether the U.S. move was ``in
accordance with international rules of conduct,'' making clear it
was not.
	   However, it said, the U.S. action ``can be seen as a broad
authorization for every country to respond to terrorism,'' said the
commentary, also published Saturday in pro-government papers in
Belgrade.
	   ``Our country, too, is faced with terrorism and separatism,'' it
said, referring to the Kosovo rebels fighting for independence.
	   (ms/rp)
</TEXT>
