<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Track-Europeans, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Drechsler wins fourth gold, Jackson third straight
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with women's long jump going to Drechsler &QL; 
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Heike Drechsler became only the third
athlete in history to win four straight European Championship
titles in the same event when she clinched the gold medal in the
women's long jump Saturday.
	   Colin Jackson of Britain won his third straight in the men's
110-meter hurdles in a championship record of 13.02 seconds. His
old mark of 13.04 came in 1994.
	   Jackson first set the record in the semifinals earlier in the
day and matched it in the final. It's the third fastest in the
world this year.
	   Drechsler soared 7.16 meters, the fourth longest jump in the
world this year, behind three by American Marion Jones, whose best
is 7.31.
	   Christine Arron powered home in the anchor leg to lead France to
victory in the women's 4x100-meter relay and clinch her second gold
medal of competition.
	   The 100-meter champion with orange-dyed hair pulled her team
from third to first with an astonishing last leg. The French won in
42.59 seconds.
	   Darren Campbell and Doug Walker also picked up their second
golds when they ran in the winning British team in the men's 4x100
relay. Campbell was the 100-meter champion, Walker the 200 gold
medalist.
	   Julian Golding, bronze medalist in the 200, ran the anchor leg
for Britain, which clocked 38.52 for the gold. France took the
silver in 38.87, while Poland was third in 38.98.
	   With stunning acceleration in the last 50 meters, Arron flew
past Russia's anchor Irina Privalova, who stared in disbelief as
Arron sprinted past her.
	   Privalova, 100-meter silver medalist and 200 champion, lost her
second place as well when Andrea Philipp of Germany nipped her on
the line. Germany finished in 42.68, while Russia clocked 42.73 for
the bronze.
	   Drechsler, a former Olympic and world champion and former world
record holder, was jumping healthy for the first time in three
years, after having surgery on both Achilles tendons.
	   Only two former Soviet athletes had previously won four straight
European titles: Janis Lusis in the men's javelin, 1962-1971, and
Nadezhda Chizhova in the women's shot put, 1966-74.
	   Fiona May of Italy, Olympic silver medalist and bronze medalist
in last year's worlds, took the silver with a jump of 7.11. World
champion Lydmila Galkina of Russia was third at 7.06.
	   In the men's hurdles, Jackson cruised home without being pushed,
but failed in his declared goal of going under 13 seconds.
	   Falk Balzer of Germany won the silver in 13.12, while Robin
Korving of the Netherlands took the bronze in 13.20.
	   Maksim Tarasov of Russia cleared 5.81 meters to win the men's
pole vault. Tim Lobinger of Germany was second with the same height
but with more attempts overall, while Jean Galfione of France, the
Olympic champion, had to settle for bronze at 5.76.
	   In the morning, Stefano Baldini overcame rainy and windy
conditions to lead an Italian medal sweep in the men's marathon.
	   ``For the last month my coach and I have believed that this gold
would be mine,'' Baldini said. ``He said that he could see victory
in my eyes before the start and my heart also told me this medal
would be mine.''
	   Baldini, who was running stride for stride with fellow Italian
Danilo Goffi at the 40-kilometer mark, pulled away before entering
the Nep stadium and won in 2 hours 12 minutes 01 second.
	   Goffi was second in 2:12.11, and another Italian, Vincenzo
Modica, took the bronze in 2:12.53. Three Spanish runners took the
next three places.
	   ``After 37 kilometers I knew that I would beat my compatriots to
the finish,'' Baldini said.
	   After a week of mostly sunshine and warm weather in the
Hungarian capital, the conditions cooled considerably after a night
of storms.
	   Baldini and Goffi ran easily, however, and both were fresh
enough to celebrate by hugging each other after the
42.195-kilometer race.
	   Winner of the world half-marathon title in 1996, Baldini, 27,
was second in the 1997 London Marathon and third in the New York
race that same year.
	   Baldini is the eighth of 10 brothers, and his older brother
Marco is also a marathon runner.
	   Wilson Kipketer, world champion and record-holder, did just
enough to qualify for the final in the men's 800 by finishing third
in his semifinal heat.
	   (ns)	   
</TEXT>
