<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIreland-INLA Attacks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Irish National Liberation Army's 23-year record of bloodshed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Northern Ireland, NIreland-INLA Text &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The Irish National Liberation Army,
which called a ``complete cease-fire'' Saturday, has left a long
trail of blood since its foundation in 1975. The milestones:
	    &UR; 1975
	   Feb. 25: Member of ``Official'' IRA, Sean Fox, shot dead in
Divis Flats, west Belfast. Start of long feud with the original
branch of IRA, which had called a cease-fire in 1972.
	   May 24: INLA kills first police officer with booby-trap bombs.
	    &UR; 1979
	   March 30: Under-car booby trap kills British lawmaker Airey
Neave, Margaret Thatcher's adviser on Northern Ireland, as he
drives out of Parliament parking lot in London.
	    &UR; 1982
	   Sept. 16: INLA bomb hidden in drainpipe in Divis Flats kills a
British soldier and two local boys aged 14 and 12.
	   Dec. 6: Bomb in rural Droppin' Well disco kills 11 off-duty
soldiers and six civilians.
	   Dec. 12: Unarmed INLA members Seamus Grew and Rodney Carroll
shot dead by police at road checkpoint.
	    &UR; 1987
	   Jan. 20: INLA internal feud between Army Council and General
Headquarters factions starts with two members shot dead in Irish
Republic hotel. Nine more fatally shot in coming weeks,
contributing to foundation of rival Irish People's Liberation
Organization (IPLO).
	    &UR; 1993
	   Oct. 31: Provisional IRA wipes out IPLO in single night, killing
one member and shooting dozens more in the arms and legs.
	    &UR; 1994
	   Feb. 10: INLA's commander in the early 1980s, Dominic ``Mad
Dog'' McGlinchey, shot dead by rivals in front of his teen-age son.
His wife had earlier been murdered.
	    &UR; 1997
	   Jan. 31: INLA commander Gino Gallagher shot fatally through back
of head in new feud between ``Army Council'' and GHQ'' factions.
Six more die.
	   Dec. 27: Three imprisoned INLA members use smuggled handguns to
kill Northern Ireland's most notorious Protestant militant, Billy
``King Rat'' Wright. Assassination unleashes string of retaliatory
attacks against Catholics.
	    &UR; 1998
	   June 25: INLA claims responsibility for car bomb in border town
of Newtownhamilton that wounds 11, on same day as Northern Ireland
voters elect members to a new compromise government.
	   Aug. 22: INLA announces cease-fire through Willie Gallagher,
Gino's brother.
	   (sp-acw)
</TEXT>
