<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-German Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Munich, Kaiserslautern, Leverkusen 1-2-3 again
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Bayern Munich and FC Kaiserslautern both coasted
to victory Saturday and found themselves right where they ended
last season _ atop the Bundesliga.
	   Munich, second last year, dismantled MSV Duisburg 3-1 with an
impressive performance to take over the top slot after two rounds,
while defending champion Kaiserslautern breezed past
Moenchengladbach 2-1 to move to the second slot.
	   Leverkusen, third last season, also took that position despite a
1-1 draw against SC Freiburg. Two other traditional league
powerhouses bounced back from opening day losses.
	   Borussia Dortmund, its rebuilt lineup showing signs of
coalescing, blasted Hertha Berlin 3-0 and defensive-minded Schalke
stopped Stuttgart 1-0.
	   Munich, which chased Kaiserslautern all last season, dominated
Duisburg and seized a 2-1 lead in the 63rd minute on Thomas
Strunz's powerful shot from 16 meters.
	   Munich, heavy title favorites, displayed more imagination on
offense than in recent years with new acquisition Stefan Effenberg
directing the offense.
	   ``The days when they had to make excuses about how they played
seem to be past,'' said former German national team player Paul
Breitner. ``They seem to finally have a leader.''
	   Effenberg, picked up from Moenchengladbach this season,
converted an 86th minute penalty and striker Carsten Jancker also
scored in the 20th.
	   Munich could have run up the score, but midfielder Mario Basler
was denied one goal on a questionable foul and a second attempt
cracked against the post. Marcus Wedau scored Duisburg's goal in
the 23rd minute.
	   Kaiserslautern, a surprise champion last season, relied again on
the scoring prowress of German international Olaf Marschall in its
home opener.
	   Marschall, the league's second leading marksman last season,
struck in the 62nd following teammate Martin Wagner's score off a
free kick 20 minutes earlier. Seven minutes before the whistle,
Sladjan Asanin put Moenchengladbach on the scoreboard.
	   Eintracht Frankfurt also fell 3-2 to 1860 Munich at home, while
in Friday's matches Nuremberg edged Bremen 3-2 and Rostock and
Wolfsburg played to 3-3.
	   Schalke, after a stunning 3-0 loss to Moenchengladbach last
week, this time showed its usual stifling defense against
Stuttgart.
	   Martin Max's 50th career goal _ a roller as he slid between two
defenders _ provided the game-winner in the 55th minute.
	   Bosnia's Sergei Barbarez and Bachirou Salou, Dortmund's new
strikers, provided the firepower as the team handed 32-year-old
Michael Skibbe his first triumph as the side's coach.
	   ``After our 1-0 loss to Stuttgart last week we were under a lot
of pressure,'' admitted Skibbe, expected to guide the former
Champions Cup winner back to its former glory. ``Luckily we found
our rythmn.''
	   Barbarez's 39th minute shot was deflected into the net by a
Berlin player and Dortmund's confidence soared afterwards in front
of 67,500 spectators at expanded Westfalenstadium.
	   Barbarez, assisted by Juergen Kohler's pass, struck again in the
52nd minute while Salou scored 12 minutes later on a keeper
mistake.
	   Leverkusen salvaged a draw when Stefan Beinlich scored in the
75th, four minutes after Alexander Iaschwili put Freiburg ahead
1-0.
	   Bernhard Winkler converted a 75th minute penalty, breaking a 2-2
tie as 1860 Munich beat Frankfurt. Teammates Daniel Borimirow and
Abderrahim Ouakili also scored.
	   Frankfurt's goals came from Alexander Schur and Ralf Weber.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
</TEXT>
