<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-South Africa-Australia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa takes Tri-Nations rugby championship
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) _ Fullback Percy Montgomery scored on
five penalties and two conversions Saturday to lead South Africa to
a 29-15 victory over Australia in the Tri-Nations championship
game.
	   The Southern Hemisphere championship was narrow throughout, with
the Springboks leading only 16-12 at haftime.
	   The victory was the Boks' first trophy under coach Nick Mallett
and underlined a remarkable rennaissance since he took charge of
the team.
	   The result put Australia second place in the Tri-Nations
tournament, with New Zeland coming in third.
	   South Africa took the lead in the second minute when Montgomery
landed a penalty.
	   Two minutes later, Wallaby fullback Matt Burke replied in kind.
	   Tighthead prop Adrian Garvey then scored in the seventh minute
after skipper Gary Teichmann had taken a line-out ball and the Boks
mauled their way through.
	   Garvey finished off a move which he was set up by coming up in
support after a great break from left wing Pieter Rossouw.
	   Montgomery's conversion took the Springboks to 10-3, but Burke's
kick drew the Aussies back to 6-10.
	   Thereafter South Africa wasted a few opportunities to increase
their lead. They ran two goalable penalties while on the attack,
and at their third opportunity finally decided to give it to
Montgomery, who made it 13-6.
	   The Wallabies answered with two penalties by Burke which brought
them within a point of the Springboks.
	   After the Wallabies had strayed off-side on the half-way line,
Montgomery landed a sensational 50-meter (yard) strike to make it
16-12 at the half.
	   Australia raised their game after the interval, and Burke again
brought Australia to within a single point in the 51st minute with
his fifth penalty.
	   Montgomery restored the Boks' 4-point cushion with a superbly
struck penalty from 45 meters (yards) out in the 57th minute.
	   The Bok fullback took the Springboks to 22-15 with his fifth
penalty after Australia had come in from the wrong side.
	   Springboks replacement flanker Bobby Skinstad scored under the
posts in the 70th minute and Montgomery converted to take South
Africa to the 29-15 final score.
	   The win marks a comeback for the world-champion Springboks.
	   After suffering their worst test defeat in their history last
year, a 55-35 embarrassment at the hands of New Zealand, the
Springboks are on the way back to supremacy of the sport.
	   The Tri-Nations championship comes on the heels of a record
96-13 win over Wales and comprehensive victories over England and
Ireland earlier in the season.
	   (sapa-aos)
</TEXT>
