<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Kidnap King,0472 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican gang leader lists his profession as `Kidnapping'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GLORIA PEREZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALMOLOYA DE JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) _ Asked by the judge to state
his profession, Daniel Arizmendi Lopez curtly responded:
``Kidnapping.''
	   Judge Armando Baez Espinoza of the 2nd Federal Criminal Court
stared in disbelief at the man dubbed the ``ear-lopper'' for
allegedly sending ransom notes attached to his victims' ears.
	   Judge Baez asked Arizmendi to repeat himself. He replied: ``I do
kidnappings ... I am a kidnapper.''
	   After the eight-hour pretrial hearing at the maximum security
prison in Almoloya de Juarez, near Mexico City, Arizmendi and his
mistress, Dulce Maria Paz Venegas, refused to plead innocent or
guilty to the charges.
	   Arizmendi said he was very tired after three days of questioning
by police at the Attorney General's Office.
	   Their court-appointed lawyer, Maria Eugenia Lopez Fuentes, asked
the hearing to be recessed until next Thursday so she could have
time to prepare her case. The judge agreed and ordered them held
without bail.
	   Arizmendi is accused of kidnapping, racketeering, laundering
money from ransom payments and illegal possession of firearms.
Lopez is accused of racketeering and money laundering.
	   Arizmendi said he was born in Miacatlan, in western Morelos
state. He gave his age as 40, and said he had a high school
education. He said he did not smoke or use drugs and stopped
drinking alcohol two years ago.
	   He also admitted serving time for car theft in 1985, before he
went into kidnapping.
	   Arizmendi, a former police officer in neighboring Morelos state,
and Lopez were arrested Monday night in Naucalpan, a northwestern
suburb of Mexico City, after a 10-month manhunt. Police found dlrs
1 million in cash in the car they were driving.
	   According to prosecutors, Arizmendi headed a kidnapping gang
numbering at least 38, with activities stretching into at least
four states. The members allegedly included both former and active
police officers.
	   Some authorities say Arizmendi's was involved in as many as 200
abductions over a period of five years, all of wealthy businessmen
or their family members.
	   The latest victim, a wealthy business executive, was shot dead
after he was kidnapped Aug. 6 in Queretaro state.
	   Police had been searching for Arizmendi since October. On May
21, Arizmendi narrowly escaped a raid on a safe house in
Cuernavaca, 35 miles (55 kilometers) south of Mexico City.
	   His son and daughter-in-law were arrested in that raid, as well
as his wife, a former nurse allegedly assigned the task of slicing
off the ears forwarded to the victims' families.
	   The three gave authorities information that, along with
intelligence gathered from phone taps, helped track down Arizmendi.
</TEXT>
