<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-European Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sweden's Gronberg moves three ahead
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) _ Mathias Gronberg rolled in a 30-foot
eagle putt at the last for a 5-under 67 Saturday to take a 3-stroke
lead going into the final round of the 1.25 million (dlrs 2
million) European Open.
	   Chasing a first price of 208,300 pounds (dlrs 344,000) _
Europe's second richest prize _ the 28-year-old Swede is out to
eclipse some of the continent's big Ryder Cup names with players
like Colin Montgomerie and Seve Ballesteros already missing the
cut, Jose Maria Olazabal 17 strokes back and Lee Westwood likely to
pull out after three rounds with a hip injury.
	   Gronberg, whose only European tour victory came three years ago,
leads American Craig Hainline by three strokes and is six ahead of
third place Darren Clarke, Bernhard Langer and Jose Rivero.
	   Hainline stayed in contention with a 69, Clarke had a 70 and
joint halfway leaders Langer and Rivero slipped back with 3-over
75s.
	   Gale-force winds and heavy rain are forecast for Sunday's final
ran and Gronberg hopes his lead is big enough for him to hold on.
	   ``There are 18 holes left, and I'll try to take it shot-by-shot
and stay calm,'' the Swede said. ``This K Club can be very
punishing, and I've heard the weather is going to be pretty
horrendous.
	   At exactly 3:10 in the afternoon, the players halted for a
minute's silence in memory of the 28 people, many of them children,
killed in a bomb blast at Omagh, Northern Ireland, a week ago.
	   Led by Clarke, European players have planned a Pro-Am to raise
money for the dependants of those who died in last Saturday's
explosion.
	   (rjm)	   
</TEXT>
