<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Social Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German opposition launches final phase of campaign
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES with more quotes, color.
 &UR; AP Photo
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ With impassioned speeches in three cities,
opposition candidate Gerhard Schroeder kicked off the final stretch
of his election campaign Saturday pledging to restore programs to
help the most vulnerable members of society.
	   Schroeder, the front-runner for the Sept. 27 national vote,
confidently predicted he will unseat Chancellor Helmut Kohl. If he
does, it will be partly with campaign promises to repeal unpopular
cuts to the welfare state passed by the conservative leader.
	   The Social Democrat fired off forceful, fist-shaking speeches in
Berlin, Munich and Bonn, hitting powerfully at his theme that
strengthening the economy shouldn't come at the expense of the
Germans struggling to get by, including workers who fall ill and
pensioners.
	   ``We must finally move ahead in Germany,'' he said as wind
whipped through his hair and rain pelted his suit at an outdoor
rally in Bonn, the last stop on the one-day sweep through Germany.
	   Schroeder was at his most forceful when he promised to repeal
cuts in sick pay pushed through by Kohl as part of reforms aimed at
making German companies more competitive.
	   ``We can win, and we will,'' he proclaimed earlier in Berlin.
	   Schroeder's intensive tour gave him a head start into the
decisive five-week spurt of heavy campaigning by both candidates:
He demonstrated vigor, while Kohl was kicking off with a single
rally Sunday.
	   Speaking at Munich's Olympic Stadium complex, Schroeder tied his
political credibility to bringing down unemployment _ the core
issue in this year's campaign.
	   If elected, he told some 5,000 spectators, the Social Democrats
wouldn't deserve another term unless they ``noticeably'' lower
joblessness.
	   Social Democratic party chairman Oskar Lafontaine, who also
spoke at the rallies, accused Kohl of breaking promises to lower
joblessness, taxes and government debt and letting them rise
instead.
	   Kohl displayed an unbroken will to hang on after 16 years in
power, despite a limp campaign that has him trailing in opinion
polls.
	   ``I'm pretty sure we will win the election,'' Kohl said in an
interview for broadcast Sunday on ZDF national television. ``The
election is not decided at all yet. We are fighting for every
vote.''
	   He said he would count on swaying the large number of undecided
voters _ nearly half according to a Forsa institute poll released
Saturday.
	   On Thursday, Schroeder presented his plan for the first 100 days
of a Social Democratic government, pledging to cut taxes but also
to scrap welfare-state reforms pushed through by Kohl's government.
	   A pragmatic pro-business moderate, Schroeder symbolizes his
traditionally left-leaning party's drive to capture a ``new
center'' in the electorate.
	   Another poll published Saturday by Focus magazine gave the
Social Democrats 42 percent compared to 38 percent for Kohl's
Christian Democrats. Neither poll gave a margin of error.
	   (tc-cb) 	   
</TEXT>
