w2569 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Dagestan     08-22 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Dagestan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian interior minister to investigate killing of Muslim leader
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's interior minister said Saturday that he
would personally supervise the investigation into the killing of
the Muslim leader in the southern region of Dagestan.
	   Mufti Said-Mohammad Abubakarov died Friday along with his
brother and their driver when their car was blown up by a
radio-controlled bomb after a service at the main mosque in
Makhachkala, the regional capital.
	   Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin said he would send his deputy
to Makhachkala on Sunday to supervise the investigation there, the
ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   The speaker of the Russian parliament, the patriarch of the
Russian Orthodox Church, Russia's chief rabbi and other religious
and political leaders sent telegrams of condolences to the Council
of Russia's Muftis, of which Abubakarov was co-chairman.
	   They called on Russian authorities to ``immediately take
practical measures to solve the crime and punish those who stand
behind this terrorist act.''
	   The council called for a prompt investigation.
	   ``This terrorist act may cause destabilization not only in the
North Caucasus, but in the whole of Russia,'' said sheik Ravil
Gainutdin, mufti of Moscow and Central Europe, who is also
co-chairman of the council.
	   ``Therefore we demand that the leadership of the country and
investigative bodies ensure a prompt, but thorough and serious
investigation,'' he said.
	   The Interfax news agency said Friday that authorities believe
that the Wahhabis, a fundamentalist Islamic sect, could be involved
in the attack.
	   Abubakarov has been a long-time enemy of the Wahhabis. He once
said in an interview that every Muslim who killed a Wahhabi would
go to heaven.
	   Dagestan, which borders secessionist Chechnya, has been restive,
plagued by frequent bombings, kidnappings and other violence as
numerous ethnic and religious groups have fought for power.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
