<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Owen Signs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Teen-age star signs new 5-year contract with Liverpool
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LIVERPOOL, England (AP) _ One of the most promising stars to
emerge from the World Cup, 18-year-old England striker Michael Owen
pledged himself to Liverpool Saturday by signing a new 5-year
contract.
	   In a move to prevent Europe's richest clubs trying to lure the
talented teen-ager from Anfield, Liverpool arranged for the new
contract to be drawn up even though Owen had signed a 5-year deal
last season.
	   That was before he made such an impact. Owen became the youngest
player this century to be called up for England and then the
youngest to score for his country. He followed that up by scoring
his first World Cup goal and then produced an amazing solo goal
against Argentina.
	   His performances on such a big stage prompted rave reviews all
over the world and Liverpool reportedly said it was prepared to
insure Owen for 60 million pounds (dlrs 100 million) in case the
18-year-old striker's career was halted by injury.
	   ``I had a clause in my last contract which said that I could
re-negotiate when I had played for England in a competitive
international,'' Owen said before Saturday's 0-0 tie with Arsenal.
	   ``I have spoken to the board recently and am pleased to have
extended my contract until 2003.
	   ``As I have said all along, all I want to do is focus on my
football and hopefully help bring more silverware back to
Anfield.''
	   (rjm)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Owen Signs; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
