<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Rebels, 10th Ld-Writethru,0452 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angolan troops invade western Congo to back government forces
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to RESTORE other events of the day. RESTORES
byline. &QL; 
 &UR; With Zimbabwe-Congo; Congo-Peace Talks &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos KIN101-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GOMA, Congo (AP) _ Angolan troops entered the war against
Congolese rebels on Saturday, landing troops in the west of the
country, a rebel leader said.
	   ``Angolan troops have invaded Congo,'' Bizima Karaha said from
the eastern stronghold of Goma.
	   Karaha said he had no details, but warned that the Angolan
involvement will complicate the crisis and that the rebels will
strike back.
	   Zimbabwe has already deployed troops to help Congo President
Laurent Kabila ward off rebel advances on the capital, Kinshasa.
	   ``Angolans must come to their senses and remove forces from
Congo immediately,'' he said. ``This involvement has put chances
for negotiated settlement at very narrow or almost impossible.''
	   Karaha, Kabila's foreign minister until his recent defection,
said earlier Saturday from the rebel stronghold of Goma that the
rebels had downed two Zimbabwean planes over rebel territory in
Congo's southwest. The report could not be independently confirmed.
	   The rebels accuse Kabila of power-grabbing, tribalism and
mismanagement of his vast African nation since he toppled Mobutu
Sese Seko 15 months ago.
	   The rebels said they were within 30 kilometers (18 miles) of
Kinshasa, but did not specify where they had shot down the jets.
	   South Africa, meanwhile, scrambled to salvage a crumbling
regional peace summit it was hosting in Pretoria.
	   Two key players snubbed the talks _ Zimbabwe's President Robert
Mugabe and Kabila, who sent out reinforcements to defend the
Congolese capital. The leaders of Uganda and Rwanda were in
Pretoria.
	   The rebels themselves are said to have the backing of
neighboring Rwanda and Uganda. Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has threatened to join the rebel side if other foreign forces do
not withdraw.
	   Earlier Saturday, witnesses in Angola's enclave of Cabinda,
which borders southwestern Congo, said Angolan troops and military
equipment were moving toward the border. Cabinda governor Amaru
Tati reportedly said that defensive border measures were being
taken, but did not elaborate.
	   Congolese Information Minister Didier Mumengi denied that
Angolan troops had arrived, and said when they do it would be
announced.
	   ``When Angola sends its troops that will be a big day, as was
the case with Zimbabwe,'' Mumengi said on state-controlled
television.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
