</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vatican-Book Warning </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vatican says some of de Mello's books incompatible with faith
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By FRANCES D'EMILIO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ With the approval of Pope John Paul II, a
Vatican commission on Saturday denounced some writings by Anthony
de Mello, a widely-selling Jesuit author, as incompatible with
Roman Catholic faith.
	   In the latest move by Vatican's watchdogs to crack down on
doctrinal unorthodoxy, the Congregation for the Doctrine of Faith
concluded that while some early books by the Indian-born priest,
who died in 1987, contained ``valid elements of oriental wisdom,''
there were many ``dangers'' in his body of work.
	   ``Already in certain passages in these early works and to a
greater degree in his later publications, one notices a progressive
distancing from the essential contents of the Christian faith,''
the congregation said.
	   For the author, the congregation said, ``religions, including
Christianity, are one of the major obstacles to the discovery of
truth'' and ``there are no objective rules of morality.''
	   Besides warning Catholics about the ``dangers'' in the texts,
the congregation's conclusions also put Catholic bookstores are
guard.
	   Since many works are ``collections of short tales which are
often quite clever, the underlying ideas can easily pass
unnoticed,'' the congregation said, concluding that ``the
above-mentioned positions are incompatibile with the Catholic faith
and can cause grave harm.''
	   De Mello's books have been best-sellers in many parts of the
world, including in Italy, where the first Italian translation
appeared in 1986. Characterized by some as ``New Age,'' his writing
enjoyed even greater popularity after his death at age 55.
	   Among the works cited by the congregation containing ideas which
could be incompatible with faith were ``The Prayer of the Frog,''
``Call To Love,'' ``One Minute Wisdom,'' ``One Minute Nonsense,''
``Awareness,'' ``Wellsprings: A Book of Spiritual Exercises,''
``The Song of the Bird,'' ``Walking on Water.''
	   If de Mello were alive, he would have had a chance to defend his
works before the congregation under recently-revised Vatican rules.
	   No spokesman was available Saturday evening at Jesuit
headquarters in Rome for comment on the warnings.
	   In de Mello's defense, the congregation noted that not all the
translations and texts of his works were authorized by him for
publication, and some were published after his death.
	   And it praised the ``positive features'' in his writings,
including, ``elements of eastern wisdom which can be helpful in
achieving self-control, in breaking the attachments and affetions
that keeps us from being truly free, in avoiding selfishness....''
	   Earlier this year, the Vatican reinstated a controversial Sri
Lankan Catholic priest-author who was excommunicated for heresy a
year ago after a ruling by the congregation.
	   The Rev. Tissa Balasuriya had been excommunicated for allegedly
challenging papal authority and the church teaching on baptism,
original sin and the virginity of Mary.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
