<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Moeller and Haessler </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moeller and Haessler latest to quit German national team
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DORTMUND, Germany (AP) _ Andreas Moeller and Thomas Haessler
Saturday became the latest players to join the exodus from
Germany's national team following its early exit at the World Cup.
	   The two Borussia Dortmund midfielders, longtime mainstays of the
national team, announced their retirement but both left the door
open for a return.
	   Eight players have now quit since three-time World Cup champion
Germany was upset in the quarterfinals at France by Croatia,
sparking fierce criticism by the media and public against the team.
	   Two of them, Dortmund's Stefan Reuter and Schalke libero Olaf
Thon said they refused to play as long as Berti Vogts remained
coach.
	   Both Haessler and Moeller had spoken to Vogts before making
their decision public.
	   ``Right now I need some distance,'' said Moeller, who has 82
caps and was stung by being banished to the bench by Vogts in
France after a poor performance against Yugoslavia in an early
match.
	   ``If I acted emotionally, I would just throw it away. But I love
playing for Germany too much and love wearing the national
uniform,'' added Moeller, 30, one of Germany's biggest talents but
a consistent underachiever at major tournaments.
	   Vogts, under fire for guiding Germany to its second straight
early World Cup exit, has promised to rebuild the oldest team in
France with an infusion of young players.
	   ``My name is never on any of these lists, so I can't be that
important,'' said Haessler, 33, with 97 caps, who said he could
only be coaxed back onto the team in an emergency.
	   Team captain Juergen Klinsmann, Andreas Koepke, Juergen Kohler
and Lothar Matthaeus have quit because they are at or near the end
of their careers.
	   The eight were among a generation of German players that
captured the 1990 World Cup and the 1996 European championship.
	   Vogts will name his roster for a Sept. 2 friendly against Malta
Monday, a list expected to include several foreign-born players
with a German passport like Brazilian Paulo Rink, who plays with
Bayer Leverkusen.
	   The hope is these players will provide a remedy for the dearth
of ball-handling skills the Germans displayed at the World Cup.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
</TEXT>
