<SLUG> BC-Tropical Weather, 4th Ld,0382 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bonnie becomes hurricane; Bahamians in southeast batten down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new Bonnie coordinates; storm surge predicted. At
2 p.m. (1800 GMT) Bonnie was centered near 23.0 north latitude,
70.5 west longitude. At 11 a.m. (1500 GMT) Charley's center was
near 28.4 north, 97.9 west and Howard's center near 13.8 north,
106.2 west. &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Graphic &QL; 
 &UR; By JESSICA ROBERTSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) _ Bonnie strengthened into the Atlantic
season's first hurricane Saturday and headed toward sparsely
populated Bahamian islands, on a route that could threaten the
southeastern United States.
	   Another storm was gaining strength in the Pacific Ocean.
	   ``It's definitely going to happen. The southeastern portion (of
the Bahamas) is going to be hit today,'' meteorologist Dave Chorney
said from the U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami.
	   On Crooked Island, fuel distributor Daisy Scavella said the sun
was shining as residents battened down windows.
	   ``I guess we're going to have a good blow,'' she said. People on
the low-lying islands were most concerned about flooding.
	   Bahamian radio warned the islands' fishing fleet and yachters to
make for safe port. The islands' meteorological department said
Bonnie would hit landfall in the southeast later Saturday and pass
by Long Island, Eleuthera and the Abacos over the next 48 to 72
hours.
	   The small islands would have little effect on Hurricane Bonnie,
which is expected to gather strength Saturday. A storm surge of 3
to 7 feet (a meter to two meters) could occur in the warned area,
forecasters said.
	   ``People along the southeastern U.S. should pay attention to its
progress,'' said Jerry Jarrell, director of National Hurricane
Center.
	   He said winds could reach 100 mph (160 kph) by Monday. Chorney
said the worst thunderstorms were on the northern side of Bonnie,
in the open Atlantic.
	   Bonnie was about 115 miles (185 kilometers) north-northeast of
Turk Island at 2 p.m. (1800 GMT) with sustained winds of 85 mph
(137 kmh) and higher gusts. Once a fast moving storm, Bonnie
stalled Saturday. It was expected to move west-northwest near 15
mph (25 kmh) with a motion expected to continue through most of
Sunday.
 &UR; The National, 10th graf, pvs 	   
</TEXT>
