<SLUG> BC-Tropical Weather, 5th Ld-Writethru,0729 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bonnie becomes hurricane; Bahamians in southeast batten down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with Bonnie stalling, raise
reference to Hurricane Howard expected to peter out; U.S. yachters
heading home; New quotes and coordinates. At 2 p.m. (1800 GMT)
Bonnie was centered near latitude 23.0 north, longitude 70.5 west.
 &UR; With AP Graphic &QL; 
 &UR; By JESSICA ROBERTSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) _ Bonnie strengthened into the Atlantic
season's first hurricane Saturday, a 300-mile-long
(480-kilometer-long) storm dwarfing sparsely populated Bahamian
islands on its route, that could threaten the southeastern United
States.
	   Another hurricane gained strength in the Pacific Ocean but was
expected to peter out over open seas.
	   ``It's definitely going to happen. The southeastern portion (of
the Bahamas) is going to be hit today,'' meteorologist Dave Chorney
said from the U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami.
	   Bonnie nearly stalled Saturday about 115 miles (185 kilometers)
north-northeast of the British Turk island, drenching it and the
nearby Bahamian island of Mayaguana with heavy rains carried by
gusty winds, residents said.
	   On Crooked Island, fuel distributor Daisy Scavella said the sun
was shining Saturday morning as residents battened down windows.
	   ``I guess we're going to have a good blow,'' she said. People on
the low-lying islands were most concerned about flooding. Bahamian
forecaster Basil Dean said the islands already were experiencing
higher-than-usual tides that Bonnie's storm surges could rise
another 3 to 7 feet (a meter to two meters).
	   Bahamian radio warned the islands' fishing fleet and yachters to
make for safe port. The Bahamas Air-Sea Rescue Association said
some U.S. yachters had turned back to Florida.
	   The islands' meteorological department said Bonnie would hit
landfall in the southeast later Saturday and pass by Long Island,
Eleuthera and the Abacos on Sunday and Monday.
	   ``People along the southeastern U.S. should pay attention to its
progress,'' said Jerry Jarrell, director of National Hurricane
Center.
	   He said Bonnie was packing sustained winds of 85 mph (140 kph)
that could reach 100 mph (160 kph) by Monday and eventually upgrade
to a Category 3 storm with winds more than 111 mph (178 kph)
capable of causing extensive damage. Chorney noted that the worst
thunderstorms were on the northern side of the system, in the open
Atlantic.
	   Bonnie was expected to resume its north-northwest tack and move
at 10-15 mph (16-24 kph) on Sunday, the hurricane center said.
	   The Bahamian government Saturday posted a hurricane watch for
the northwest islands and hurricane warnings covered the British
Turks and Caicos islands and the southeastern and central Bahamas.
	   ``Preparations to protect life and property should be rushed to
completion,'' the hurricane center urged.
	   North Florida is the most likely target to be hit if the storm
reaches the mainland. Still, the storm could veer out to sea and
miss the U.S. coast entirely, Jarrell said.
	   Meanwhile, another weather system that threatened parts of Texas
lost power Saturday.
	   All warnings were discontinued when Tropical Storm Charley
weakened to a depression, though the hurricane center warned small
vessels to remain in port along the northwestern Gulf of Mexico
until winds and waves that reached 10 feet (3 meters) subside.
	   The threat of heavy rains and a storm forced the evacuation of
thousands of people from oil rigs in the Gulf of Mexico.
	   As it moved into Texas, Matagorda Island was hit the hardest
with 9 inches (23 centimeters) of rain and 70 mph (110 kph) wind
gusts early Saturday.
	   Also Friday, a storm in the Pacific Ocean reached hurricane
strength but remained far off the Mexican coast.
	   Hurricane Howard intensified Saturday, with winds of 110 mph
(176 kph). The hurricane center said it was expected to become
stronger before dissipating in the Pacific later Sunday.
	   Authorities closed the Acapulco port and warned ships to be
cautious of high waves along the southwestern Mexican coast.
	   The Atlantic Basin typically has nine tropical storms each year
with six of them becoming hurricanes, two of them intense. In 1997,
there were seven named storms, three hurricanes and one intense
hurricane. 	   
</TEXT>
