<SLUG> BC-Weather-Caribbean-Advisory,0434 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bulletin
</HEADLINE>
Hurricane Bonnie intermediate advisory number 12a
National weather service miami fl
2 pm edt sat aug 22 1998

...Bonnie hesitates...
 
A hurricane warning remains in effect for the turks and caicos
Islands...And the southeastern and central bahamas. A hurricane
Watch is in effect for the northwest bahamas.
 
Preparations to protect life and property should be rushed to
Completion in the hurricane warning area.
 
Bonnie could threaten the east coast of the united states within the
Next few days.  Residents along the coast should continue to monitor
The progress of the hurricane.
 
Fixes from the air force reconnaissance plane indicate that at 2 pm
Edt ...1800z...The center of hurricane Bonnie was located near
Latitude 23.0 north... Longitude  70.5 west  or about 115 miles
...185 km...North northeast of turk island. This position is
Adjusted a little bit to the northeast from the previous location.
 
Bonnie has been moving little during the past few hours but is
Expected to resume a west-northwest track at 10 to 15 mph during
Most of Sunday.  Thereafter a gradual turn to the northwest is
Expected.  On this track the center of Bonnie will be passing a
Little to the north of the southeastern and central bahamas.
 
Maximum sustained winds remain near  85 mph...140 km/Hr...With
Higher gusts.  Additional strengthening is forecast during the next
24 hours and Bonnie could eventually reach category three on the
Saffir-simpson hurricane scale.
 
Bonnie is a large hurricane with hurricane force winds extending
Outward up to 45 miles... 75 km... From the center.  Tropical storm
Force winds extend outward up to 200 miles...325 km...To the north
Of the center and about 100 miles...160 km...To the south of the
Center.
 
Latest minimum central pressure recently reported by an air force
Reconnaissance plane was 977 mb...28.85 inches.
 
A storm surge of 3 to 7 feet above normal tide levels could occur in
The warned area.
 
Rainbands associated with Bonnie are beginning to spread into the
Warned area...Producing locally heavy showers and strong gusty
Winds.  Five to ten inches of rain may occur along the path of the
Hurricane.
 
Repeating the 2 pm edt position...23.0 n... 70.5 w.  Movement
Toward...West northwest near 10 to 15 mph.  Maximum sustained
Winds... 85 mph.  Minimum central pressure... 977 mb.
 
The next advisory will be issued by the national hurricane center at
5 pm edt.
 
Avila
 


 &HT;    
