w2626 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sudan-Factory     08-22 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Factory </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Factory owner's lawyer says no links to bin Laden, no weapons
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Sudan-War at Home
 &UR; By ANTHONY SHADID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ A pharmaceutical plant destroyed by U.S.
missiles produced only drugs and its owner never met Osama bin
Laden, the Muslim militant America blames for the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in Africa, the owner's lawyer said Saturday.
	   Washington attacked the north Khartoum plant Thursday, saying it
was making precursors for chemical weapons that might be used by
bin Laden.
	   ``I think the Americans are under bad information and they are
not well briefed,'' said Ghazi Suleiman, a lawyer for Salah Idris,
the factory's Sudanese owner.
	   ``I think it would have been prudent before destroying the plant
to come and investigate the site.''
	   Idris purchased El-Shifa Pharmaceutical Industries Co. in March
1998 from another Sudanese businessman, Bashir Hassan Bashir, and
Baboud Marine and Trade Corp., a business based in Jeddah, Saudi
Arabia, Suleiman said. He did not know the price.
	   The plant, which employed 300 people, mainly manufactured
antibiotics, Suleiman said. It produced 60 percent of Sudan's
pharmaceutical drugs and exported as well.
	   Suleiman is a leading Sudanese opposition figure who spent 25
days in prison earlier this year. Idris, he said, has no political
affiliation and never met bin Laden or spoke of him.
	   ``They are different characters. Mr. Idris has no interest in
politics. He is a businessman,'' Suleiman said.
	   Idris was in London when the attack occurred, he said.
	   The government has denied the plant was producing material for
chemical weapons. It has said its products were antibiotics and
drugs to treat malaria and tuberculosis.
	   The missile attack demolished the site, leaving mounds of red
brick and twisted sheet metal. One person was killed and nine were
wounded in the attack.
	   The government has allowed people to visit the site and has
taken foreign diplomats around it.
	   Suleiman said Idris may seek dlrs 50 million in compensation
from the United States, but has yet to take any steps.
 &UR; as-jbm
</TEXT>
