<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Rebels, 11th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angolan troops invade western Congo to back government forces
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to raise escalation of war, ADDS reaction from
Congolese minister. Edits to conform, trims dated material. No
pickup.
 &UR; With Zimbabwe-Congo; Congo-Peace Talks
 &UR; AP Photos KIN101-104
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GOMA, Congo (AP) _ Rebels battling to topple President Laurent
Kabila on Saturday accused Angola of entering the fray in Congo's
escalating war, which already includes forces from Zimbabwe and
threatens to engulf other African states.
	   Angolan troops landed in the west of this vast central African
country in support of Kabila's loyalist forces, a rebel leader said
without giving details.
	   ``Angolan troops have invaded Congo,'' Bizima Karaha said from
the rebel's stronghold of Goma in eastern Congo.
	   Karaha warned that the Angolan involvement will complicate the
spiralling crisis and the rebels will strike back. Zimbabwe had
earlier deployed troops to help Kabila ward off rebel advances on
the capital of Kinshasa.
	   ``Angolans must come to their senses and remove forces from
Congo immediately,'' he said. ``This involvement has put chances
for negotiated settlement at very narrow or almost impossible.''
	   Information Minister Didier Mumengi denied that Angola had
deployed troops to Congo, but hinted that they would be sent before
long.
	   ``Certain African countries have offered their solidarity. They
have done this in a clear manner in full view of everyone,''
Mumengi told The Associated Press. ``As soon as Angola sends their
troops it will be done openly.''
	   Namibia and Zambia earlier in the week announced their support
for Congo's embattled president, but did not specify how, or if,
they would contribute to the war. There were unconfirmed reports of
two plane loads of weapons arriving in Kinshasa from Namibia last
week.
	   Two neighbors on Congo's eastern border, Rwanda and Uganda, are
said to have forces in Congo and Kabila has accused them of
masterminding the rebellion. Both countries deny the charge, but
warn of future intervention to protect their own territories.
	   Rwanda and Uganda played key roles in Kabila's rise to power in
a rebellion over longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko 15 months ago
but have since fallen out with the Congolese president, who they
accuse of allowing ethnic Hutu attacks on their countries from
covert bases in eastern Congo.
	   Karaha, who was Congo's foreign minister until his recent
defection, said earlier Saturday that the rebels had shot down two
Zimbabwean planes over rebel territory in Congo's southwest. The
report could not be independently confirmed.
	   There was no immediate comment on the downed aircraft from
Kinshasa, but a former military intelligence officer with close
government ties said Kabila's army had recently acquired fighters
being flown by either Cuban or Angolan pilots.
	   ``We know that the government does have air support
capabilities,'' the officer said on condition of anonymity.
	   A Zimbabwean spokesman denied Zimbabwe's Chinese-built MiG-21
fighters had been deployed to Congo, but did not specify whether
the country's other warplanes were there.
	   The rebels accuse Kabila of power-grabbing, tribalism and
mismanagement of his vast African nation since he toppled Mobutu.
	   The rebels said they were within 30 kilometers (18 miles) of
Kinshasa, but did not specify where they had shot down the jets.
	   South Africa, meanwhile, scrambled to salvage a crumbling
regional peace summit it was hosting in Pretoria.
	   Two key players snubbed the talks _ Zimbabwe's President Robert
Mugabe and Kabila, who sent out reinforcements to defend the
Congolese capital. The leaders of Uganda and Rwanda were in
Pretoria.
	   Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni has threatened to join the
rebel side if other foreign forces do not withdraw.
	   Earlier Saturday, witnesses in Angola's enclave of Cabinda,
which borders southwestern Congo, said Angolan troops and military
equipment were moving toward the border. Cabinda governor Amaru
Tati reportedly said that defensive border measures were being
taken, but did not elaborate.
	   Mumengi said when Angolan troops had arrived, it would be
announced.
	   ``When Angola sends its troops that will be a big day, as was
the case with Zimbabwe,'' Mumengi said on state-controlled
television.
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press reporter Ian Stewart contributed
to this story from Congo's capital of Kinshasa.
	   (bur/ids/gam) 	   
</TEXT>
