<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-South Africa-Australia, 1st Ld-Writethru,0504 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa takes Tri-Nations rugby championship with 29-15
</HEADLINE>
victory &QL; 
 &UR; EDS: RECASTS with quotes. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Fullback Percy Montgomery
kicked two of his five penalties to break open a one-point match
and led South Africa to the Tri-Nations rugby championship with a
29-15 victory over Australia on Saturday.
	   The victory capped a remarkable rennaissance for the Springboks,
the reigning World Cup champion which last year and earlier this
year had slid to its worst test defeat and gotten mired in a
organizational political mess.
	   ``I can honestly say on this day, 22 August 1998, South Africa
is the best team in the word,'' coach Nick Mallett's said. ``I'm
very proud to be a part of it.''
	   After Wallaby fullback Matt Burke pulled Australia within a
point for the second time 16-15 with a 45-meter penalty in the 51st
minute, Montgomery put South Africa back in control 22-15 with his
two final penalties.
	   Replacement flanker Bobby Skinstad then clinched the victory in
the 70th with a try beneath the posts to the delight of the crowd
of 62,308 at Ellis Park.
	   The title was the Boks' first trophy under Mallett and
dramatized the resurgence of the team since he took charge
following last year's 55-35 loss to New Zealand, the country's
worst test defeat.
	   ``I think this side is better than the World Cup side,''
Springbok scrumhalf Joost Van der Westhuizen said. ``This is the
best ever South African team in which I've played, in terms of
spirit and confidence. We're one big family.
	   ``For myself, other than the World Cup victory, this was my best
win.''
	   Australia finished second with a 2-0-2 record in the Southern
Hemisphere championship. New Zealand lost all four games and
finished third.
	   ``They were physically stronger at the breakdown and that didn't
allow us to get continuity,'' Australian coach Rod Macqueen said.
	   Montgomery and Burke traded penalties in the second and fourth
minutes before South Africa took the lead for good in the seventh
on a try by Tighthead prop Adrian Garvey.
	   Skipper Gary Teichmann had taken a line-out and the Boks mauled
their way through. Garvey finished off a move which he was set up
by coming up in support after a great break from left wing Pieter
Rossouw.
	   Montgomery's conversion put the Springboks ahead by seven, but
another of Burke's penalties kept it close.
	   South Africa wasted a pair of opportunities to increase its
lead, running two penalties while on the attack before Montgomery
took advantage of a third to make it 13-6.
	   Burke landed two more penalties to pull the Wallabies within a
point, but after Australia strayed offside on the half-way line,
Montgomery landed a 50-meter strike to give the Boks a 16-12
halftime lead.
	   The Tri-Nations championship comes on the heels of a record
96-13 win over Wales and comprehensive victories over England and
Ireland earlier in the season.
</TEXT>
