<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli shelling wounds Lebanese civilian
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS troops killing alleged Israeli collaborator final grafs &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SIDON, Lebanon (AP) _ Israeli forces shelled suspected guerrilla
hideouts and villages in southern Lebanon on Saturday, wounding a
Lebanese civilian, Lebanese security officials said.
	   A villager, Samir Hammoud, was lightly injured by shrapnel from
a shell that exploded near his house in Arab Salim, a village just
outside the Israeli-occupied zone, the officials said.
	   Hammoud, who was admitted to a hospital in the port city of
Sidon, was the second civilian to be wounded by Israeli shells in
two days.
	   A seventy-year-old Lebanese man was wounded Friday when Israeli
artillery retaliated for a guerrilla ambush that killed two Israeli
soldiers.
	   Saturday's shelling appeared to be in retaliation for guerrilla
attacks hours earlier on Israeli positions in the occupation zone.
	   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, said its fighters
attacked positions of the Israeli army and its allied South Lebanon
Army at Sojod and Bir Kallab in the zone.
	   There was no immediate word on casualties.
	   Hezbollah is the main guerrilla group fighting to dislodge
Israeli troops and their SLA allies from southern Lebanon. Israel
set up the zone in 1985 to protect its northern territory from
cross-border attacks.
	   Separately, Lebanese troops shot dead Saturday a man wanted for
collaboration with Israel, a security official said.
	   Ayyoub Malak, who was also wanted for smuggling goods from the
occupied zone to the rest of Lebanon, was killed in a shootout in
central Lebanon as troops tried to arrest him, the official said.
Two soldiers were lightly wounded.
 &UR; str-zk-jbm
</TEXT>
