<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Pilot Pen,0323 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ivanisevic, Kucera to meet in Pilot Pen finals
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By DONNA TOMMELLEO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW HAVEN, Connecticut (AP) _ Goran Ivanisevic shook off an
aching shoulder and continued his dominance over Yevgeny
Kafelnikov, eliminating the defending Pilot Pen champ 6-3, 6-4
Saturday with a dominating service game.
	   Ivanisevic leads the head-to-head series 9-2, and has beaten the
Russian in their last seven matches. His powerful serve, clocked as
high as 131 mph (211 kph) in the tournament, kept him in control
through most of the 1 hour, 5 minute match.
	   The left-hander had a dozen aces to Kafelnikov's four and won 87
percent of his first service points.
	   In the hunt for his first tournament win in the United States,
Ivanisevic will play No. 7 seed Karol Kucera, of Slovakia, in
Sunday's final. Kucera advanced by beating No. 4 seed Richard
Krajicek, 6-7 (8-6), 6-4.
	   The 26-year-old Croat entered the semifinal nursing a sore left
shoulder he said was damaged from a decade of countless serves.
Ivanisevic said fifth-seeded Kafelnikov broke him in the first game
of the match before the pain-killers kicked in.
	   Ivanisevic broke back in the second game.
	   ``It was good that I broke him straight away. I was doing a lot
of running today,'' said Ivanisevic. ``He made me run with his drop
shots. The crowd liked it, but I was tired.''
	   The sore shoulder also dictated that he take a little off his
serves and rely more on his volleys, the part of his game he says
has steadily improved.
	   ``Especially on hard court. I can come in, I can finish with a
volley ... I can stay back,'' Ivanisevic said.
	   Kucera, a three-time singles winner, holds a 2-1 lead over
Ivanisevic in head-to-head meetings, and is ranked No. 13 on the
tour.
	   He broke Krajicek for the match when the hard-serving Dutchman's
return volley just missed the baseline.
</TEXT>
