<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Syria-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Syrian President meets U.S. senator
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) _ U.S. Senator Chuck Hagel held talks
Saturday with Syrian President Hafez Assad on the stalled Middle
East peace process, a presidential spokesman said.
	   Hagel, who is on the fourth leg of a fact-finding mission to the
Middle East, told reporters afterwards that Israel's recent
decision to build 2,300 homes and 2,500 vacation units in the
occupied Golan Heights, was hindering the process.
	   ``There is no question that is not helpful,'' Hagel said.
	   Israel captured the heights in the Arab-Israeli War of 1967.
Syria has refused to resume peace talks, which broke off in
February 1966, until Israel agrees to a complete return of the
plateau. The Israeli government says the heights are essential to
national security.
	   Earlier Saturday, Hagel met with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Sharaa.
	   Hagel, who serves on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, is
due to travel to Saudi Arabia. He has already visited Israel and
the Palestinian territories, Egypt and Lebanon.
 &UR; dam-mae/bm-jbm
</TEXT>
