<HEADLINE>
Marseille stages stunning five-goal comeback to win 5-4
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Marseille scored five goals in a remarkable second
half recovery to beat Montpellier 5-4 Saturday and maintain its
winning start to the season.
	   Bordeaux also won, 1-0 at home to Auxerre, to join Marseille on
nine points after three rounds of the French championship.
	   In one of the most amazing games ever witnessed at the Stade
Velodrome, Marseille came back from 4-0 behind at half time, to win
5-4.
	   Laurent Blanc won the match with a penalty in injury time.
	   Earlier, Montpellier scored four times in front of an angry home
crowd, with young striker Ibrahima Bakayoko netting twice.
	   Marseille, which won its first two games without conceding a
goal, started its recovery with goals by Florian Maurice, his first
since transferring from Paris Saint-Germain, and Fabrizio
Ravenelli.
	   Christophe Dugarry made it 4-3 with a powerful header, before
Ravenelli struck again to level the scores.
	   In the dramatic final seconds, Robert Pires was fouled inside
the penalty area and veteran defender Blanc kept his cool to give
Marseille a famous victory.
	   Bordeaux has also won its first three games, after a 1-0 home
victory against Auxerre.
	   It collected three points thanks to a fourth-minute close range
volley by Sylvain Wiltord, his fourth goal of the season.
	   Bordeaux dominated the match, and Johan Micaud came close to
doubling the lead with a late header that just cleared the
crossbar.
	   Late in the match Bernard Diomede had a chance to equalize, but
put a left-footed shot just wide.
	   Monaco, the other team that had won its first two games, drew
0-0 at Toulouse in a lifeless match.
	   PSG won 1-0 at struggling Strasbourg.
	   After Bernard Lama made a fine early save from a Frederic
Arpinon header, PSG began to dominate.
	   It scored the winner in the 64th minute.
	   Strasbourg midfielder Corentin Martins misplaced a pass, and PSG
worked the ball to Patrice Loko, who crossed for Marco Simone to
score.
	   The defeat means that Strasbourg has yet to score this season.
	   Rennes came from behind to win 2-1 at home to Le Havre, its
second victory of the season.
	   Miladin Becanovic opened the scoring with a 21st minute penalty.
	   But Rennes grabbed maximum points with second half strikes from
Shabani Nonda and a Ludovic Pollet own goal.
	   In other matches, Lyon, which beat Toulouse 6-1 last week, won
at minnow Lorient with a 58th minue goal by Marco Grassi.
	   Bastia thumped last season's runner-up Metz 3-0.
	   (parf-ae) 	   
</TEXT>
