<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Little League WS, 1st Ld-Writethru,0355 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eight teams survive big odds to get into championship
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: REWRITES throughout to UPDATE with Canadian winner; add
details, quotes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WILLIAMSPORT, Pennsylvania (AP) _ Amazing feats brought these
eight teams to the Little League World Series. One youngster threw
a no-hitter in the deciding game. Another hit a two-run homer in
the last at-bat. Another hit two home runs with a trip to
Williamsport on the line.
	   The best of the more than 7,000 teams from America, Europe and
Asia won regionals on three continents and make a run at the world
championship starting Sunday at the Howard J. Lamade Stadium. The
championship is Aug. 29.
	   ``When you think of the chances of getting this far, it is
pretty amazing. More than 7,000 teams started out, and we're among
the final eight,'' said Tom Meyer, the coach of the U.S. Central
team from Jenison, Michigan.
	   Meyer also coaches a high school American football team in town,
so he commuted the 600 miles (965 kilometers) from Jenison to
Indianapolis for each day of the U.S. Central Regional last week.
Godwin Heights High School administrators said he could skip the
all-night drives and two-a-day football practices this week.
	   ``They said I could go to the World Series,'' he said, smiling.
	   Jenison is joined in Williamsport by three other U.S. teams _
Greenville, North Carolina, Toms River, New Jersey, and Cypress,
California _ and four non-U.S. teams, including Langley Little
League of British Columbia, who defeated Glace Bay of Nova Scotia,
4-1, to win the Canada Region Championship.
	   Guadalupe, Mexico, has three players returning from last year's
championship team, which scored four runs in the final inning to
beat Mission Viejo, California.
	   Kashima, Japan bring along the first girl to play for a Far East
champion. Sayaka Tsushima, who plays center field, becomes the
fifth girl to play in the Little League World Series, all since
1984.
	   The Arabian American Little League of Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, won
the European Regional for the fourth consecutive year.
</TEXT>
