<HEADLINE>
Mexican gang leader lists his profession as `Kidnapping'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS graf 7 to Correct Lopez to Paz. &QL; 
 &UR; By GLORIA PEREZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALMOLOYA DE JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) _ Asked by the judge to state
his profession, Daniel Arizmendi Lopez curtly responded:
``Kidnapping.''
	   Judge Armando Baez Espinoza of the 2nd Federal Criminal Court
stared in disbelief at the man dubbed the ``ear-lopper'' for
allegedly sending ransom notes attached to his victims' ears.
	   Judge Baez asked Arizmendi to repeat himself. He replied: ``I do
kidnappings ... I am a kidnapper.''
	   After the eight-hour pretrial hearing at the maximum security
prison in Almoloya de Juarez, near Mexico City, Arizmendi and his
mistress, Dulce Maria Paz Venegas, refused to plead innocent or
guilty to the charges.
	   Arizmendi said he was very tired after three days of questioning
by police at the Attorney General's Office.
	   Their court-appointed lawyer, Maria Eugenia Lopez Fuentes, asked
the hearing to be recessed until next Thursday so she could have
time to prepare her case. The judge agreed and ordered them held
without bail.
	   Arizmendi is accused of kidnapping, racketeering, laundering
money from ransom payments and illegal possession of firearms. Paz
is accused of racketeering and money laundering.
