<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Obit-Garro, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Leading Mexican novelist Elena Garro dead at 77
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Elena Garro, a leading Mexican playwright and
novelist, died in a hospital Saturday after a long illness. She was
77.
	   The former wife of the late Mexican poet and Nobel laureate
Octavio Paz, Garro had been suffering for years from ephysemia.
	   Monday she checked in at a hospital in Cuernavaca, 35 miles
south of Mexico City, where she died of heart and lung failure,
according to her attending physician, Dr. Marco Aurelio Eslava.
	   Garro wrote more than two dozen best-selling novels in Spanish
and as many plays, and held a number of literary awards, among them
the Sor Inez de la Cruz, one of Mexico's top prizes.
	   Her foremost novel was ``Recuerdos del Porvenir'' (Remembrances
of the Future). Other literary works included ``Mariana,''
``Reencuentro con Personajes'' (Reencountering Personages), ``La
Casa Junto al Rio'' (The House Next to the River), and ``Memorias
de Espana'' (Memories of Spain).
	   With the exception of a couple of plays, few of her works were
translated into English. But she was well known in Europe,
especially in Spain.
	   Garro was born Dec. 12, 1920, in Puebla, the capital of the
state of the same name, 65 miles southeast of Mexico City. She
started writing when she was very young.
	   She later settled in the Mexican capital where she moved in
literary circles, and met and married Paz in 1937. The young couple
moved to Spain soon after to write about the 1936-39 Spanish Civil
War.
	   Her marriage to Paz ended in an angry divorce three decades
later. Octavio Paz died in Mexico City on April 19 _ they never
reconciled or spoke to each other.
	   She first went to the United States, then France and later
settled in Spain in 1972, where she lived for 21 years. She moved
to Cuernavaca, the capital of Morelos state, three years ago and
lived a solitary life in a small apartment with her daughter,
Helena (cq) Paz Garro and 10 cats.
	   Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
	   Garro is survived by her daughter Helena Paz.
</TEXT>
