<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Northville Seniors,0522 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hall and Shaw share lead after two rounds
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JIM O'CONNELL &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERICHO, New York (AP) _ Walter Hall shot a 3-under-par 69
Saturday to hold a share of the lead of the dlrs 1 million
Northville Long Island Classic for the second straight year, this
time with Tom Shaw, who had a 66.
	   Hall, in his second year on the Senior PGA Tour, held a
three-stroke lead after an opening 65 and his 10-under 134 total
matches what he had last year after two rounds at the 6,842-yard
(6,254-meter) Meadow Brook Club. He had a final-round 74 last year
and finished 11th.
	   ``I have a lot more experience than I did last year, that was
just my second senior tournament,'' said Hall, who played the first
three holes in last year's final round three over par. ``I'm not
saying I'm going to win by a long shot, but if I happen to get off
to a better start hopefully things will be better but I am happy
with where I am.''
	   That would be tied with Shaw and two strokes ahead of Spaniard
Jose Maria Canizares and South African Gary Player, who both
matched their opening-round 68s. John Schroeder, who had a 65, and
Lee Trevino, who had a 69, were at 7-under 137.
	   Hall bogeyed Nos. 7 and 8 to fall to six under and knew he
needed something to jump start his round.
	   ``At 8, I was over for the round and I'm watching everybody
going by on the leaderboard,'' Hall said. ``Then I made some
birdies on the way in.''
	   Hall's birdies on Nos. 11, 14 and 16 came on putts of 10, 8 and
20 feet (3, 2.4 and 6 meters).
	   Shaw jumped right into contention by starting his second round
with an eagle and a birdie.
	   ``My goal for tomorrow is to get off to a better start than I
did today,'' Shaw said breaking into a big laugh. ``If I do, just
come drag me off the golf course.''
	   Shaw had a chance at a spectacular round, but missed six birdie
putts of 10 feet (3 meters) or less.
	   Shaw, 59, hasn't won on the Senior PGA Tour since 1993, the last
year he also held a lead entering the final round of a tournament.
	   ``The last three years I've been in kind of a slump, but this
year I'm playing pretty well,'' he said. ``I've been waiting for
the chance to put three good rounds together.''
	   Canizares was one of the players who shared the 36-hole lead
with Hall last season and he missed the playoff by one stroke. He
could have held second alone, but missed a 3-foot (1-meter) putt
for par on the final hole.
	   Player won the 36-hole MasterCard Champions, his fourth straight
victory on the mini-tour for players over 60.
	   ``At the presentation I thought back to the 1961 Masters when I
won dlrs 20,000,'' said Player, whose 8-under total was six better
than Jim Ferree. ``Now at almost age 63 I win dlrs 18,000 for a
super seniors. That is food for thought.''
	   Defending champion Dana Quigley had a 68 and was at 141.
 &UR; DIVOTS: &LR;  Canizares' 15-year-old son Jose Alejandro was his caddy
for the first time in the United States. The younger Canizares, who
plays to a 3 handicap, will work just the one week as he has to
head back to school in Spain.
</TEXT>
