w2818 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-RoyalPoll     08-22 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Royal Poll </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poll indicates growing doubts that princess' crash was accident
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ New opinion polls indicate there are growing
public doubts that Princess Diana's death was an accident, and
increasing approval for Queen Elizabeth II since the week of
Diana's funeral.
	   Nearly a year after the princess and Dodi Fayed died in a Paris
car crash, 59 percent of Britons asked in an NOP poll said they
believed the deaths were an accident, compared with 84 percent in a
similar poll in September, shortly after the crash.
	   In the poll published in The Sunday Times, 24 percent of the
1,003 people asked said they believed there was a conspiracy to
have the princess murdered. There was no comparative figure for
last year. Twelve percent said they didn't know, and 5 percent said
it was neither.
	   Twenty-nine percent believed the queen should abdicate now or at
age 75, compared with 52 percent a year ago. Sixty-two said she
should never step down, and 63 percent said the country would be
worse off without the monarchy.
	   Another poll, published in The Mail on Sunday, found 75 percent
believed Britain is better off with a monarchy.
	   That MORI poll of 804 adults also indicated substantial support
for Prince Charles.
	   Three-quarters of those polled believed he had done a good job
bringing up his sons. Only 9 percent said the prince and Camilla
Parker Bowles should split up, 42 percent said they should conduct
their relationship in public, and 35 percent said the relationship
should remain private.
	   Assuming they remained a couple, 38 percent said they believed
the two should marry, and 29 percent were opposed. The rest did not
have an opinion. If Charles and Camilla did marry, half of those
surveyed believe Charles should still be allowed to become King,
and 41 percent were against. The rest did not know.
	   At the time of Charles' divorce from Diana in August 1996, The
Mail on Sunday said, 66 percent believed Charles should not be king
with Camilla at his side.
	   Prince Charles has said he did not intend to remarry.
	   In the NOP poll of 1,003 adults, three-quarters said there
should be an end to the ``cult of Diana'' and that she should be
allowed to rest in peace _ although 17 percent said it was
understandable that public interest in her remains intense.
	   Both polls were taken last week and had a margin of error of 3
percent.
	   (acw) 	   
</TEXT>
