<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0631 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Items include Archbishop Desmond Tutu, John Lennon, Janet
Jackson, European golfers. Some items may have moved as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ATLANTA (AP) _ For Archbishop Desmond Tutu, the way to unwind
after two years as chairman of the a commission investigating
apartheid-era crimes in South Africa is to tackle major theological
issues at a U.S. university.
	   The Nobel peace laureate will join Emory University's theology
department for the coming academic year.
	   ``I'm much looking forward to unwinding after the work in which
we have been involved in the Truth and Reconciliation Commission
back home in South Africa,'' Tutu said.
	   The commission's work is wrapping up. On Friday, former
President P.W. Botha was found guilty of ignoring a summons to
appear before the panel. He was given a suspended prison sentence
and fined.
	   Tutu said theology may be the key to stopping terrorist attacks
like the recent bombings of U.S. embassies in Africa.
	   Tutu will work on a book this fall and will not take on any
classroom duties. He will teach two courses in the spring, with the
topics to be determined later, Emory spokeswoman Elaine Justice
said.
	   ___
	   ATTICA, New York (AP) _ The deranged fan who killed John Lennon
doesn't want a cent for the Beatles album he got the former Beatle
to autograph shortly before the murder.
	   Lennon signed and dated the ``Double Fantasy'' album for Mark
David Chapman outside his New York apartment building the same day
he was killed, Dec. 8, 1980.
	   The record is being offered for an asking price of dlrs 1.8
million on the Internet by an anonymous man who found it at the
crime scene.
	   Chapman, who is serving a 20-years-to-life prison sentence, said
he was contacted last week by a New York City lawyer who told
Chapman he had the legal right to ``assert a claim'' to the album
as a personal possession.
	   Chapman, 43, said he stashed the album behind a watchman's booth
and fired five shots from a .38-caliber revolver into Lennon's back
as the rock star returned home from a recording session.
	   After being examined by police as evidence, the album was
returned to the man who found it.
	   ___
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ If the audience sees a little of Broadway's
style in Janet Jackson's new razzle-dazzle ``Velvet Rope'' tour,
it's not by accident.
	   ``To me, being on stage is about entertaining,'' said Jackson,
32, the youngest daughter of the celebrated Jackson family. ``I
know there are people who just walk on stage and give you a show by
just doing their music, but I always wanted something extra.''
	   The Broadway influence goes back to her childhood.
	   ``I'm crazy about Broadway. I saw my first Broadway show when I
was 10,'' she said Friday. ``I saw Stephanie Mills in `The Wiz' on
Broadway and I saw it over and over again. Then I saw 'Annie' and I
wanted to be in it so badly.''
	   ___
	   The tour, which has drawn capacity crowds, was in Southern
California last week.
	   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) _ Some of Europe's top golfers will take
part in a fund-raising match for those killed and injured in the
recent bombing in Omagh, Northern Ireland.
	   ``We can't bring people back, but we would like to do something
to show our support,'' said Ryder Cup player Darren Clarke, who is
from County Tyrone where the tragedy took place.
	   ``Not that other atrocities haven't affected me, but this one
has hit deeper. Adults and children were just slaughtered _ it was
a senseless, murderous act.''
	   The Pro-Am event will be at Portmarnock Links in Northern
Ireland on Sept. 14.
	   The goal is to raise about dlrs 250,000 for the Omagh Fund.
Saturday's bomb killed 28 people, many of them children, and
injured more than 330.
</TEXT>
