<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0613 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   GOMA, Congo (AP) _ Rebels battling to topple President Laurent
Kabila on Saturday accused Angola of entering the fray in Congo's
escalating war, which already includes forces from Zimbabwe and
threatens to engulf other African states. An Angolan government
source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said troops would
defend Kinshasa, although he gave no official word on his
government's position on the fighting. Angolan troops landed in the
west of this vast central African country in support of Kabila's
loyalist forces, a rebel leader said without giving details.
(CONGO-REBELS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ President Bill Clinton moved to choke off
funds to Osama bin Laden and his terrorist group while opposition
Republicans presented an increasingly unified front in supporting
the president's missile strikes in Sudan and Afghanistan. U.S.
officials suggest more strikes might come in the future. ``We must
not allow sanctuary for terrorism _ not for terrorists or for their
money,'' Clinton said Saturday. He announced that on Thursday, the
day of the U.S. air strikes, he signed an executive order blocking
all financial transactions between bin Laden's organization and any
U.S. individual or company. Clinton urged other nations to file
suit. (US-BOMBINGS)
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Whipping up popular anger over a U.S.
missile strike, President Omar el-Bashir said Saturday that the
Sudanese were prepared to die in a holy war. ``America is attacking
us because we are guardians of Islam,'' el-Bashir told a central
Khartoum rally of at least 5,000 people, who replied with chants of
``Death to America.'' After his speech, some 500 protesters went to
the British Embassy, where they hurled stones at the building. One
demonstrator climbed to the top of the embassy flagpole and cut
down the Union Jack. After the flag fell to the ground, angry
demonstrators tore it to pieces. (SUDAN-US)
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ With impassioned speeches in three cities,
opposition candidate Gerhard Schroeder kicked off the final stretch
of his election campaign Saturday pledging to restore programs to
help the most vulnerable members of society. Schroeder, the
front-runner for the Sept. 27 national vote, confidently predicted
he will unseat Chancellor Helmut Kohl. If he does, it will be
partly with campaign promises to repeal unpopular cuts to the
welfare state passed by the conservative leader. The Social
Democrat fired off forceful, fist-shaking speeches in Berlin,
Munich and Bonn, hitting powerfully at his theme that strengthening
the economy shouldn't come at the expense of the Germans struggling
to get by, including workers who fall ill and pensioners.
(GERMANY-SOCIAL DEMOCRATS)
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Weeks of high waters cracked soggy dikes
protecting cities along the Yangtze River on Saturday, and soldiers
in the northeast fought to stop a breached levee hard by China's
largest oil field. The state disaster relief agency warned that
high waters surged anew on the upper Yangtze, threatening another
round of flooding downstream. Governor Wang Maolin said dikes in
central Hunan province were already soggy and seriously damaged.
While the latest Yangtze flood crest receded Saturday around
Hunan's Dongting Lake, its retreat exposed fractures in protective
embankments. Some 830,000 soldiers and civilians worked to shore up
dikes and patch cracks, one of them 70 meters (230 feet) long,
around Yueyang city, state media reported. (CHINA-FLOODS)
</TEXT>
