<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru ,0311 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Contiguglia wins U.S. federational presidential vote
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Adds quotes from Contiguglia. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WAILEA, Hawaii (AP) _ Dr. Bob Contiguglia, the endorsed
candidate of outgoing American soccer head Alan Rothenberg, was
elected president of the U.S. Soccer Federation on Saturday.
	   The chairman of the U.S. Youth Soccer Association from
1990-1996, Contiguglia, 55, beat outgoing USSF executive vice
president Larry Monaco with 57.6 percent of the vote of USSF
members. Monaco received 42.4 percent of the vote.
	   Contiguglia was seen generally as the candidate that was more
supportive of continuing to build on the gains of the professional
division, meaning essentially Major League Soccer, and the national
teams.
	   ``The final candidates are still the final four,'' Contiguglia
said. ``We will have a small working committee basically made up of
the folks who have working about this the last several months. The
committee will make a recommendation and the president will make
the final decision. ...
	   ``The criteria would be international experience, working with
professional athletes, obviously track record and preferably, if
possible, as American. One of my criteria would be someone who's
played in the World Cup, too.''
	   Monaco was looked upon as more geared toward the federation's
membership, two-thirds of which is youth and amateur.
	   Rothenberg, the head of the 1994 World Cup organizing committee
and the founder of MLS, is stepping down after completing his
second four-year term as USSF president. USSF bylaws prevented him
from running for a third.
	   In Saturday's other contested election, John Motta, a business
entrepren eur from the New Hampshire Soccer Association, defeated
MLS Deputy Commissioner Sunil Gulati for executive vice president
by only 11 votes.
</TEXT>
