<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Briefs,0668 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A Package of Caribbean News Briefs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; BAHAMAS: Bonnie begins blowing in southeastern Bahamas &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) _ Bonnie strengthened into the Atlantic
season's first hurricane Saturday, a 300-mile-long
(480-kilometer-long) storm dwarfing sparsely populated Bahamian
islands on its route, that could threaten the southeastern United
States.
	   Another hurricane gained strength in the Pacific Ocean but was
expected to peter out over open seas.
	   At 8 p.m. (0000 GMT) Saturday, the National Hurricane Center
said Bonnie's center was located about 210 miles (335 kilometers)
east-southeast of San Salvador in the Bahamas, the island where
Columbus is believed to have first landed in the hemisphere.
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: Caribbean nations sign trade pact
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Caribbean nations
signed a trade pact more than doubling their market Saturday at a
16-nation summit overwhelmed by one-time bogeyman Fidel Castro, who
appears to have been promoted overnight to the role of regional
elder statesman.
	   The summit marks the high point of the formerly insular
Dominican Republic's effort to become a lynchpin of the Americas
through its Hispanic culture, Caribbean location and ties to the
United States where over a million Dominicans live.
	   The free trade accord will over six years remove most tariffs
between the Caribbean Community, whose fifteen nations have a
population of 6 million people, and the Dominican Republic with 8
million people. It was timed to coincide with negotiations for a
free trade zone encompassing the entire Western Hemisphere by 2005.
 &UR; ST. LUCIA: Election shows ruling party still popular
	   CASTRIES, St. Lucia (AP) _ The ruling St. Lucia Labour Party won
a special election held Friday, showing it remains strong more than
a year after it swept to power in an unprecedented landslide.
	   In a by-election to replace Kenneth John, a member of Parliament
who died in July while trying to save a swimmer, the Labour party
won by a better than 2-1 margin, in results announced Saturday.
	   Labour candidate Michael Gaspard retained the seat for the party
with 2,858 votes, compared to 1,402 votes for Allan Bosquet Jr. of
the United Workers Party.
	   Prime Minister Kenny Anthony hailed the results as evidence that
his party retains public confidence. In the young Caribbean
nation's largest election landslide, Labour defeated the Workers
party in the May, 1997 general election. The Workers party had
ruled for all but three years since St. Lucia gained independence
in 1979.
	   With the win in Friday's special election, Labour continues to
hold 16 of the 17 seats in the assembly.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Dean once lost in Puerto Rico forest resigns post
	   HURON, Ohio (AP) _ A college dean who spent 12 days last summer
lost in a rain forest will resign at the end of the school year.
	   Darby Williams has been dean of Bowling Green's Firelands campus
for five years. He may remain at Bowling Green as an administrator
or a professor, said Lesley Ruszkowski, a spokeswoman at Firelands.
	   She said he has been considering a career change for several
months.
	   She said Williams, 56, decided to announce his resignation now
to give the college a full year to search for a replacement.
	   Williams was reported missing in July 1997 in the 28,000-acre
Caribbean National Forest. He had gone there to take video
recordings for a book he planned on Puerto Rico.
	   When a heavy rain started, he got lost. He said he ate snails
and ferns and drank mountain water for 12 days while searching for
a way out.
	   More than 60 police officials, civil defense officials and
forest rangers, assisted by police dogs, searched the area for
Williams. He eventually found the trail he was on when he entered
the forest and was found by tourists.
</TEXT>
