<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Bo Derek,0783 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Horses and surf attract widowed Bo Derek to TV series
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo LA303 &QL; 
 &UR; By BOB THOMAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Bo Derek, who gave new meaning to the number
10, is joining the fall television sweepstakes. She plays the
mother of two teen-age boys in an NBC dramatic series, ``Wind on
Water.''
	   Judging from the pilot episode, which debuts Saturday, Oct. 17,
the show is a cross between ``The Big Valley'' and a Bruce Brown
surfing movie.
	   Like Barbara Stanwyck in the 1960s Western series, Miss Derek is
the matriarch of a sprawling cattle ranch. In the grand old
tradition of Westerns, she fights over water rights with a neighbor
who wants to take over her property.
	   And since the spread is located on the Big Island in Hawaii,
there is ample opportunity for water sports, and the two sons are
championship surfers.
	   Miss Derek has had a curious career since her sensational
appearance in 1979 as the object of Dudley Moore's obsession in
``10.'' Instead of accepting the big-money roles that were
available, she worked only with her mentor and husband, John Derek.
She produced the films and he directed and photographed them.
	   None achieved popularity.
	   John Derek died of heart failure on May 22 at 71. His widow put
their 31-acre (13-hectare) horse ranch in Santa Ynez on sale and is
returning to acting with ``Wind on Water.''
	   Miss Derek paused for a recent interview at the production
company's Encino offices before heading to the Hawaii location
where the whole series will be filmed.
	   She was accompanied by her German shepherd, who was trained as a
guard dog in Germany and Hungary.
	   There is a hint of maturity in the Derek face but it still could
stop freeway traffic. So could her figure.
	   Except for a couple of projects she doesn't want to remember,
Miss Derek hasn't acted for 10 years.
	   ``I don't think I meant it to be such a long delay; it just
worked out that way,'' she said. ``As you may remember, I'm not the
most motivated person in the world. I'm very good at finding
excuses why I shouldn't do something.
	   ``Recently I said, `You know what? This is becoming a habit.
It's time I jump back in the water and try to swim.' ''
	   When ``Wind on Water'' was proposed to her last March, it seemed
comfortable for her _ except for playing the mother of two
teen-agers.
	   ``I have no experience, and I guess they're different from dogs
and horses,'' she said with a smile. ``But I've seen my sisters and
my brother with their children, as well as my friends. So it's not
entirely foreign to me.''
	   She certainly feels comfortable in the role of Ciel Connolly,
whose life has been spent on horseback and in the water.
	   ``I was brought up on the beaches of Southern California,'' she
said. ``A lot of water sports. Because of my father's job, we went
to Hawaii a lot. My little-girl dream would have been to have the
horse ranch on the water in Hawaii. Life took me somewhere else,
but this would have been a dream for me.''
	   Ciel Connelly is widowed in the first episode. Her sons are
described as ``hotshot athletes,'' so the series affords a variety
of sports. The first episode features a leap from a helicopter to a
ski run (that's right: skiing in Hawaii) as well as a surfing
contest with huge waves. Also promised: windsurfing, polo, canoe
racing, dirt biking, snowboarding and skydiving.
	   The series arose before John Derek died.
	   ``He didn't like the show,'' his widow admitted. He couldn't see
her playing a matriarch _ ``That was not the little girl he fell in
love with. I'm 41, so it's definitely possible. But he just didn't
see that for me.
	   ``But I feel very good about it. ... Before John died, it would
have been trying. Now it's an absolute blessing.
	   ``The strangest part about being alone now is making decisions
for myself, which I've never really done. I was 16, still living at
home, when I met John. So I've never really been on my own, even to
decide what I want for dinner, or what I'm going to do tomorrow.
You always take into consideration the person you're with, or your
family.
	   ``I always relied on John's opinions and experience, coming from
a good place, from someone who really loved me.''
	   She expressed no regret about working almost exclusively with
her husband after ``10,'' although she acknowledged it ``might be
some kind of self-defense mechanism.
	   ``Not that the decisions not to work were always right. But they
were mine. I had to live with the consequences, good or bad.
Whatever those decisions were they had to be part of the reason my
relationship with John remained so good for 25 years.''
</TEXT>
