<DATE_TIME> 08/22/1998 20:49:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2867 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-US-SturgesCenten     08-22 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Sturges Centennial,1024 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Preston Sturges celebrated on 100th anniversary of his birth
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With ARTS-Sturges Centennial-Rules &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NY343 &QL; 
 &UR; By BOB THOMAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ With his sly wit and uncanny feel for the
American idiom and character, writer-director Preston Sturges hit
the heights from 1940 to '44 with a series of film comedies
considered classics today.
	   His descent was equally rapid. The glory years ended with ``Hail
the Conquering Hero,'' and he spent his last 15 years struggling to
recapture his brilliance.
	   Sturges was born 100 years ago Aug. 29, and the centennial is
being celebrated this month on both coasts: Manhattan's Film Forum
offered a festival of his films with newly minted prints, and the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences scheduled a tribute
featuring the filmmaker's widow, Sandy Sturges, and Eddie Bracken,
his star of ``Conquering Hero'' and ``The Miracle of Morgan's
Creek.''
	   The Los Angeles County Museum of Art was staging a major
retrospective, and Universal Studios Home Video issued four movies
Sturges wrote but did not direct. His directorial classics are
available on videocassette.
	   His films have long been revered by movie buffs, though,
astoundingly, none made the American Film Institute's recent list
of the 100 best films. They constituted one of the greatest bursts
of creativity in film history: ``The Great McGinty,'' ``Christmas
in July,'' ``The Lady Eve,'' ``Sullivan's Travels,'' ``The Palm
Beach Story,'' ``The Miracle of Morgan's Creek,'' ``Hail the
Conquering Hero.''
	   ``He was touched with genius,'' comments Billy Wilder, who first
knew Sturges when both were writers at Paramount Studio in the
1930s.
	   ``I thought he was a genius,'' agrees Betty Hutton, who played
the non-singing role of a mother of sextuplets in ``Morgan's
Creek.'' ``I loved the man.''
	   ``He was my best friend,'' adds Eddie Bracken. ``I wouldn't want
to change a word of his scripts, they were so perfect.''
	   Sturges' own life contains the stuff that movies are made of. He
was born into a wealthy Chicago family and educated in private
American schools and in France, Germany and Switzerland. His mother
owned a cosmetics company, and at 16 he was managing the office in
Deauville, France.
	   He flew for the Army in World War I, then returned to the
cosmetics company, where he invented a lipstick that wouldn't be
transferred by a kiss. In the late 1920s he drifted into the New
York theater, first as stage manager, then as playwright, scoring a
hit with ``Strictly Dishonorable.'' After a couple of flops, he
shifted to Hollywood.
	   Like most screenwriters, Sturges was disturbed by how directors
mangled his scripts. In 1940, he urged the Paramount bosses to let
him direct his political satire, ``The Great McGinty.'' Since the
low-budget film presented little risk of financial loss, they
agreed.
	   ``Sturges was the first writer to become a director,'' says
Billy Wilder. ``I was the second, and then came John Huston, Joe
Mankiewicz and others who convinced the studio bosses they could
film their scripts better than anyone else.''
	   ``The Great McGinty'' earned Sturges his only Oscar, for
original script. He continued writing hit after hit, aiming gentle
satire at such American institutions as politics, advertising and
hero worship.
	   Even though he was bringing acclaim and money to Paramount,
Sturges' oddball habits disturbed studio executives. Eddie Bracken
recalls when production boss Buddy DeSylva came to the ``Morgan's
Creek'' set in mid-afternoon to complain that no film had been shot
that day:
	   ``The studio had a rule that directors had to shoot (at least)
three pages of script per day. DeSylva kept complaining until
Preston said, `Get off my set.' By 6 o'clock he had shot 11 pages.
Of course for the next three days he did retakes on those 11
pages.''
	   Sturges' methods were indeed unique. He preferred to write his
scripts in the early hours of the morning. A stock company composed
of silent screen comics, ex-vaudevillians, Broadway has-beens and
former prizefighters peopled scripts awash with dialogue, to be
spoken at a breakneck pace.
	   ``Diana Lynn and I had a 5-minute scene of rapid dialogue in
`Morgan's Creek,' '' Hutton remembers. ``We did it perfectly in one
take! Preston was delighted, and he asked how I could do it. I said
I memorized it like a song, learning the lines rhythmically.''
	   A clash of egos at Paramount led to Sturges's departure.
	   ``He went crazy when he became partners with Howard Hughes,''
declares Wilder. ``They bought their own studio, and that was the
beginning of Sturges' decline. He never did anything important
after that.''
	   At two o'clock one morning in 1945, this reporter visited
Sturges at his new headquarters at California Studio, where he was
working on a script for a Harold Lloyd comeback he titled ``The Sin
of Harold Diddlebock.''
	   An actor read pages from the script, and the great man nodded
approvingly. With his trim mustache, handsome features and deep,
cultivated voice, he resembled an actor himself.
	   ``Diddlebock'' turned into a disaster. Hughes kept demanding
changes, finally cut the film himself and released it as ``Mad
Wednesday.'' It was a resounding failure.
	   Darryl Zanuck hired Sturges for two films at Fox: ``Unfaithfully
Yours,'' a romantic comedy with Rex Harrison and Linda Darnell, and
a Betty Grable Western, ``The Beautiful Blonde from Bashful Bend.''
Both showed signs of the Sturges brilliance, but failed to find an
audience. Sturges' Hollywood career had ended.
	   He exiled himself to Paris, the scene of his youthful days. He
managed to make one last film, ``The French They Are a Funny
Race,'' released in the United States in 1955 to little notice.
	   ``He remained the boulevardier,'' Wilder recalls. ``He occupied
a table at the Alexander cafe on the Avenue George V, cadging
drinks from American tourists who passed by.''
	   On Christmas Day, 1958, he returned to New York with plans of
reviving his career. He died a few weeks later at the age of 60.
</TEXT>
