w2873 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-UAE-Hollywoodoft     08-22 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-UAE-Hollywood of the Gulf,0757 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A multi-milllionaie invests dlrs 100 million in film development in
</HEADLINE>
Dubai &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY302 &QL; 
 &UR; By FAIZA SALEH AMBAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) _ This small ambitious emirate
got the nickname, Hong Kong of the Middle East, for its role as a
commercial hub, shopping mecca and top tourist draw for the
surrounding region.
	   Now it wants to add another notch to its belt _ Hollywood of the
Gulf.
	   Multi-millionaire businessman Khalaf al-Habtoor, the man behind
the vision, has plans. Big plans.
	   He has invested dlrs 100 million in film development in Dubai,
brought in superstars Patrick Swayze and Jean-Claude Van Damme to
discuss future film roles, and envisions building a film school and
studio.
	   Some see oil-rich Dubai _ with its stifling heat and
conservative Muslim views _ more as a source of investment than as
a setting for making movies for worldwide audiences.
	   But the bespectacled Al-Habtoor, 46, trim from hours of tennis,
disagrees.
	   ``Dubai is a natural choice. We are at the crossroads between
East and West. We have the infrastructure, varied locations, and
plenty of cheap labor,'' he says.
	   A number of movie-stars, screen-writers, directors and producers
have started flocking to Dubai, lured by the fledgling industry and
the potential investors.
	   Aether Media, formed by Gulf contractor Jumaa al-Naboodah and
British expatriate John Robins, is working on four film projects.
Robins says he found possible backers in Saudi Arabia and Qatar and
would like to lure others across the Gulf.
	   Canadian director Izidore Musallam, whose last film starred Omar
Sharif, arrived recently with the Egyptian film star looking for
financing for a new movie.
	   Next year, Al-Habtoor Entertainment will start filming ``The Eye
of the Falcon,'' an adventure tale set in the Gulf before the
discovery of oil whose double heroes are an Arab tribesman and an
American photographer.
	   Al-Habtoor says along with inviting Swayze and Van Damme to
discuss the Western lead, he talked to Steven Seagal. The movie's
British co-producer Dominic Berger says he found interest from
distributors in the United States, Britain, Germany and France.
	   Another planned al-Habtoor film would examine conspiracy
theories behind the death of the Arab world's most popular leader,
suggesting Egyptian President Gamel Abdel Nasser may not have died
of a heart attack.
	   Al-Habtoor says he has twin goals in all his movie projects:
promoting both Dubai and Arab culture, which he feels has gotten a
bad rap on film.
	   ``There are a lot of wonderful stories in this part of the world
that would make great movies. And I would like to see Arabs shed in
a more realistic light, not only as bad guys or terrorists,'' he
says.
	   British screen-writer Gerry Sherard, who helped script ``The Eye
of the Falcon,'' plans a film with East-West interest. He bought
movie rights to a book about British pop star Cat Stevens, who
stopped singing at the height of his career after converting to
Islam.
	   ``A movie about someone like Cat Stevens, which might not find
financing in the West, has more of a chance here,'' he says.
	   Sherard is staying in Dubai because of his optimism over the
future of movie-making here. ``We need just one success story for
the industry to take off,'' he said.
	   However, many hurdles remain to the emirate becoming a Hollywood
of the Gulf.
	   Unlike Egypt and Syria _ which have made movies for decades _
Dubai has few experienced film people. Flying in talent would be
expensive.
	   Then there are the summer temperatures averaging 40 degrees
Celsius (104 Fahrenheit) and humidity of 90 percent, which make
filming practical only half the year.
	   Al-Habtoor says his planned film school and the production
called complex ``Dreamland'' could overcome some of Dubai's
shortcomings, teaching film skills and allowing interior shots in
summer.
	   As for the expense of bringing in talent, al-Habtoor has an
edge. Among his properties are hotels, a car dealership and a
construction company, meaning he can put up and drive around actors
and technicians _ and even build sets.
	   But al-Habtoor, one of the emirate's wealthiest businessmen,
makes clear he's not motivated by charity in pushing Dubai as a
movie capital.
	   ``We're willing to break even or even incur a small loss on the
first two films. Then we expect to make money,'' he said.
``Otherwise we cannot continue. It has to be profitable.''
</TEXT>
