<SLUG> BC-ARTS-James Carter-Album,0253 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Common thread in James Carter's new album is the Hammond organ
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With ARTS-US-James Carter &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The common thread running through James Carter's
new album ``In Carterian Fashion'' (Atlantic) is the Hammond organ.
The 10 tracks each feature one of three organists _ Cyrus Chestnut,
Henry Butler and Craig Taborn _ backing Carter and his band.
	   ``Our premise is to give an overview of the importance of the
organ in the black music experience,'' said Carter. ``Whatever the
situation, there's a certain soul that I've grown up hearing in the
organ.''
	   The selections go back to the spiritual roots (``Trouble in the
World'') through the tenor-organ combo sound of the 1950s
(``Lockjaw's Lament'') and up to 1970s disco funk (``In Carterian
Fashion'') and more modern free-form (``Odyssey'').
	   Carter has recently been in the studio working on pianist
Chestnut's new album and performing tunes from ``Porgy and Bess''
for Herbie Hancock's ``Gershwin's World,'' a tribute marking the
centennial of George Gershwin's birth.
	   Although his stylistic tastes might seem eclectic, Carter sees
the link between jazz past and present.
	   ``The way I was brought up musically is that the music doesn't
really separate. ... To me it all just relates. One wouldn't be
existing without the other. I've heard Lester (Bowie) do certain
things on trumpet that I've also heard `Sweets' (Edison) do,'' said
Carter. ``The music to me is all a part of one continuum.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-James Carter-Album; CT:i; 
