<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-James Carter,0755 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
James Carter: he's got sax appeal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With ARTS-James Carter Album &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photo NY344 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES J. GANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ James Carter swaggers onto the Bryant Park
bandstand in midtown Manhattan for his JVC Jazz Festival set with
the self-assuredness of a young Muhammad Ali. He is cocky,
handsome, charismatic and, at times, playful and humorous.
	   The 29-year-old saxophonist is a legitimate contender for the
tenor title long held by Sonny Rollins. Although tenor sax is his
main horn, because Carter says ``it comes closest to the human
voice,'' he also ranks among the top vote-getters in jazz magazine
polls for soprano and baritone sax and miscellaneous instrument
(bass clarinet).
	   On a balmy late summer evening in the park, Carter shows the
audience what sets him apart from many of his contemporaries who
are locked into a neotraditionalist approach. Leading his quintet,
he covers a full spectrum of jazz styles from swing to the
avant-garde _ sometimes in a single piece. His influences include
not only the legendary jazz saxophonists, but also Jimi Hendrix
(for his multinote playing and freedom of expression) and old
Warner Bros. cartoons with orchestra music by Carl Stalling (for
the use of sound effects to express emotions).
	   As Carter bobs and weaves _ using body language to punctuate his
powerful playing _ the audience begins to react. A female fan
shouts out ``talk to me'' and ``work it'' when Carter gets down and
dirty in a funk groove in the title piece to his new album, ``In
Carterian Fashion'' (Atlantic). Suddenly, it's as if he's playing
just for her _ and not a crowd of several thousand.
	   ``In essence, I feel that there should be a dialogue with the
audience, just in general bringing the music back to the people,''
said Carter. ``There's a point where the audience needs to be able
to identify with certain things.''
	   Carter wants to reach beyond the hard-core jazz audience. He was
among the young jazz lions featured in Robert Altman's 1996 film
``Kansas City'' _ ``a jazz memory'' of the director's hometown in
the 1930s. He was appropriately cast as the aggressive-playing and
flirtatious tenor saxophonist Ben Webster.
	   There's no question that Carter has both sex and sax appeal.
He's now represented by Wilhelmina Models. He was ``The Cat in the
Hat'' in a July 1997 GQ magazine spread in which he modeled clothes
by some of his favorite designers, including Giorgio Armani and
Joseph Abboud.
	   ``James is a natural,'' said Kevin Jones, creative director at
Wilhelmina. ``He is attractive, wears clothes very well, and is
making a fashion statement. ... It's a strong, positive black male
image.''
	   Beneath his brash, bold image, Carter holds deep-rooted core
values. He wants his music to be accessible, but doesn't water it
down into a pablum for the ears. He describes what he does as
``edutainment.''
	   Carter grew up in a musical family in Detroit, and describes
music ``as the glue that kept us together.'' He began studying
saxophone at 11. As a teen-ager, he was invited to play some dates
with Wynton Marsalis. He moved to New York in 1990. He made his
first recording as a leader in Japan (``JC on the Set'') in 1993.
His 1995 Atlantic debut, ``The Real Quietstorm,'' established him
as a saxophone contender.
	   Carter, who lives on Manhattan's Upper West Side with his wife
Tevis, a former model, is obsessed with the history of his
instrument. He is constantly tinkering with his collection of
dozens of saxophones and other woodwind instruments. While on tour,
he visits saxophone makers and can trace the history of instruments
back to the date they were shipped from the factory.
	   He holds a deep respect for the jazz tradition and its elder
statesmen. His 1996 album ``Conversin' With the Elders'' (Atlantic)
paired Carter with some of the musicians who were his mentors and
who inspired him _ from swing veterans, trumpeter Harry ``Sweets''
Edison and tenor saxophonist Buddy Tate of the Count Basie band, to
modernists, baritone saxophonist Hamiett Bluiett and trumpeter
Lester Bowie.
	   ``My initial concept was just being thankful for individuals who
helped my development,'' said Carter. ``As opposed to giving them a
posthumous tribute, this was an active one where these individuals
are still alive and able to play. ... How many people do you find
nowadays up in Harlem who are actually conversing with the elders
as opposed to backlashing at them?''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-US-James Carter; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
