<HEADER>
w2890 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-US-JamesMarsden     08-22 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-James Marsden,0722 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Five Questions with James Marsden: from nerdy teen to the big
</HEADLINE>
screen &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photo NY345 &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHLEEN SAMPEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   At 24, James Marsden bears more than a passing resemblance to
Tom Cruise, so it's hard to believe he was ever a misfit. But
Marsden insists that before he took his first drama class in Putnam
City North High School in his hometown of Oklahoma City, his social
ineptitude had his mother worried.
	   ``I was kind of this nerdy kid who didn't wear the cool clothes,
and I weighed 100 pounds (45 kilograms),'' he says. ``My mom saw
that I was not quick to get involved in the cliques in school. She
wanted me to try out for sports, get involved in the drama class.
She thought getting up and performing in front of people would let
down my guard.''
	   In ``Disturbing Behavior,'' his first big-screen film, Marsden
must keep his guard up.
	   The clever teen thriller is about how some creative
brain-tinkering by a guidance counselor turns slacker high-school
students into overachievers _ and violent killers.
	   It also stars 19-year-old Katie Holmes of U.S. television's
``Dawson's Creek.'' She plays Marsden's love interest in the film.
Marsden considers her a good friend. ``She's got a great sense of
humor and more talent than she needs to have at that age,'' he
says, laughing.
	   Marsden was her age when he packed up his car and headed for Los
Angeles in search of an acting career. ``My dad said he'd support
me financially for one year so I could concentrate on getting
parts.
	   ``I was very lucky that my dad grew up with a casting director
who's now in L.A. who knew a manager who was actually legitimate
and agreed to take me on,'' he says. ``You can easily fall into the
wrong hands in Hollywood.''
	   Success came with small roles in U.S. TV shows like ``The
Nanny'' and ``Saved by the Bell.'' In between acting stints, he
modeled Versace.
	   Marsden was the original Griffin on the Fox hit, ``Party of
Five,'' which he left to join the cast of ABC's ``Second Noah.''
That series was canceled after 1 1-2 seasons but it showcased
Marsden's singing talents when his character joined a rock band.
	   Later, Marsden appeared with Vanessa Redgrave in the CBS
miniseries, ``Bella Mafia.'' His movie-of-the-week credits include
``Ambush in Waco,'' ``Taken Away,'' ``Search and Rescue'' and ``On
the Edge of Innocence.''
	   1. ``Disturbing Behavior'' makes some interesting points about
the dangers of conformity. Do you think they apply in real life?
	   Marsden: I think people can fall into the trap of belonging to a
group just because they're socially accepted among their peers.
Especially when it's against their personality. Somebody who has no
interest in doing drugs or drinking will hang out with those people
just because they think they're cool. That's one of the main things
that kids lie to themselves about.
	   2. In addition to being an actor, you're also a trained singer,
right?
	   Marsden: I've kind of let my voice go a bit. In high school and
college I was always in vocal training classes and kept it in
really good shape. I love Frank Sinatra and Bobby Darin. I love
that kind of singing.
	   3. Would you like to sing on the big screen?
	   Marsden: Yes. I'm so upset that the movie musical has frittered
away. Ever since 'Grease' there hasn't been anything. I would love
to do a new kind of 'Grease' movie or an old movie like 'Singin' in
the Rain' shot in Technicolor.
	   4. When you were in the miniseries ``Bella Mafia'' did you pick
up any acting tips from Vanessa Redgrave?
	   Marsden: What I learned is that you always have to stick up for
yourself as an actor because ultimately you're the person up on the
screen. I would see her working on the set and the director would
say to do one thing and she would absolutely not do it. Some people
see that as difficult but I see it as sticking up for what you know
is right.
	   5. You once said you had no ambition whatsoever and that's why
you dropped out of Oklahoma State University. Is that true?
	   Marsden: I say it with a sense of humor. It seemed like there
wasn't anything in college that I wanted to go after. I didn't want
to settle for anything like being an insurance agent or a news
broadcaster. I wanted to give acting a shot.
</TEXT>
