<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Celebrity Birthdays,0653 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   In the spotlight: Elvis Costello
	    &UR; Personal stats: Elvis Costello was born Declan Patrick McManus
on Aug. 25, 1954, in Liverpool, Merseyside, England. He quit school
at 15. He moved to London, where he worked as a computer operator
at a perfume factory. He formed his own band, Flip City, and began
moonlighting on the local club scene, honing his songwriting
skills. By 1976, he was sending demo tapes to record companies.
	    &UR; A pseudonym is born: His great-grandmother's name was Costello.
He started using the name D.P. Costello after Flip City disbanded.
After signing with Stiff Records, he changed his first name, saying
``I thought Elvis was a better name than Jesus, and almost as
exclusive.'' In 1977, he made his live debut as Elvis Costello at
the Nashville in London. Shortly thereafter, he quit his day job at
the perfume factory.
	    &UR; Stardom comes: ``My Aim Is True,'' Costello's debut album, was
hailed by critics. More than a dozen albums later, he has clearly
demonstrated that he never plows the same musical furrow twice. His
songs have flirted with various aspects of pop music _ like
``Everyday I Write the Book,'' ``Watching the Detectives'' and
``Alison'' _ as well as country, folk, Irish traditional, baroque
pop, jazz and children's music.
	   ``I'm not trying to annoy them,'' he says of his listeners. ``I
have to be prepared to lose people who want everything to stay the
same, in order to gain the people who are prepared to listen with
all their heart. That's much more important, really.''
	    &UR; Recently: Costello worked with Brian Eno on the track ``My Dark
Life'' for the compilation CD, ``Songs in the Key of X,'' music
from and inspired by the popular U.S. television show ``The
X-Files.''
	    &UR; What the critics think: ``Perhaps the most versatile and adept
of rock's many literate non-singers, Costello employs a wide range
of peculiar inflections and punning emphases,'' says Rolling Stone
magazine. ``Underneath the churning, impatient veneer lurks a
fan-turned-musician with a startling command of roots.''
	   Celebrity birthdays for Aug. 23-29:
	   Aug. 23: Actress Barbara Eden is 64. Actor Ronny Cox is 60.
Actress Shelley Long is 49. Actor-singer Rick Springfield is 49.
Musician Dean DeLeo of Stone Temple Pilots is 37.
	   Aug. 24: Musician Jim Capaldi (Traffic) is 54. Musician Ken
Hensley (Uriah Heep) is 53. Actor Joe Regalbuto (``Murphy Brown'')
is 49. Actor Steve Guttenberg is 40. Actress Marlee Matlin is 33.
Actor-comedian Dave Chappelle is 25.
	   Aug. 25: Game show host Monty Hall is 75. Actor Sean Connery is
68. Actor Tom Skerritt is 65. Actress Anne Archer is 51. Singer
Gene Simmons (Kiss) is 49. Actor John Savage is 49. Singer Elvis
Costello is 44. Actress Ally Walker (``Profiler'') is 37. Musician
Vivian Campbell (Def Leppard) is 36. Actor Blair Underwood is 34.
Rap DJ Terminator X (Public Enemy) is 32. Country singer Jo Dee
Messina is 29.
	   Aug. 26: Singer Valerie Simpson is 50. Singer Bob Cowsill is 49.
Actor Michael Jeter (``Evening Shade'') is 46. Musician Branford
Marsalis is 38. Actor Chris Burke (``Life Goes On'') is 33.
Musician Adrian Young (No Doubt) is 29. Actor Macaulay Culkin is
18.
	   Aug. 27: Musician Daryl Dragon (The Captain and Tennille) is 56.
Actress Tuesday Weld is 55. Actor Paul Reubens is 46. Musician Alex
Lifeson (Rush) is 45. Musician Tony Kanal (No Doubt) is 28. Actress
Sarah Chalke (``Roseanne'') is 22.
	   Aug. 28: Actor-dancer Donald O'Connor is 73. Actor Ben Gazzara
is 68. Actor David Soul is 55. Actor Daniel Stern is 41. Actor
Jason Priestley is 29. Country singer LeAnn Rimes is 16.
	   Aug. 29: Actor-director Sir Richard Attenborough is 75. Actor
Elliott Gould is 60. Movie director William Friedkin is 59. Singer
Michael Jackson is 40. Actress Rebecca DeMornay is 36. Singer
Me'Shell NdegeOcello is 29. Actress Carla Gugino is 27.
</TEXT>
