<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0527 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Mexico and Peru &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALMOLOYA DE JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) _ A pretrial hearing took a
bizarre twist Saturday when a defendant told the judge that his
profession was ``kidnapping.''
	   Daniel Arizmendi, 40, known as the ``ear-loper'' for allegedly
sending ransom notes attached to his victims' ears, refused to
enter a plea in the case, saying he was tired after three days of
police questioning.
	   His mistress, Dulce Maria Paz Venegas is also on trial and also
would not enter a plea.
	   When Judge Armando Baez Espinoza asked Arizmendi to repeat
himself, the Arizmendi replied: ``I do kidnappings ... I am a
kidnapper.''
	   Their court-appointed lawyer asked that the hearing be recessed
until Thursday, and the judge ordered the couple held without bail.
	   Arizmendi is accused of kidnapping, racketeering, laundering
money from ransom payments and illegal possession of firearms. Paz
is accused of racketeering and money laundering.
	   ___ &UR; 
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A famous theater and television comic was
wounded during a holdup in Mexico City on Saturday, but managed to
kill one of the gunmen before he was shot.
	   A police report said Eduardo Manzano suffered three bullet
wounds during the shoot-out in the midtown neighborhood of Roma and
was hospitalized in serious but stable condition.
	   Manzano was buying film at a photographic shop when three armed
men rushed in, the police report said. Manzano drew a gun and fired
at one of the men, killing him instantly.
	   The other two fired back, wounding Manzano, and fled in a
waiting automobile. The car was found by police abandoned a few
blocks away. Manzano was rushed to a hospital.
	   Mexico City has been hit by a crime wave in the past four years.
Police records show an average of 700 crimes involving a weapon
were committed every day in the Mexican capital last year,
resulting in six deaths daily.
	   ___
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) _ Ecuadorean troops began to withdraw Saturday
from a disputed region where it fought a brief war with neighboring
Peru in 1995, easing a tense border standoff, Peru's Foreign
Ministry said.
	   ``The withdrawal should be concluded in seven days,'' a Foreign
Ministry news release said.
	   There's been no official comment from Ecuador on the withdrawal.
The ministry news release did not mention if the Peru's troops were
also withdrawing.
	   Peru charged two weeks ago that 300 Ecuadorean troops had
infiltrated its territory and were ``face-to-face'' with Peruvian
troops in a remote stretch of mountainous jungle 560 miles north of
Lima.
	   Ecuador denied the charge, saying the border was undefined in
the area, known as the Cordillera del Condor.
	   Fears of a war were defused on Aug. 13, when Peru and Ecuador
agreed to allow the deployment of international peacekeepers in the
area as a prelude to the removal of both countries' troops and the
creation of a temporary demilitarized zone.
	   The countries have fought wars in 1941, 1981 and 1995 over their
disputed border. In the last two, fighting was over 49 miles (78
kilometers) of unmarked border. 	   
</TEXT>
