<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Entertainment Flashbacks,0493 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
That Was the Week That Was
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Entertainment highlights during the week of Aug. 23-29:
	   65 years ago: Jean Harlow, Wallace Beery, Marie Dressler, Lionel
Barrymore, John Barrymore and Billie Burke starred in the film,
``Dinner at Eight.''
	   50 years ago: Variety reported that Paramount newsreels were
presenting more feature stories because they couldn't compete with
television's prompt delivery of the news.
	   And ``Rope'' starred James Stewart, Farley Granger and John
Dall. It was director Alfred Hitchcock's first color film, and it
was notable for Hitchcock's use of extended takes to provide a
seamless flow of movement.
	   40 years ago: George Harrison joined John Lennon's band, the
Quarry Men, which also included bassist Paul McCartney.
	   35 years ago: Peter, Paul and Mary performed ``Blowin' In The
Wind'' before civil rights marchers who had gathered in Washington
to hear Martin Luther King Jr. speak.
	   30 years ago: The Beatles released ``Hey Jude'' as a single.
	   And Who drummer Keith Moon drove a Lincoln into the swimming
pool of a hotel in Flint, Michigan, after a raucous birthday party.
	   15 years ago: ``Merry Christmas, Mr. Lawrence,'' starring David
Bowie and Tom Conti, opened in the United States. It was director
Nagisa Oshima's first film in English.
	   10 years ago: More than 90,000 British fans joined in a 30th
birthday salute to pop music star Michael Jackson, who was
performing at Round Hay Park in Leeds, England.
	   Five years ago: The 1980s pop band Duran Duran cemented its '90s
comeback with a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame. Some 1,500 fans
turned out as the sidewalk star was unveiled. The band's 1980s hits
included ``Rio'' and ``Hungry Like a Wolf.'' They were back with an
album featuring the hit songs ``Ordinary World'' and ``Come
Undone.''
	   And a 1969 white Mercedes owned by George Harrison and used in
the Beatles' film ``Let It Be'' sold for dlrs 29,740 at an auction
of rock memorabilia in London. Other auction highlights: a pair of
Michael Jackson's dancing shoes, which fetched dlrs 5,577, and a
collection of clothing owned by the late punk rocker Sid Vicious,
which went for more than dlrs 16,900.
	    &UR; Spoken five years ago:
	   ``I found out that this was a fascinating exercise as a way to
get out of my self and into somebody else's head. It was an
opportunity to live other lives and experience things that I would
not be able to experience in my own life.'' _ Harrison Ford, on
acting.
	   ``When you walk past our star, make sure you are smiling at us
because we'll be smiling back at you.'' _ Singer Simon Le Bon of
Duran Duran, referring to the band's new star on the Hollywood Walk
of Fame.
	    &UR; Spoken one year ago:
	   ``I'm not just a rapper, I'm a singer, I'm a writer, I'm a
producer, I'm an entertainer, all of that.'' _ Rapper Missy
``Misdemeanor'' Elliott.
</TEXT>
