<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Victoria Gotti,0810 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Forget the descriptions _ she's just plain Vickie
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY324 &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY McSHANE &QC; 
 &UR; AP National Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Victoria Gotti has this dream.
	   The author has just finished her latest best seller and
completed her round of interviews. She goes through the book
reviews and the newspaper clippings, and not one contains these
phrases:
	   _ Mafia princess.
	   _ Daughter of the don.
	   _ Capo di cutie capi.
	   ``In a perfect world,'' Ms. Gotti says with a sigh, ``in my
profession, you want to go before the camera or the critics as
Victoria Gotti the author, not Victoria Gotti, the daughter of ...
	   ``By the next book, maybe people will say, `The heck with the
background.'''
	   Or maybe not.
	   When your father is the jailed head of the Gambino crime family,
and your brother is allegedly his hand-picked successor, it's tough
to maintain that public perception of a career woman.
	   Things happen.
	   On this summer afternoon, shortly before an interview to promote
her second novel, ``I'll Be Watching You,'' Victoria put up her
dlrs 4 million Long Island mansion as collateral for brother John's
bail.
	   ``SIS TO THE RESCUE,'' read the front-page Daily News headline.
Sibling John ``Junior'' Gotti has been jailed since January on a
variety of criminal charges.
	   ``We deal with it,'' she explains patiently. ``We keep dealing
with it. It's not something you run away from.''
	   The blond, 34-year-old mother of three doesn't shy away from
addressing the Gotti family's reputed links to the Gambino family.
But she prefers to play down talk of organized crime when it comes
to her work as an author.
	   ``Victoria Gotti lives on Long Island with her husband and three
sons,'' says the understated book jacket bio. And ``I'll Be
Watching You'' steers clear of the mob; the book is a love triangle
tale intertwining a powerful Kennedyesque clan, an illegitimate son
and a best-selling author.
	   ``It's entertainment, escapism,'' she says. ``This is a little
more entertaining, a little lighter than my first book.''
	   That novel, ``The Senator's Daughter,'' garnered positive
reviews for the suburban housewife turned novelist.
	   ``Gotti weaves a fascinating tale of murder, betrayal, loss of
trust, and revenge,'' the San Francisco Examiner said of her debut.
	   ``I'll Be Watching You'' received a thumbs-up from a more
important critic: her father. John Gotti, serving a life sentence
for murder and racketeering, read the book in his Marion, Illinois,
jail cell.
	   ``I got a letter in the mail saying, `I liked it!''' she says.
``That was a great, great feeling. It seems we always seek out
parents' approval, no matter how old we are.''
	   The Dapper Don might have recognized a bit of himself in one of
the book's main characters, business magnate Dmitri Constantinos.
	   Constantinos offers odds on his acquittal in a criminal trial _
a stunt first pulled by Victoria's father. ``Three-to-one odds I
beat this,'' Gotti had boldly (and accurately) predicted of a 1990
assault case.
	   And during Gotti's first federal trial, defense attorney Bruce
Cutler told the jury: ``So he didn't go to Harvard. So he gambled a
little. That makes him a mob leader?''
	   Fictional defense attorney Evan Miller, representing
Constantinos, offers this defense of his client: ``(He) dresses in
dlrs 2,000 suits. He wears expensive shoes. He had influential
associates. But is that a crime?''
	   Not in Victoria Gotti's books.
	   Ms. Gotti, the second of five children, does her writing late at
night, sitting down at 11 p.m. and banging at a keyboard until she
grows weary. She's up most mornings at 6:30, taking care of her
brood.
	   ``I sit down for two or three hours, until I can't work any
more,'' she explains. ``I'm very nocturnal, although that's not by
choice. I'm sort of an insomniac.''
	   Actually, heart medication makes it difficult for Ms. Gotti to
fall asleep. She was diagnosed in college with mitral valve
prolapse, a condition which can cause dizziness or palpitations.
	   Her struggle with the illness led to Ms. Gotti's first book,
1995's ``Women and Mitral Valve Prolapse.'' Her move to fiction
soon followed _ but she kept a strong dose of reality in her
fictional tales.
	   ``I don't like that whole Cinderella stuff, with a fairy tale
ending,'' she says. ``I try to keep everything real. Everything
doesn't always end happy.''
	   One of Ms. Gotti's most enjoyable tasks is answering her own
mail, complying with requests for autographs and pictures.
	   Why?
	   She believes such contact dispels the ``Mafia princess'' image _
and she dreams of the day when it disappears.
	   ``I wake up, and there are children, beds to make,'' she
explains merrily. ``I work. It's a reward in itself. ... We don't
live in a Francis Ford Coppola world.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-US-Victoria Gotti; CT:i; 
