w2912 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-US-AngelaBassett     08-22 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Angela Bassett,0722 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angela Bassett discovers a new groove
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: 'How Stella Got Her Groove Back' opened Aug. 14 &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY323 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARK KENNEDY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Think vulnerable.
	   Make it soft and tender. Then turn it into a movie role. OK, now
cast actresses.
	   Which of Hollywood's actresses immediately spring to mind?
	   Chances are Angela Bassett doesn't.
	   So the 40-year-old actress was fighting a case of nerves in the
back of the theater during the premiere of ``How Stella Got Her
Groove Back,'' a movie with a mush level that could rival a
Hallmark warehouse. Bassett fills the sexy title role in the
adaptation of Terry McMillan's go-girl best seller about a
40-year-old stockbroker who falls hard for a 20-year-old Jamaican
Adonis.
	   ``I was a little worried, to be honest,'' admits Bassett, who
has played her share of battered, abused and abandoned spouses.
``This was quite a new direction for me. How was it going down?''
	   From the next seat, the answer came with a friendly squeeze from
her husband, actor Courtney Vance. He leaned over during one
smoochie scene and whispered in delight: ``Oh, you look like a
little girl here!''
	   ``He's used to seeing me play just strong,'' Bassett says. ``And
courageous. And intense. This time, he said it was nice to see the
little girl.''
	   That's an unfamiliar side of Bassett, especially after she
ignited the screen like an acetylene torch in ``What's Love Got to
Do With It?'' ``Malcolm X'' and ``Waiting to Exhale.''
	   ``I love that she allowed her Stella to have fun,'' says Deborah
Schindler, who produced the film. ``We see her be playful. We
haven't seen that before that I really remember.''
	   It's 10 years since Bassett left the New York stage for Los
Angeles to break into film. The Ivy League-educated actress did a
few bit movie parts (``Kindergarten Cop,'' ``F/X''), some
television (``The Cosby Show,'' ``thirtysomething,'' ``The Guiding
Light''), and some straight-to-video clunkers (``Critters 4'').
	   It wasn't until she stepped into a pair of spiky high heels for
her strutting, hip-shimmying performance as Tina Turner in ``What's
Love Got to Do With It?'' that Bassett became a star, receiving an
Academy Award nomination.
	   Reared by an aunt in Harlem until she was 5, Bassett moved to
St. Petersburg, Florida, with her mother, who struggled alone to
raise two daughters.
	   ``My mother was on us 24 hours a day ... She never let us sit
back, she was always active because she never wanted me to make the
same mistakes she had as a young woman,'' Bassett says.
	   After ``Love,'' Bassett's next big role was Bernadine, a mother
of two whose husband leaves her for another woman in the 1995
surprise hit, ``Waiting to Exhale.''
	   In one blistering scene, Bernadine stuffs all her unfaithful
husband's designer duds into his BMW and torches it.
	   In the flesh, Bassett's fearsome image soon gives way. Those
biceps still knot gloriously. And her cheekbones are so chiseled it
seems at times as if she's nestling two golf balls up there. But
there's a delicateness, too: Her soft, almond-shaped eyes and
expressive eyebrows give her an elegant, leonine beauty. She curls
up in her chair like a kitten.
	   Bassett got interested in acting during a class trip to
Washington when she was in the 11th grade. One night, she saw James
Earl Jones rip up the stage in ``Of Mice and Men'' at the John F.
Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. Bassett says she left
weeping and trembling.
	   ``I knew what I had to do,'' she says, with an enormous smile.
	   What she did was go from a Florida housing project to Yale
University to Broadway and then on to Hollywood.
	   ``I look back and I can appreciate how far I've come. I sort of
stand outside myself and I still feel like the little 8-year-old
with her favorite song on the turntable. She's singing into a brush
like a microphone and she's acting out the parts for her sister and
her aunties,'' Bassett says.
	   ``There was a girl who came up to me last night. She said, 'I'm
an actress. Well, I want to be an actress. And you're my
inspiration,''' Bassett recalls. ``I'm somebody's inspiration? I
was the one looking for inspiration! I'm an inspiration to somebody
who's coming behind me? That's what amazes me.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-US-Angela Bassett; CT:i; 
