w2914 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-AudioReviews     08-22 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Audio Reviews,0765 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sound Bites: audio reviews
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ``Adore'' _ Smashing Pumpkins (Virgin)
	   The Smashing Pumpkins have taken a lot of heat for failing to
give the public ``the next great rock album.''
	   Instead, the Pumpkins _ now minus drummer Jimmy Chamberlain _
offer up 16 oddly moody love tunes. It's a bold gamble, but one
which lead singer Billy Corgan says was in the works while the
Pumpkins were riding high on 1995's kaleidoscopic ``Mellon Collie
and the Infinite Sadness.''
	   Chamberlain, once one of rock's more formidable drummers, is
sorely missed. The Pumpkins might have made a strong statement by
firing Chamberlain following his heroin debacle, but they have not
filled the void left by his absence.
	   Electronic drums and other computer-generated sounds provide the
beat to many songs on ``Adore'' _ sometimes to distraction. And
doing a quiet turn is not that new for this group. ``Disarm'' off
1993's ``Siamese Dream'' stands as one of the Pumpkins' most
powerful songs.
	   Still, ``Adore'' does succeed on several levels. Corgan's vocals
show his emotional range throughout, and the arrangements of these
tunes, especially the string-fueled ``Tear,'' are superb.
	   This disc grows on you, but it is not the next great rock album.
Some of the songs _ ``Pug,'' for instance _ yearn to be given the
full sonic Pumpkins treatment.
	   ``Adore,'' for what it's worth, is a quirky interlude for a band
continuing to grow and experiment _ and it's definitely worth a
listen.
	   _ By John Pacenti, Associated Press Writer.
	   ``Airbag/How is My Driving?'' _ Radiohead (Capitol)
	   Radiohead's ``Ok, Computer'' could be a candidate for best rock
album of the decade.
	   The 1997 disc was a soundtrack for the 1990s, positing that what
a technology-based society considers safe and normal is actually
nothing but spiritual totalitarianism in disguise. It was a rarity
in which rock became true art.
	   This English band's new release, ``Airbag/How is My Driving?''
gives a glimpse of some of the creativity that went into the music
of that previous work, but little more.
	   Fans are treated to a laydown track that never got vocals. The
other cuts mostly show how rooted this band is in British
psychedelic.
	   Only ``Pearly'' and ``Polyethylene (Part II)'' seem fleshed out
enough that they contain the otherworldly feeling that is
Radiohead's essence.
	   _ By John Pacenti, Associated Press Writer.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   ``The Elektra Years Anthology'' (Elektra) _ Paul Butterfield
Blues Band
	   This set of Paul Butterfield's earliest recordings shows the
fresh talent he had for playing Chicago blues faithfully, and for
advancing the music to broader audiences.
	   In the 1950s, Butterfield, who is white, remarkably won the
affection of the black blues giants of the time, and in tandem with
Elvin Bishop he formed the first of the great ``white blues
bands.''
	   Butterfield and Bishop were adored by the white American fans
who were drawn to folk festivals and ``roots'' music but were
alienated from classic black performers. The two also won great
standing in the blues heartland of black performers and fans.
	   ``Walkin' Blues'' in particular shows the young singer and
harmonica player with one foot in each world, pop and blues, while
the instrumental ``East West'' shows the band's rock sensibility.
	   Many record stores with weak blues sections display overpriced
box sets with photos and booklets promising to offer the gift of
history.
	   This modest package slips two discs into a single case that is
easily overlooked yet vastly more valuable.
	   _ By Ralph Siegel, Associated Press Writer.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   ``The Sugarcubes_A Collection,'' (Elektra) _ The Sugarcubes
	   It used to be that a band had to have an extensive recording
history to warrant a greatest hits album.
	   But these days even a mediocre group like the Lemonheads can
become immortalized with a ``best of'' collection. The Sugarcubes _
best known for debuting the trip-hop waif Bjork in the late '80s _
fit somewhere in between those extremes.
	   Culled from the Icelandic band's three albums from 1988-91,
``The Sugarcubes_A Collection'' includes the minor hits
``Birthday'' and ``Hit,'' as well as the lesser known gems
``Regina'' and ``Walkabout.''
	   The Sugarcubes were a quirky breath of fresh air during a stale
period in modern rock, and it's a shame they didn't stick around
longer. But then we wouldn't have witnessed Bjork's phenomenal solo
career.
	   _ By David Kligman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-Audio Reviews; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
