<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Tony Orlando,0865 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tony Orlando after the Dawn: Life and show business still good
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY328 &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN ROGERS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRANSON, Missouri (AP) _ Hide the polyester. Tony Orlando is
back with a new documentary on VH1 and thoughts of releasing some
of his old recordings.
	   To those who disdain the 1970s as the Me Generation decade of
bad music and even worse clothes, the mention of Orlando's name can
bring smirks of sarcastic recognition.
	   He was, after all, the guy who strutted around on stage and TV
doing pop songs like ``Candida'' and ``Knock Three Times'' when he
wasn't being made the butt of jokes by his singing partners, Telma
Hopkins and Joyce Vincent-Wilson, known as Dawn. Their show, which
began as a summer replacement for ``The Sonny and Cher Comedy
Hour,'' quickly became one of the decade's bigger hits, airing on
CBS from 1974 to 1976.
	   But despite those reflexively dismissive feelings about him from
'70s haters, Tony Orlando has built a career as an all-round
entertainer in the tradition of his heroes, Frank Sinatra and Sammy
Davis Jr. He has starred in Las Vegas, even played P.T. Barnum in
the hit Broadway musical ``Barnum,'' as well as having had a string
of hit songs dating as far back as 1961.
	   Now, a quarter-century after ``Tie A Yellow Ribbon Round The Ole
Oak Tree,'' became the biggest-selling record of 1973, Michael
Anthony Orlando Cassavitis, the loud, boisterous,
heart-on-his-sleeve Greek-Puerto Rican guy from New York City, is
still at it.
	   Only now he's one of the biggest stars in this Midwestern mecca
of live entertainment where legions of his fans come to see him
perform.
	   Not bad, he says proudly, for a guy who never made it to high
school.
	   ``It's funny, most people relate childhood to playing in the
baseball game, going to high school,'' Orlando says. ``My childhood
was singing doo-wop on street corners.''
	   He and his group, The Five Gents, would strut down Broadway each
day to the section of Manhattan known as Tin Pan Alley, where the
offices of all the big music companies were. ``And then we'd walk
down every floor singing, hoping someone would hear us and open the
door,'' he recalls.
	   When no one ever did, the others gave up. But Orlando kept
coming back until record producer Don Kirshner finally hired him
for dlrs 50 a week to record demos _ songs that famous singers
would hear and, it was hoped, decide to record themselves.
	   He was good-looking enough but, at 250 pounds (113 kilograms),
too fat to be a famous singer himself in those days. Or so it
seemed until Kirshner put out his version of Carole King's melodic
``Halfway to Paradise'' in 1961 and it became one of the year's
biggest hits.
	   So he slimmed down and went on tour to promote it, becoming a
teen idol with screaming girls at every show and guards to escort
him to his car.
	   ``It was quite a thing for a guy who was all of 16,'' he recalls
now.
	   And it barely lasted until he was 20, when the Beatles arrived
and pushed every teen-age crooner off the charts.
	   So he found a day job in music publishing, and he might still be
doing that if a friend from his teen idol days hadn't approached
him in 1970.
	   The friend, Hank Medress of the Tokens, the group that recorded
``The Lion Sleeps Tonight,'' told Orlando he was sure everyone
would love a song titled ``Candida,'' if he could just find a
singer to record it.
	   Orlando was worried about his job. ``I said if my boss finds out
I recorded for another label, he'll fire me.''
	   No problem. They would put out the record under a fake name _
Dawn.
	   When it rose to No. 3 on the charts, Medress was back to cut a
follow-up, ``Knock Three Times.'' It went to No. 1 and Orlando was
a pop star again.
	   ``I backed into the whole kit and caboodle as a favor for a
friend,'' he says, smiling broadly. ``Some favor, huh?''
	   Not that all that resulted was good, though.
	   He has acknowledged becoming addicted to cocaine in the '70s and
fighting weight and depression over the years. He got divorced, met
his second wife, Francine, and turned everything back around, only
to see it start to go sour again when two backup singers in Branson
accused him of sexual harassment this year.
	   A jury found him innocent after a trial in March, but Orlando
still sounds hurt and angry about it.
	   ``I no longer sign autographs `Love, Tony Orlando' _ on the
advice of my attorneys,'' he says, shaking his head in disgust.
	   Still, life has been good since moving to Branson, where the
54-year-old entertainer quickly became one of the town's most
visible stars.
	   He was profiled in the hour-long documentary ``Tony Orlando:
Behind the Music'' that debuted on the music channel VH1 on June
28. And after a request from Rhino Records to include a song in one
of its collections, he is looking into bringing out unreleased
recordings he made over the years.
	   ``For a guy who never saw high school,'' says Orlando, ``I've
walked the streets of Pompeii, entertained for six presidents now.
Had my own TV show, my own theater in Branson. Starred on Broadway.
... Who could have any regrets?''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-US-Tony Orlando; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
