<HEADER>
w2920 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-BroadwayRecordin     08-22 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Broadway Recordings,0806 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Remastering the sound of Broadway's Golden Age
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MICHAEL KUCHWARA &QC; 
 &UR; AP Drama Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The old vinyl discs most likely molder in
cardboard boxes or stand upright on a bottom shelf in your rec
room, basement or attic.
	   Their battered square covers potently recall some of Broadway's
biggest hits.
	   _A caricature of George Bernard Shaw manipulating a marionette
of Henry Higgins who, in turn, manipulates a marionette of Liza
Doolittle: ``My Fair Lady.''
	   _A line of nervous, eager dancers spread across a gray-brown
background and silver letters: ``A Chorus Line.''
	   _Quaint medieval drawings suggesting the King Arthur legend,
Guinevere and the Knights of the Round Table: ``Camelot.''
	   Decca may have begun the Broadway cast recording revolution with
``Oklahoma!'' in 1943, but Columbia, under its label of Columbia
Masterworks, expanded it even further, particularly after the
introduction of the long-playing record in the late 1940s. These
albums were among the LPs that introduced a generation to Broadway.
	   When compact discs replaced records in the mid-1980s, some of
recordings were released on CD, but they were not digitally
remastered using the latest state-of-the-art audio techniques.
	   Now a few of these classics have been. And not only has the
sound been improved, the company cannily includes bonus tracks of
material not available on the original albums.
	   The first five recordings by Sony Classical and Columbia/Legacy
Recordings _ ``My Fair Lady,'' ``A Chorus Line,'' ``Camelot,''
``Cabaret'' and ``Kiss Me, Kate'' _ are in U.S. stores.
	   Except for ``Kate,'' the original recordings were the work of
the legendary producer Goddard Lieberson.
	   ``Goddard had two goals _ to capture the show and to make it
perfectly playable and dramatically readable when you remove the
sets, lights and costumes,'' says Thomas Z. Shepard, one of the
producers who supervised the redoing of the discs. ``His recordings
had a wonderful way of standing on their own because they just
resonated drama.''
	   For Broadway buffs, these reissues resonate even more
effectively. They are a treasure trove of the familiar and the
obscure.
	   The original jacket covers remain intact. Yet in the case of
``Kiss Me, Kate'' it is a yellow-and-red cover that has not been
seen since the recording was first released in 1949.
	   Then there is that tantalizing additional material.
	   ``The average show LP was probably between 45 and 50 minutes;
pop ones were even shorter,'' Shepard says. ``Compact discs can get
nearly 75 minutes.''
	   ``Cabaret'' offers the most unusual treats _ four songs cut from
the original production, played and sung here by its composer, John
Kander, and its lyricist, Fred Ebb.
	   One of these forgotten songs, ``I Don't Care Much,'' made it
into the current hit Broadway revival of the show, but who could
hum the other three _ ``Roommates,'' ``Good Time Charlie'' and
``It'll All Blow Over'' until now?
	   For ``My Fair Lady,'' the producers mined an album made by
orchestra leader Percy Faith to find ``The Embassy Waltz,'' a bit
of music from the show that never was on the original album.
	   ``A Chorus Line'' offers an expanded version of ``Hello Twelve,
Hello Thirteen, Hello Love,'' nearly two more minutes of a song
that further defines the dancers at an audition for a big musical.
	   The original recording of Cole Porter's ``Kiss Me, Kate'' never
started with its overture. It began with the entr'acte, the music
heard just before the beginning of the second act.
	   Now things have been righted _ a bit. The original overture,
recorded in 1958 by veteran conductor Lehman Engel, has been added
to the CD, but at the end of the recording. And the entr'acte is
where it has always _ wrongly _ been because, according to the
liner notes, ``not to do so ``would be a denial of the album as it
has stood for the past 50 years.'' Only Lerner and Loewe's
``Camelot'' doesn't contain any bonus material, although the album
always contained two numbers that eventually were cut from the show
to pare its running time. Now the producers have placed the songs
back in their original playing order.
	   ``The songs had been put out of order so they would play better
on the LP,'' Shepard says. ``But there is a certain wonderful
darkness to `Camelot'. You leave the original sequence and the show
gets kind of sadder and sadder toward the end.''
	   Upcoming toward the end of September are a second set of
classics: ``South Pacific,'' ``West Side Story,'' ``The Sound of
Music,'' ``On the Town'' and ``Annie.''
	   ``Annie'' could include several unused numbers done by composer
Charles Strouse and lyricist Martin Charnin, plus an early, rare
recording by them of the musical's ubiquitous anthem ``Tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-Broadway Recordings; CT:i; 
