 &QC;  &QC;  &QC; APTV'S 0100 OUTLOOK FOR SUNDAY AUGUST 23, 1998 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the next 12
hours  &QC;  &QC; 
----
EXPECTED:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
US: Missiles - APTV is continuing to monitor events in Sudan,
Pakistan, U-S, and elsewhere for further possible reaction in the
wake of the U-S cruise missile attacks on Sudan and Afghanistan.
--------
INDONESIA: GRAVES -  APTV special report on investigations into
graves from remote sites thought to be the remains of dozens of
Islamic separatists killed by Indonesian troops. APTV travels with
forensic teams to the graves in the Aceh province of Indonesia.
(EXPECTED FIRST RUN EUROPE EARLY 0300GMT)
----
PAKISTAN: BHUTTO - An APTV report on embattled former Pakistani
Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and her husband whom a Swiss court has
declared should be indicted for alleged corruption. The report
includes latest comment from Bhutto. (EXPECTED FIRST RUN EUROPE
EARLY 0300GMT)
----
 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  APTV : DIANA SPECIAL ADVISORY MON AUG 24  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
-
As the anniversary of Princess Diana's death approaches APTV will
run a series of background features and special reports.
-
A special half-hour compilation will run from 0200 GMT MONDAY AUGUST
24. This will be repeated at 0600 / 1200 / 1800 GMT.
-
The Special will contain seven items:
Diana: Profile - a package of highlights from the last years of
Diana's life.
UK: Royal Family - how Princess Diana's death has affected the Royal
Family.
UK: Charles Media - the new relationship between Prince Charles and
the media.
France: Diana Inquiry - a fresh look at the inquiry into the car
crash in Paris.
France: Diana Doctor - an interview with the French doctor who was
the first on the scene of the crash.
UK: Rees-Jones - Trevor Rees-Jones, the bodyguard who survived the
car crash which killed Princess Diana, talks to APTV. (First run on
August 3 1998)
UK: Diana Books - a look at the books published to coincide with the
anniversary of the death of Princess Diana.

Other stories will be running on a daily basis in scheduled
b-u-l-l-e-t-i-ns. Please see regular Outlooks and Advisories for
details.
----
RUNNING:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
SUDAN: WRAP - APTV has the rally of thousands of Sudanese in
Khartoum demonstrating against the U-S missile attack including
vision of a demonstrator scaling the British Embassy flagpole to
tear down the Union Jack. Also includes soundbites from Sudan's
President rallying his people and condemning America for the attack.
(FIRST RUN EUROPE LATE 1500G/F-L-A-S-H 1415G and LATIN AMERICA
UPDATE 2130G)
----
US: SECURITY - Heightened security measures in the wake of U-S
military strikes on suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan and
Sudan have been put in place in the American capital.  APTV's
package  includes these security measures, Bill Clinton's address to
the nation, comments from White House press secretary Mike McCurry,
and pictures from Martha's Vineyard where Bill Clinton has returned
to resume his holidays. (FIRST RUN 1830 NORTH AMERICA UPDATE)
----
US: VIETNAM MASS - Basilica of National Shrine of the Immaculate
Conception hosts an estimated 5,000 Vietnamese Catholics from across
the U-S for the conclusion of 200th anniversary of Virgin Mary's
apparitions to persecuted Christians in La Vang forest, formerly
part of South Vietnam.  APTV has coverage. (FIRST RUN 1945 ASIA
PACIFIC EARLY)
----
BOLIVIA: ANNIVERSARY - Hundreds of protestors marked the 27th
anniversary of current president, Hugo Banzer's coup d'etat in 1971
and remembered those who disappeared during his dictatorship.  APTV
is covering. (FIRST RUN 1900 LATIN AMERICA)
----
DOM REP: CASTRO - APTV continues its coverage of the five day summit
of 15 Caribbean leaders underway in the Dominican capital, Santo
Domingo.  The coverage includes pictures of Cuban leader Fidel
Castro's attendance at the summit. (FIRST RUN 2130 LATIN AMERICA
UPDATE)
----
KOSOVO: FUNERAL -  As fighting continues in the southern regions of
Kosovo with causalities on both sides, APTV has pictures of the
funeral of 29 year old Avni Saci who was killed Friday by police in
an unclarified incident in Drenica.  Pictures also include Kosovo
Liberation Army soldiers toasting the memory of their fallen comrade
and saluting his grave site. (FIRST RUN 1830 NORTH AMERICA UPDATE)
----
JORDAN: OWNER - The owners of the Khartoum factory say they were
making tuberculosis medication, and not chemical weapons as the U-S
has claimed. Includes pictures of the bombed site. (FIRST RUN EUROPE
LATE 1500GMT PART NO ACCESS JORDAN)
----
LEBANON: REAX - Religious leaders in Lebanon used Friday prayer time
to attack the U-S for carrying out their air strikes. (FIRST RUN
EUROPE UPDATE 1130G)
----
PAKISTAN: 2 - The body of the U-N military observer,
Lieutenant-Colonel Carmine Calo, has been flown out of Kabul, amid
claims that he had been deliberately targeted. Pictures include the
coffin's arrival in Islamabad - accompanied by U-N personnel, today
pictures of American embassy staff leaving the capital, and hospital
scenes of the wounded from Thursday's air strike on Afghanistan.
(FIRST RUN EUROPE LATE 1500G/F-L-A-S-H 1415G)
----
CONGO: REBELS - Congolese rebels fighting to oust President Laurent
Kabila say they shot down two Zimbabwean jet fighters southwest of
Kinshasa as a warning. News of the jet attack came at the start of a
peace summit, organised by South African President Nelson Mandela in
Pretoria, to avert a deepening crisis in sub-Saharan Africa.
Includes soundbites from participants. (FIRST RUN F-L-A-S-H 1215G)
----
CONGO: MARINES - As fighting continues in the Democratic Republic of
Congo, British Royal Marines are preparing to help if any
evacuations of foreign citizens are needed.  APTV has pictures of
members of the 539 Squadron who have swapped the English Channel for
the Congo River, where they are practising with high speed boats
called ``Rigid Raiders.'' (First ran 1715 F-L-A-S-H)
----
WBANK: CLASHES - Israeli soldiers fired rubber bullets at around 60
Palestinian protesters on Saturday - in the second day of clashes on
the West Bank. (FIRST RUN EUROPE UPDATE 1130G)
----
RUSSIA: COMMUNISTS - Thousands of communist supporters gathered
today for a colourful march in Moscow against the current government
of President Boris Yeltsin. (FIRST RUN EUROPE LATE 1500G)
----
NIRELAND: MEMORIAL - Tens of thousands of people in Northern Ireland
and the Irish Republic fell silent on Saturday in memory of the 28
dead and 220 injured in the Omagh bombing. Includes coverage of a
the memorial Mass. (FIRST RUN EUROPE LATE 1500G) NO ACCESS UK
----
