<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-LPGA Rainbow Classic,0353 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rain forces postponement of second round
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MAPLE GROVE, Minnesota (AP) _ It took a late afternoon rainstorm
Saturday to keep Michelle Estill from building a commanding lead in
the LPGA Rainbow Classic.
	   Estill was at 9-under par through three holes of the second
round, and was lining up a birdie putt attempt on the fourth hole
of the Rush Creek Golf Course when the heavy rain chased nearly
half of the field to cover.
	   Sixty-six of the 138 golfers will return early Sunday morning to
finish the second round, then come back for the final 18 holes of
the dlrs 600,000 event.
	   Should further delays occur Sunday, the tournament would be
extended to Monday.
	   The weather forecast for Sunday was for partly cloudy skies with
a 20 percent chance of showers and thundershowers, mainly in the
morning hours. The predicted high temperature was in the mid-80's.
	   Estill, who is trying for her second career LPGA victory and
first in seven years, followed an opening-round 65 with birdies on
the first two holes of the second round to move to 9-under par. She
was standing on the fourth green when the rain came.
	   The only win on the LPGA tour for Estill came when she was a
rookie in 1991.
	   Wendy Ward, Nancy Harvey and Tracy Hanson were at 6-under par.
Ward finished seven holes and Harvey and Hanson four when play was
stopped.
	   Six others were on the course at 5-under par.
	   Mitzi Edge fired a 66 early Saturday to join Beth Daniel and
Gail Graham in the clubhouse at 3-under par. Graham shot 67 on
Saturday and Daniel a 69. Finishing the first two rounds at 2-under
par were Lori West, Cindy Figg-Currier, Jenny Lidback and Marilyn
Lovander.
	   The tournament is being held without many of the top players on
the LPGA tour. Only two of the top 10 money winners and eight of
the top 20 are entered. Among the absentees is South Korean rookie
Se Ri Pak, who has won two majors and four tour events this season.
She withdrew last week. The top European players, such as Annika
Sorenstam, are playing in the Compaq Open in Sweden.
</TEXT>
