w2991 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HurricaneBonnie 1stLd-Writethru   08-22 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hurricane Bonnie, 1st Ld-Writethru,0509 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hurricane Bonnie strengthens, could threaten eastern United States
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Bonnie strengthening, no immediate threat to
southern Florida; new coordinates. CORRECTS that direction is
west-northwest, sted north-northwest. At 11 p.m. (0300 GMT) Bonnie
was centered near latitude 23.6 north, longitude 71.5 west. &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Graphic &QL; 
 &UR; By JESSICA ROBERTSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) _ Hurricane Bonnie continued to strengthen
Sunday, becoming a 300-mile-long (480-kilometer-long) storm and
skirting sparsely populated Bahamian islands on a route that could
threaten the eastern United States.
	   Another hurricane gained power in the Pacific Ocean but was
expected to diminish over open seas Sunday.
	   At 11 p.m. Saturday (0300 GMT Sunday), the National Hurricane
Center said Bonnie's center was located about 195 miles (310
kilometers) east of San Salvador in the Bahamas.
	   Maximum sustained winds were estimated to have increased to near
95 mph (155 kph) and the hurricane was expected to grow stronger
Sunday, meteorologists said.
	   ``Bonnie could threaten the east coast of the United States
within the next few days,'' the National Hurricane Center said in a
statement. It said the likelihood of the hurricane hitting
southeast Florida has decreased. But it urged residents of the
coast and keys to be ready to ``take quick action'' if the
situation changed.
	   Jerry Jarrell, director of the center, said Bonnie could
eventually strengthen to a Category 3 storm with winds more than
111 mph (178 kph) capable of causing extensive damage.
	   Though the hurricane stalled for hours Saturday, it resumed its
west-northwest path after dark. Bonnie is expected to continue on
that course for about 24 hours before a gradual turn to the
northwest that could steer it from the U.S. mainland, the hurricane
center said. Bonnie was moving at about 9 mph (14 kph).
	   If it does hit the United State, north Florida is the most
likely target, Jarrell said.
	   Bahamian forecaster Basil Dean said the islands closest to the
hurricane would experience waves 6 to 9 feet (1.8-2.7 meters) above
normal, and Bonnie's storm surge and rain could cause flooding.
	   The islands' meteorological department said Bonnie would have
the greatest effect on San Salvador island, which could see five to
10 inches (13-25 centimeters) of rain, while more populated areas,
including the capital of Nassau, were unlikely to suffer as much.
	   Meanwhile, another weather system that threatened parts of Texas
lost power Saturday.
	   As it moved into Texas, Matagorda Island was hit the hardest
with 9 inches (23 centimeters) of rain and 70 mph (110 kph) wind
gusts early Saturday.
	   Also Friday, a storm in the Pacific Ocean reached hurricane
strength but remained far off the Mexican coast.
	   Hurricane Howard intensified Saturday, with winds of 110 mph
(176 kph). The hurricane center said it was expected to become
stronger before dissipating in the Pacific later Sunday. 	   
</TEXT>
