w1001 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Tennis-PilotPe     08-22 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Pilot Pen,0453 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ivanisevic, Kucera to meet in Pilot Pen finals
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs, CORRECTS scores in 11th graf &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By DONNA TOMMELLEO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW HAVEN, Connecticut (AP) _ His golf game will have to wait.
	   Nursing an aching shoulder made tender from years of countless
serves, admitted golf nut Goran Ivanisevic planned to forego 18
holes on the eve of his fourth U.S. singles final.
	   ``I just take it easy. I put more ice and a little massage and
play some cards instead of golf,'' he said after beating Yevgeny
Kafelnikov, 6-3, 6-4 Saturday in the Pilot Pen International
semifinal.
	   A strong service game helped the No. 8 seed Ivanisevic continue
his dominance over the Russian. He leads their head-to-head series
9-2 and has beaten Kafelnikov in their last seven matches.
	   His serve, clocked as high as 131 mph in the tournament, kept
him in control through most of the 1-hour, 5-minute match.
	   The left-hander had a dozen aces to Kafelnikov's four and won 87
percent of his first service points.
	   But the sore left shoulder also dictated that he take a little
off his serves and rely more on his volleys, the part of his game
he says has steadily improved.
	   ``Especially on hard court. I can come in, I can finish with a
volley ... I can stay back,'' Ivanisevic said.
	   If there was something missing off the serves, Kafelnikov, the
defending Pilot Pen champ and No. 5 seed, said he didn't notice.
	   ``It seemed like he was serving like in normal day, aces, one
after another,'' Kafelnikov said.
	   The 26-year-old Croat, ranked No. 16 on tour, is in the hunt for
his first tournament win in the United States and will play No. 7
seed Karol Kucera, of Slovakia, in Sunday's final. Kucera advanced
by beating No. 4 seed Richard Krajicek, 7-6 (8-6), 6-4 on the New
Haven hard courts.
	   Sunday's final will be Kucera's first on U.S. soil. Ranked 13th
in the world, Kucera opened the season with a singles title at
Sydney, his first hard court title.
	   Kucera said it took him nearly the first set to figure out the
hard-serving Dutchman, who topped the tournament with speeds of 132
mph. Krajicek had eight aces to Kucera's six.
	   ``After the second set I think I got a little bit more returns
back and I could break him two times,'' he said.
	   He had a chance to serve for the match at 5-4, but admitted
feeling the pressure and Krajicek broke him.
	   ``I am not used to win all my service games and I knew I have to
today because if I would lose the serve like in the second set and
Krajicek is coming back,'' he said.
	   He broke the Krajicek for the match when Krajicek's return
volley just missed the baseline.
</TEXT>
